<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Apologizes to Olympic Sponsors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- IOC vice president Dick Pound  
apologized to Sydney Games sponsors on Tuesday for any negative 
fallout because of the Salt Lake City bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	But Pound, who also heads the IOC marketing commission, defended  
recent reforms and stressed how much money the international body 
generates for local organizers such as the Sydney Organizing 
Committee for the Olympic Games. 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG is still about $90 million short of reaching its record  
marketing revenue target of about $550 million, but Pound said he 
believed the shortfall could be made up as the IOC recovered from 
the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten IOC members resigned or were dismissed because of the  
bribery disclosures involving Salt Lake City's successful bid for 
the Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people have asked how we let this happen in the first  
place. I think the simple answer is we took our eye off the ball,'' 
said Pound, who chaired the IOC's ad hoc Salt Lake commission of 
inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, it was a breach of trust on our part and we accept  
full responsibility for the conduct of our members.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian lawyer told a sponsors' workshop, ``We will try and  
make sure that it is temporary and demonstrate that your investment 
is one of the best marketing decisions you've ever made.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
