<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Lead In Baltimore Mayoral Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A white city councilman took an early lead in  
Tuesday's Democratic mayoral primary in Baltimore, a predominantly 
black city struggling with poor schools, a high drug-driven murder 
rate and a fleeing populace. 
</P>
<P>
	With 48 percent of precincts reporting, Martin O'Malley, who  
promised to clean the streets of open-air drug markets with a 
zero-tolerance policing strategy, had 27,042 votes, or 55 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Former City Councilman Carl Stokes had 13,085 votes, or 27  
percent, and City Council President Lawrence Bell had 8,170 votes 
or 17 percent of the vote. Both are black. 
</P>
<P>
	The three were among 17 Democrats running in the primary, the  
election to win in this city where Republicans are outnumbered 9 to 
1. There were six candidates in the GOP primary. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest poll showed Stokes and O'Malley in a statistical dead  
heat, with Bell not far behind. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since 1971, an incumbent was not on the  
ballot. Mayor Kurt Schmoke, the city's first elected black mayor, 
decided not to run for a fourth term. 
</P>
<P>
	The race was almost comic. Among the original list of candidates  
were six with arrest records and three who had filed for 
bankruptcy. Police arrested one candidate on burglary charges after 
recognizing her on TV. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell, the best-known candidate, was damaged by revelations of  
his personal financial troubles and by an incident in which his 
supporters disrupted an O'Malley event. 
</P>
<P>
	Stokes weathered revelations that he failed to pay taxes for  
several years and that his campaign literature falsely said he 
graduated from college. 
</P>
<P>
	Race is a key factor in Baltimore, where two out of three  
residents are black. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Malley has the support of prominent black state lawmakers, and  
Bell has been endorsed by the mostly white police union. 
</P>
<P>
	Will Jackson, who is black, was driving a van Tuesday plastered  
with O'Malley posters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've taken some flak from my friends,'' he said. ``This is the  
worst election I've seen in 25 years. It's been really divisive, 
and for no real reason other than, `Hey, we're black and let's keep 
it black.''' 
</P>
<P>
	On the eve of the primary, Schmoke said the city's estimated  
59,000 drug addicts -- and the crime they create -- are the next 
mayor's key problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they focus their attention like a laser beam on that issue,  
then we may see a significant turnaround,'' said Schmoke, who did 
not endorse any candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	But he criticized the zero-tolerance policing strategy that  
O'Malley has made a centerpiece of his campaign and which Bell also 
supports. Schmoke said it could give police license to be overly 
aggressive. 
</P>
<P>
	The general election is in November.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
