<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Fuming About U.S.-Russia Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican lawmakers are criticizing the  
Clinton administration's support for aid to Russia, as 
investigators widen their inquiry into allegations that Russian 
gangsters laundered billions of dollars through a major U.S. bank. 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, called the Clinton  
policy toward Russia ``the greatest U.S. foreign policy failure 
since Vietnam.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The unparalleled financial graft in Russia -- much of it  
apparently involving money from U.S. taxpayers -- marks the 
effective end of the Clinton-Gore administration's approach to 
Russian reform,'' Armey said Tuesday at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``The stated purpose of the Clinton-Gore policy was to help  
Russia become a peaceful and productive free-market democracy. 
Instead, Russia has become a looted and bankrupt zone of 
nuclearized anarchy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman David Leavy said Armey's remarks were  
irresponsible and ignored ``the events that have happened in Russia 
in the last 10 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has ``made important strides'' in promoting  
``Russia's transition toward a free-market democracy,'' Leavy said. 
He cited Russia's voluntary disabling of nuclear weapons and the 
rise of personal and press freedom and an independent judiciary. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has been put on the defensive by suspicions,  
arising from allegations of the money-laundering scheme using the 
Bank of New York, that International Monetary Fund loans and U.S. 
food aid to Russia may have been illegally diverted. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican criticism came as Russian investigators were in  
Washington meeting with State and Justice Department officials to 
discuss the money-laundering case and ways they can cooperate in 
their inquiries. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators and prosecutors in France, Austria and Switzerland  
also have taken actions recently related to the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, as the IMF's biggest member, has delayed  
deciding whether it should approve new loans to Russia from the 
international lending agency until a full accounting is made of the 
money already lent. The 182-nation IMF has lent Russia some $22 
billion since 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore is coming under fire from Republicans for  
his close relationship with Russian leaders and his hands-on role 
in U.S.-Russian diplomacy, particularly as chairman of a joint 
commission on bilateral ties with former Russian Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of a congressional GOP strategy, Rep. Benjamin Gilman,  
R-N.Y., chairman of the House International Relations Committee, 
announced that he would hold a series of hearings on U.S. policy 
toward Russia, including the bilateral commission headed by Gore 
and Chernomyrdin. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration's support for Russia ``has apparently gone  
hand in hand with a willing disregard for the high-level corruption 
within the (Russian) government,'' Gilman said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Banking Committee plans hearings next week on the  
alleged money-laundering scheme involving as much as $10 billion at 
the Bank of New York, the 15th-largest U.S. bank. The Senate 
Foreign Relations Committee also plans to hold hearings soon, with 
topics to include corruption in Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the House passed a measure, 419-0, aimed mainly at  
Russia that would impose sanctions on countries helping Iran 
develop nuclear, chemical or biological weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration said President Clinton's senior advisers  
would recommend he veto the bill because it would ``have the effect 
of undermining multilateral support that is vital to effectively 
fight proliferation.'' Clinton vetoed a similar bill last year. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
