<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 01:10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Courts Hispanic Community </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore made the most of his  
limited Spanish-speaking skills as he began a week of wooing 
Hispanic voters and showing off his rapport with them. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore addressed a gala for the National Hispanic Foundation for  
the Arts on Monday. Today, he was expected to launch his ``Ganamos 
con Gore,'' or, We Win with Gore, campaign with endorsements from 
dozens of Latino elected officials and community activists. The 
vice president also is scheduled to attend the Congressional 
Hispanic Caucus dinner on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	All the events are intended to show growing support among  
Hispanics for Gore's presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president sprinkled Spanish words and phrases during  
his speech to the National Hispanic Foundation for the Arts at a 
downtown hotel Monday night. He told the group he shared the 
organization's mission of reaching the day when ``our American 
culture fully reflects the full diversity of America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Hispanic American culture has already left an indelible stamp  
on our culture and on our society. The question is -- will we do 
more as a nation to recognize it and embrace it?'' he said to a 
crowd that included actors Jimmy Smits and Sonia Braga and singer 
Jon Secada. ``Will we swing open the doors of opportunity so more 
talented young Latinos and Latinas can achieve their full 
potential?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore deplored the lack of diversity in the mainstream media. He  
said Latinos made up only 3 1/2 percent of last year's movie and 
television roles -- and ``that's unacceptable to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The portrayal of Latinos in the media must be expanded because  
``children spend much more time -- much more time --in front of the 
television set than in the classroom,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Like the quality of our schools, the images we project into  
our living rooms and in our movie theaters send a powerful and 
unspoken message,'' he said. ``If they present only part of our 
society, then we risk giving the message to everybody else -- you 
don't have a place here, you don't have anything to contribute.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore attended the gala after spending the day in Tennessee,  
where he garnered support from union members at the state's AFL-CIO 
convention. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president, along with his leading Republican  
counterpart, George W. Bush, have taken advantage of what Spanish 
they know while campaigning for the White House. Both candidates 
have said their use of the language was intended to show respect 
for the Hispanic culture. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
