<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes Keeping Princeton Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Steve Forbes  
has criticized Princeton University for hiring a professor who says 
parents should be allowed to euthanize severely handicapped 
newborns. 
</P>
<P>
	But Forbes this week rejected entreaties from allies on the  
issue to cut ties to his alma mater and withhold charitable 
contributions unless the professor, Peter Singer, is removed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know how difficult it is to work for change from within a  
system and a culture that has rejected what we know is the first 
freedom, the freedom to be born and the right to life,'' Forbes 
wrote Monday to a group called Princeton Students Against 
Infanticide. 
</P>
<P>
	But he added: ``To withdraw from the system or the culture you  
are seeking to transform only marginalizes your voice.... I have 
credibility and standing, in part, precisely because I am a member 
of the Board of Trustees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Singer, widely considered the father of the international animal  
rights movement, began work in July as the Ira W. DeCamp 
Professorship of Bioethics at Princeton's Center for Human Values. 
</P>
<P>
	In his books, Singer has said that children less than one month  
old have no human consciousness and do not have the same rights as 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	Antiabortion groups, the disabled and others have fiercely  
opposed his Princeton appointment. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, a 1970 Princeton graduate, has made opposition to  
abortion a central tenet of his second campaign for the White 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, Forbes wrote to Princeton President Harold T. Shapiro  
that Singer's appointment ``sends a dangerous and debilitating 
message that anything goes, that there are no bounds when it comes 
to questions of life and death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- GOP presidential hopeful Gary Bauer attacked  
Texas Gov. George W. Bush's abortion stance Tuesday in a speech to 
the American Association of Christian Schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer said the GOP front-runner's refusal -- if elected -- to  
impose an antiabortion litmus test on Supreme Court nominees would 
undermine the possibility of reversing Roe vs. Wade during the next 
presidential administration. 
</P>
<P>
	With several Supreme Court justices about to retire, Bauer said,  
the next president could appoint justices who would rapidly reverse 
the nation's abortion law. He criticized fellow Republican 
candidates -- Bush and former American Red Cross president Elizabeth 
Dole among them -- who have said they personally oppose abortion but 
do not believe the nation is ready to reverse abortion rights law. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the next three years you could wake up and the headline  
could be, 'Court overturns Roe; finds right to life,''' Bauer said. 
``It is that close to our grasp.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer said Bush's father, former President Bush, did not ask his  
nominees enough questions about policy positions, and that ended up 
costing conservatives a guaranteed vote on the court. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is how we got stuck with David Souter -- his Dad's  
appointee -- who is a reliable vote for Clinton-Gore,'' said Bauer. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hurricane Floyd forced Texas Gov. George W.  
Bush on Tuesday to postpone a presidential campaign swing through 
South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the Wednesday events postponed were a defense policy  
speech at The Citadel in Charleston, S.C., an appearance in 
Columbia, S.C., and a fund-raising event in Charleston, W.Va. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush picked up yet  
another endorsement Tuesday -- the latest from the California Young 
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	The California Young Republicans have 5,000 members, ages 18 to  
40. The group is affiliated with the National Young Republicans and 
has been involved with GOP politics for more than 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Associated Press writers Laurence Arnold and Douglas Kiker  
contributed to this report. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
