<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retirees Settle Buyout Suit vs. IBM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- About 340 former employees of IBM's  
Lexington plant will receive $15.5 million to settle a lawsuit 
alleging the company misled them about an early retirement program. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement, approved in federal court in Lexington on  
Monday, will include some lump-sum payments of past-due benefits to 
retirees. The rest of the settlement will be added to future 
benefit payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Former workers will receive anywhere from $2,000 to $150,000,  
depending on their age, salary, length of service and the date of 
their retirement, said plaintiffs' lawyer Ken Hall of the 
Louisville firm of Middleton &AMP; Reutlinger. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement comes amid another benefit controversy at IBM.  
The Armonk, N.Y.-based company is one of more than 300 companies 
that have recently converted to new cash-balance pension plans, 
which can reduce costs by cutting future benefits to middle-aged 
workers while allowing younger workers to take a larger payout if 
they depart before retiring. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say that the plans violate age-discrimination laws.  
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission Chairwoman Ida Castro said 
Tuesday the commission will review the plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1992 suit stemmed from IBM's 1990 sale of its  
Lexington-based information services division, which later became 
Lexmark International Inc., a manufacturer of computer printers and 
their components. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to trim its work force, IBM offered a package of  
incentives to employees who wanted to retire by the end of 1990. 
The suit alleged that the company told workers that there would be 
no financial advantage to extending their length of service with 
IBM by taking leaves of absence prior to retiring. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than a month after those early retirements took effect, the  
suit contended, IBM amended its retirement plan to offer enhanced 
benefits that were not available to those who had already retired -- 
and which would have been available had the retirees taken leaves 
of absence. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall said information exchanged during litigation of the suit  
showed IBM officials contemplated enhancing the retirement benefits 
as early as October 1990, but did not inform the workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Former IBM worker Don Adams of Lexington, who will share in the  
settlement, said he is glad to finally have the suit settled. 
</P>
<P>
	Adams, now 61, worked for IBM for 33 years and 11 months and was  
the superintendent of an assembly area when he took early 
retirement at the end of 1990. He said he would not have retired if 
he had known he could take a one-month leave of absence and qualify 
for improved benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Adams declined to discuss how much he will receive from the  
settlement, but said he does not harbor ill will toward his former 
employer. ``I just feel like there was some people there that made 
some bad decisions,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Adams said he thought the case was lost in 1996, when U.S.  
District Judge Karl Forester in Lexington granted a summary 
judgment to IBM. That ruling was overturned in January by the 6th 
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Cincinnati, which said that an 
employer who considers changes to a retirement plan has an 
obligation to make retirees aware of those possible changes. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6th Circuit ruling prompted IBM to negotiate the settlement.  
</P>
<P>
	``The case had been in the courts for many years and we thought  
that rather than litigate, it would be prudent for us to settle on 
terms that we thought were reasonable, given how old the case 
was,'' IBM spokeswoman Jana Weatherbee said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall said the $15.5 million settlement amounts to 87.5 percent  
of the amount the plaintiffs sought when they filed the 
class-action suit. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the settlement, IBM also agreed to drop its appeal of  
the 6th Circuit ruling to the U.S. Supreme Court, Hall said. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
