<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dems To Blame GOP for Tax Cut Veto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After President Clinton vetoes the  
Republicans' $792 billion tax cut, the Democrats are going to blame 
them for the lack of any break for taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	Or try.  
</P>
<P>
	That backspin argument from the Democrats will be the next phase  
of the maneuvering over tax cuts, with Clinton waiting to veto the 
GOP bill he calls excessive, a risk to vital programs, the surplus 
and the economy itself. The Senate Republican leader now says 
that's it, no fallback compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton says he's for ``sensible tax cuts,'' less than half the  
size of the GOP measure, and designed to benefit lower and middle 
income Americans. The administration is willing to bargain up to 
$300 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	In each case, that would be over 10 years, and taxpayers  
wouldn't see any big breaks immediately under either version. 
</P>
<P>
	There's always the possibility of compromise, but Clinton balked  
earlier at a $500 billion cut, which had some Democratic support, a 
fallback GOP tax cut advocates weren't buying anyhow. 
</P>
<P>
	So it's the veto, perhaps later this week, Republican leaders  
having held the bill since it passed on Aug. 5 so that Clinton 
wouldn't be able to reject it while Congress was in its summer 
recess and he had the stage to himself. Besides, the Republicans 
said they'd spend the late summer building taxpayer support for 
their tax cut to put more pressure on Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	But after a month of trying, the polls still put tax cuts far  
down the list of voter concerns, and showed more people more 
interested in reducing the national debt. When the question is put 
as Republicans put it, lower taxes or increased spending, 
majorities prefer tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	So that is the GOP argument, as it has been all along.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's is that the GOP bill would irresponsibly risk vital  
programs, costing revenues needed for Medicare and the long-term 
financing of Social Security, and eventually swallowing the 
surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	The president said he is open to negotiations, and that if the  
Republicans won't work on compromise, it will prove that their real 
motive is not a tax cut but an issue for the 2000 campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	There will have to be at least one tax bill this year, to renew  
provisions that expired on June 30, and that could become a vehicle 
for attempts at a broader measure. 
</P>
<P>
	But that would require bargaining for compromise, and while Sen.  
Trent Lott, the GOP leader, said he'll never give up on a tax cut, 
he sounds as though he has for 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	In the weekly radio address Republicans had been using to  
promote their tax cut, Lott said there won't be one. ``No tax cut 
this year because as far as Mr. Clinton is concerned, your refund 
is already spent here in Washington,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democrats counter that there can be a cut, but only with  
compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	The minority leaders, Rep. Richard A. Gephardt and Sen. Tom  
Daschle, said the Republicans' summer tax campaign showed that the 
voters don't want the GOP bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe instead of the partisan back and forth that we've had  
all summer long, we ought to sit down and see if we can find places 
where we do agree,'' White House chief of staff John Podesta said 
on CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott had a different description.  
</P>
<P>
	``If our past experience with this administration is any guide,  
in a few weeks ... President Clinton will want to make a deal,'' he 
said. ``He will agree to some throwaway tax fixes in return for a 
massive hike in spending for all his pet projects. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be impolite to call that blackmail, but we've been  
through this routine before, and we know where it ends up,'' Lott 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	His problem is that it has ended up to Clinton's advantage. He's  
used his veto power, and the threat of it, more effectively than 
the Republicans have used their majorities in the House and Senate. 
That's how he won spending for his priorities as the price of a 
budget deal in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Clinton's vetoes of Republican-drawn appropriations  
bills led to the shutdown of federal agencies for lack of money, 
saying they'd forced him to it. GOP leaders defied his veto 
warnings, figuring he'd be blamed for the mess. Instead, they were. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the hand the Democrats hope they can play again on tax  
cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
