<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Globe Changes Publishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Boston Globe will begin publishing an early  
Sunday edition next month in an effort to stem shrinking 
circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	Available at stores on Saturdays starting Oct. 23, the early  
Sunday edition will contain features and non-breaking news from the 
regular Sunday edition, as well as supplemental sections such as 
the Help Wanted, Real Estate, TV Week and Parade Magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to increase Sunday circulation by giving consumers  
more time on the weekend to spend with the Sunday Globe,'' said 
Boston Globe Publisher Richard H. Gilman in a statement. ``It's 
another way we're trying to meet the changing needs of our 
readers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday circulation has been declining in recent years at many  
major metropolitan newspapers, including The Globe, a wholly-owned 
subsidiary of The New York Times Company. The Globe's latest 
circulation figures, for the six-month period ending March 1999, 
put Sunday circulation at 730,420, a decrease of 2.4 percent 
compared to the same period a year before. 
</P>
<P>
	Early editions have been published successfully in such markets  
as Chicago, San Francisco, Philadelphia, Miami, Los Angeles, 
Dallas-Fort Worth and New York. Early edition sales in those 
markets range from a few thousand to more than a hundred thousand. 
</P>
<P>
	The Globe's early Sunday edition would be delivered to stores  
between 9 a.m. and 2 p.m. on Saturdays. The initial press run is 
expected to be nearly 40,000 copies. 
</P>
<P>
	Home delivery subscribers, which account for 60 percent of  
Sunday Globe circulation, will be unaffected and will continue to 
receive the latest edition on Sunday morning. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 17:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lie Detector Use Opposed at Labs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIVERMORE, Calif. (AP) -- More than a dozen scientists at one of  
the nation's top nuclear weapons labs on Tuesday spoke against the 
government's plan to require top-security researchers to take lie 
detector tests in an effort to catch spies. 
</P>
<P>
	Angry researchers at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory  
criticized the idea that polygraph tests were needed and questioned 
their accuracy. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're coming here to threaten our honor and integrity, to  
require us on effective threat to our employment to volunteer for 
an even deeper intrusion to our right to privacy,'' said David 
Dearborn, a lab scientist. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Douglass E. Post, a lab physicist, warned that the tests  
will make it even harder to recruit and retain talented scientists, 
since the private sector does not require them and offers higher 
salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, the Energy Department announced plans to give polygraph  
tests to some 5,000 workers in sensitive nuclear weapons jobs, part 
of a broad initiative to beef up security after widely publicized 
accusations of leaks to the Chinese. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers will be asked if they have committed espionage,  
committed sabotage or terrorism, illegally disclosed classified 
information, and if they had any unauthorized contact with any 
foreign intelligence service. 
</P>
<P>
	If any of the four answers raises a red flag, the person tested  
would have to take a more complex test and then be the subject of 
an FBI investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Some lab workers objected to the polygraph testing, fearing that  
errors might incriminate innocent people. 
</P>
<P>
	A panel of four members heard the testimony. The panel will also  
hold hearings in Albuquerque, N.M., Los Alamos, N.M., and in 
Washington. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
