<DOCNO> APW19990914.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 07:40:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smithsonian Names New Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawrence M. Small, a leading figure in the  
financial world, is taking over leadership of the 16 museums of the 
Smithsonian Institution and the National Zoo. 
</P>
<P>
	Small, 58, was named Monday as the 11th secretary of the  
Smithsonian in January. He is leaving his job as president of 
Fannie Mae, one of the principal U.S. home mortgage financing 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Smithsonian, founded in 1846, runs the national museums of  
American History, American Art, Natural History, Air and Space and 
others in the capital. It employs 6,400 people and annually hosts 
more than 30 million visitors at its 17 facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Small will succeed I. Michael Heyman, 69, a former law professor  
and university chancellor, who is retiring. 
</P>
<P>
	Small, who studied Spanish literature at Brown University and  
the flamenco guitar in Spain, is a longtime collector of art from 
the rain forests of South America and Africa. He has served on the 
boards of the Joffrey Ballet, the National Building Museum and on 
the council of the U.S. Holocaust Memorial, and he was treasurer of 
Morehouse College, a historically black college in Atlanta. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 07:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philly Gets Arena Football Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Ron Jaworski, a 17-year NFL veteran, is part of  
an investment group that purchased an Arena Football League 
expansion team Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jaworski, who quarterbacked the Philadelphia Eagles to the 1981  
Super Bowl and now is a sportscaster for ESPN, is joined by former 
Arena League commissioner Jim Drucker, and Craig Stein, owner of 
the Double-A Reading Phillies baseball club. 
</P>
<P>
	The location for the league's 19th team, which will begin play  
no later than the 2002 season, has not been determined, AFL 
commissioner David Baker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Arena Football recently awarded expansion teams to Los Angeles  
and Raleigh, N.C., for next season, and Chicago for 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jaworski, Drucker, Stein and their partners are another  
ownership `Dream Team' for the Arena Football League,'' Baker said. 
``Ron brings a vast knowledge of pro football to Arena Football, 
and he's highly respected by NFL owners, coaches and players. Jim 
Drucker was AFL commissioner for three seasons and was commissioner 
of the CBA for eight years and has a successful track record with 
growing national leagues. Craig Stein brings experienced team 
ownership to the AFL.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Drucker, AFL commissioner from 1994-96, said his group evaluated  
17 potential areas before narrowing the list to ``five top 
cities.'' Three of those cities are Philadelphia, Washington and 
Salt Lake City. He hopes to announce a decision on the site of the 
franchise by March 15. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 07:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FTC Warnings for Credit Cardholders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Federal Trade Commission guidelines warn credit cardholders to  
be wary of those promoting protection plans who: 
</P>
<P>
	--Say you are liable for more than $50 of unauthorized charges on  
your credit card account. 
</P>
<P>
	--Say you need credit card loss protection because computer  
hackers can access your credit card number and charge thousands of 
dollars to your account. 
</P>
<P>
	--Say that the Y2K computer bug will make it easy for thieves to  
place unauthorized charges on your credit card account. 
</P>
<P>
	--Say or imply that they are calling from ``the security  
department'' and want to activate the protection features on your 
new card. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC also advises consumers not to give out personal  
information -- including credit card or bank account numbers -- 
unless they have initiated contact or are very familiar with the 
business involved. People who find unauthorized charges on credit 
cards should call the issuers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 07:52:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Emmy Voters Gunshy on 'Sopranos' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The Sopranos'' may have been the critical  
darling of the Emmys, but the mafia drama faced enough hurdles to 
fill the trunk of a mobster's car by the time the ceremony rolled 
around. 
</P>
<P>
	The HBO series about a New Jersey crime family led the field  
with 16 nominations yet came away with just four Emmys, two at the 
Sunday awards show and two technical awards given earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first cable program nominated for best dramatic  
series, but lost to last year's winner, ABC's legal drama ``The 
Practice.'' David E. Kelley, creator of ``The Practice,'' also went 
home with the award for best comedy series, ``Ally McBeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Sopranos'' went into the awards with great reviews and  
hardcore fans among HBO subscribers. But its dark tone and cast of 
unsavory characters may not have played well with television 
academy voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``What drives the shows that win Emmys is sentiment,'' said  
Thomas O'Neil, author of ``The Emmys.'' ``The thing that makes 'The 
Sopranos' work so well is cynicism, not sentiment, while David E. 
Kelley is a master of sentiment and impacting voters and grabbing 
hold of voters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Emmy voters generally look for characters and situations they  
can relate to, and a mob drama laced with graphic violence and 
profanity doesn't quite fit the bill, O'Neil said. 
</P>
<P>
	David Chase, creator and producer of ``The Sopranos,'' said  
Monday the show ``does flaunt some pretty basic rules about 
television, like the likeability factor. I don't know that our 
characters are very huggable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The series had five acting nominations, yet won just one -- for  
the most upright ``Sopranos'' character. Edie Falco, who plays a 
soul-searching mob wife, took home the award for best actress in a 
drama series. 
</P>
<P>
	``Emmy voters in general want to like who they're voting for,''  
O'Neil said. ``Look who did win. Edie Falco, the woman who is the 
moral center of that series, the moral center of that immoral 
world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other major award ``The Sopranos'' won Sunday was for  
dramatic writing, a category the series dominated with four of the 
five nominations. 
</P>
<P>
	Voters who pick Emmy winners also tend to gravitate more toward  
the familiar and traditional. The three other drama nominees, 
``NYPD Blue,'' ``ER'' and ``Law &AMP; Order,'' all have been perpetual 
nominees, and each has won the dramatic series award in past years. 
</P>
<P>
	Veteran series also dominated the acting awards, with such  
perennial winners as Dennis Franz of ``NYPD Blue'' and Helen Hunt 
of ``Mad About You'' going home with more awards. 
</P>
<P>
	``The television academy membership does tend to be reasonably  
conservative in terms of embracing new media,'' said Gerald 
Isenberg, a former producer who is a film and television professor 
at the University of Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Albrecht, HBO president of original programming, said  
there may have been some backlash against ``The Sopranos'' because 
of the wide press coverage the show had gained. The explicit 
violence, language and sex also may have worked against the series, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``More than likely there are people who are offended by some of  
that content when they're in the voting room,'' Albrecht said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet even ``The Practice'' creator Kelley conceded afterward that  
he had gone into the Emmys with a hunch ``The Sopranos'' would win 
best drama. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's such a terrific show,'' Kelley said. ``I don't think  
it's one that approximates anything that I've seen before on 
television or anything that I've done before.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 07:51:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Morning Off-Hours Trading Offered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The race to bring off-hours stock trading to  
regular investors is about to stretch from the late afternoon and 
evening to the morning before most markets open. 
</P>
<P>
	Island ECN, an electronic exchange owned by Web broker Datek  
Online, said Monday it will expand its late-afternoon session to 
four hours and introduce a new mini-session before the traditional 
9:30 a.m. start of trading on the New York Stock Exchange and 
Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	The expanded schedule -- from 8 a.m. to 9:30 a.m. and from 4 p.m.  
to 8 p.m. -- will begin Wednesday through smaller broker-dealers, 
but no major broker is set to offer the Island service yet. A Datek 
spokesman said the firm expects to introduce morning and evening 
trading soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, individual investors are expected to gain  
round-the-clock access to the after-hours market, which until 
recently was open only to major money managers. And like most 
things Internet-related, the mainstreaming of that market has been 
quicker than anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	Island and Datek broke the after-hours barrier in late July when  
they launched a mini-session from 4 p.m. to 5:15 p.m., prompting a 
stream of announcements by the likes of ETrade Group, Instinet, 
Charles Schwab, Fidelity Investments and America Online. 
</P>
<P>
	In late August, Discover Brokerage and Dreyfus Brokerage  
Services introduced the first real evening session, from 6 p.m. to 
8 p.m., through a new electronic exchange named MarketXT. 
</P>
<P>
	Island's new schedule goes a step farther by offering four  
continuous hours of late trading rather than shutting down for two 
hours after the normal 4 p.m. close of traditional markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Many online investors have shown an interest in making portfolio  
decisions at home, where they have more privacy and time to think. 
An estimated 20 percent to 25 percent of online trades are 
currently placed outside normal hours, and then executed when 
regular trading resumes in the morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Some investment experts worry that after-hours trading will  
expose individual investors to sharp price swings if there isn't 
sufficient demand to buy or sell a stock. 
</P>
<P>
	For that reason, many of the first after-hours services are  
limiting trading to only major companies and requiring investors to 
specify the highest price they're willing to pay when buying a 
stock or the least they're willing to take when selling. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 10:32:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fergie New 'Today' Show Reporter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The ``Today'' show has a new royal reporter: the  
Duchess of York. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Sarah Ferguson has been hired as a London-based  
correspondent for the top-rated morning news show. She'll 
contribute human interest stories, features and interviews, NBC 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``From the first time she appeared on `Today,' Sarah struck me  
as someone with a natural ease in front of the camera and the 
ability to tell a good story -- two key components in the job of a 
television correspondent,'' said ``Today'' executive producer Jeff 
Zucker. 
</P>
<P>
	The duchess, the ex-wife of Prince Andrew, said she will  
contribute about one report a month to the show. She's interested 
in reporting, for example, on health and weight issues and how 
children have coped with the war in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have always for a long time wanted to be in television,''  
she said in a telephone interview. ``There's no better place to 
gain experience than to work with Katie (Couric) and Matt 
(Lauer).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, she was host of a talk show on a British television  
network. The show, ``Sarah ... Surviving Life,'' ran for 10 
episodes and she's considering other TV work over there. 
</P>
<P>
	On her first show there, Fergie, as she is popularly known in  
Britain, sat on a couch and discussed life's crises with guests who 
included a woman raped by a serial killer and a hit-and-run driver 
who had confessed 20 years later. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the first time I really felt comfortable with my job,''  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today'' dominates the ratings for morning news shows, but is  
facing energized new competition this fall from ABC and CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	It isn't the first time ``Today'' hired a British notable:  
Princess Diana's brother, Charles, was a reporter for the show for 
a time a decade ago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
