<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Clears Fields for Floyd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Navy ships headed out to sea and  
military aircraft were flown to the safety of airfields inland 
Tuesday as Hurricane Floyd took aim at the Southeast coast from 
Florida to the Carolinas. 
</P>
<P>
	The USS John F. Kennedy, an aircraft carrier with about 5,000  
aboard, and the RFA Gold Rover, a visiting British ship, sailed 
from Mayport Naval Station near Jacksonville early Tuesday to join 
12 other Navy ships that left port Monday to ride the storm out at 
sea. 
</P>
<P>
	About 10,000 airmen, family members and civilian contractors at  
Patrick Air Force Base and Cape Canaveral Air Force Station in 
Florida coast were ordered out, as were about 1,000 sailors and 
their families at Mayport. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marine boot camp at Parris Island, S.C., was preparing  
school buses to move 7,000 recruits to shelter inland. 
</P>
<P>
	Navy and Air Force installations in Florida and the Carolinas  
also began flying helicopters, air tankers, cargo planes and 
fighter jets out of Floyd's path, positioning them at bases from 
Maine to Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	The affected installations also included Tampa's MacDill Air  
Force Base and Jacksonville Naval Air Station in Florida; Seymour 
Johnson Air Force Base near Goldsboro, N.C.; and Shaw Air Force 
Base in Sumter, S.C. 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida National Guard went on alert to help secure damaged  
areas and provide other assistance. By Tuesday morning, 990 Guard 
members in southern and central Florida had been told to report to 
their armories. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
