<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish Movies Showcased in Toronto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- When Ramiro Puerta, an official for the Toronto  
film festival, first thought of a series on new Spanish movies he 
assumed Pedro Almodovar's latest would be included. The deal fell 
through, and Puerta insists he isn't sorry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, part of the purpose of this series is to show that  
Spanish movies can hold their own even without Almodovar,'' Puerta, 
the festival's international programmer, said Monday. ``Spanish 
cinema is bursting at the seams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Almodovar is not only among the world's most famous directors,  
but probably the only living foreign-language filmmaker whose name 
alone can sell a movie in the United States. His upcoming release, 
``All About My Mother,'' won the prize at Cannes for best director 
and will open the New York Film Festival. 
</P>
<P>
	But Spain is home to a variety of talented directors. Their work  
ranges from the meditative style of Carlos Saura to the comedy of 
Fernando Colomo to the social realism of Benito Zambrano. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was young, the idea of going to a Spanish movie never  
crossed my mind,'' said Fernando Trueba, born in 1955 and director 
of the Academy Award-winning ``Belle Epoque.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But young people now are not ashamed. A lot of things have  
changed. For all the problems we've had our quality of life has 
changed for the better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three generations of Spanish directors are represented at the  
10-day Toronto International Film Festival, which ends Saturday. 
Saura, a three-time nominee for the Academy Award, has been making 
movies since the 1950s, when Gen. Francisco Franco was in power. 
Trueba began working not long after Franco died in 1975. Benito 
Zambrano, born in 1965, has just completed his first feature, 
``Alone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some directors who barely know who Franco is,'' said  
Saura, whose films include ``Carmen,'' ``Tango'' and his new 
feature, ``Goya in Bordeaux,'' which imagines the painter's final 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Spanish filmmakers have been acclaimed internationally  
at least since the 1920s, when Luis Bunuel emerged, modern Spanish 
cinema essentially took off after Franco's death. For American 
art-house audiences, Almodovar films such as ``Law of Desire'' and 
``Women on the Verge of a Nervous Breakdown'' defined the 
uninhibited style of post-Franco Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	``His coattails have been very strong in the United States.  
Almodovar opened the door for a lot of Spanish filmmakers,'' said 
Jason Blum, co-head of the acquisitions department of Miramax 
Films, the U.S. distributor for Almodovar's ``Time Me Up! Tie Me 
Down!'' and other Spanish movies. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the Spanish films began the festival with deals for the  
U.S., but Puerta said there has been strong interest in at least 
three: ``Goya in Bordeaux,'' Trueba's ``The Girl of Your Dreams'' 
and Manuel Gomez Pereira's ``Between Your Legs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trueba's film, winner in seven categories of Spain's Goya award,  
is set during the Spanish Civil War and tells the story of a 
pro-Franco production company at the UFA studios in Nazi Germany. 
For one onlooker, according to Trueba, the film proved much too 
vivid. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was an old man on the set and he was in a panic. He was  
an electrician back in the '30s and he had met Joseph Goebbels a 
few times,'' Trueba said. ``And when he saw our actor dressed as 
Goebbels and talking like him, he was shocked. He thought Goebbels 
had come back from the dead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Almodovar fans should love ``Between Your Legs,'' especially the  
opening sequence: A doctor arrives home from work. His wife is 
away, his daughter asleep. His only company is the housekeeper, the 
beautiful housekeeper. 
</P>
<P>
	Within minutes, the two are on the couch, screaming with  
pleasure. In a flash, they're screaming with pain. The daughter 
stands over them. She's holding a knife. She's using the knife. 
</P>
<P>
	Cut to a closeup of the doctor, years later, confessing his sad  
story. His family has left him, his career is in ruins. The camera 
pulls back. He's addressing an audience, and not just any audience, 
but the Association of Sex Addicts Anonymous. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the listeners are a handsome man and an attractive woman.  
</P>
<P>
	Before long, their eyes meet.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
