<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Tech Waits for Ricky's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) -- Both Ricky Williams are nursing leg  
injuries and their status for next weekend is doubtful. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's Heisman Trophy winner from Texas hurt his ankle in  
his NFL debut last weekend. And Texas Tech's Ricky Williams had to 
miss last week's 38-17 victory over Louisiana-Lafayette because of 
a sprained left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Complicating matters for Tech coach Spike Dykes is that his  
Williams isn't around to have his leg tested. He's been in Dallas 
since Sunday with his ailing mother and hasn't undergone a medical 
exam since last week. 
</P>
<P>
	As of late Tuesday, the team was uncertain when or if he will  
play again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm no doctor, so I don't like to step out on a limb and try  
to say whether I think he is going to come back or when,'' Dykes 
said. ``We have to let the doctors look at him and until he gets 
back from Dallas, we don't know when that's going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams had played every game at Tech (1-1) the past two  
seasons, rushing for 1,582 yards and 13 touchdowns last year. He 
also was on pace to eclipse the career rushing record set last year 
at Texas by the other Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Tech's Williams injured his knee in the first half of the opener  
against Arizona State. The prospect of playing without him has the 
team worried. 
</P>
<P>
	``You always wish you had your best option available and on the  
field,'' quarterback Rob Peters said. ``We don't know for sure what 
we are capable of without him. But we've got to play football and 
win, not worry about people who aren't on the field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tech managed a convincing victory without Williams last weekend.  
</P>
<P>
	James Easterling rushed for 114 yards and two touchdowns against  
Louisiana-Lafayette, formerly Southwestern Louisiana, and Peters 
threw for two TDs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
