<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 09:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Speaks At Amtrak Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A railroad signals expert testified today he  
found no evidence that a crossing gate hit a steel-loaded truck 
that drove into the path of an Amtrak train, setting off a crash 
that killed 11 passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	The testimony of John Sharkey, a communications and signals  
general manager for Canadian National-Illinois Central Railroad, 
contradicted a witness who told of watching the descending gate hit 
the truck as it tried to beat the train across the tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharkey's account came on the second of three days of public  
hearings called by the National Transportation Safety Board to seek 
clues in the March 15 crash of the City of New Orleans train near 
Bourbonnais, about 50 miles south of Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the 11 deaths, 122 people were injured.  
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Luis A. Nieves, who claims he was driving the second  
of two cars stopped behind John R. Stokes' tractor-trailer, told 
board members through an interpreter that he saw he saw a crossing 
gate strike Stokes' truck as he attempted to drive it around the 
barrier, shortly before it was struck in the rear by the train. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sharkey said today that he investigated the crossing gate at  
the crash site and saw no markings indicating it hit the truck. 
</P>
<P>
	And truck driver Aubrey Fosburgh -- who was picking up cargo  
about 75 to 100 yards from the crash site -- said Monday the 
crossing gate was up when Stokes crossed the railroad, adding that 
he ``never (saw) the gate down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also described the ball of flame that shot into the air  
shortly after the crash. ``It was a mess,'' Fosburgh said, who 
rushed to the scene to help passengers escape a mangled train car. 
</P>
<P>
	The conflicting accounts did little to clear up two key  
questions: Was Stokes trying to drive his fully loaded truck around 
the railroad's crossing gates and beat the oncoming locomotive? Or 
did the crossing's warning signals activate too late -- or not at 
all -- leaving him unaware that the train was rumbling toward him at 
79 mph? 
</P>
<P>
	Following the conflicting testimony Monday, George Black, the  
NTSB member who is chairing the hearing said , ``I don't know that 
there's anything that is clear one way or another as a result of 
today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Black said the NTSB probably won't make any final determinations  
until March. 
</P>
<P>
	Stokes, who was not hurt in the crash, refused to testify  
Monday. He told authorities after the crash that he didn't see the 
train approaching, and claimed the crossing's warning bells, lights 
and gates activated after he was on the tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	In other testimony Monday, train engineer Angel Flores said he  
sounded the whistle and activated the emergency braking system as 
the train neared the truck, but said he didn't remember whether 
lights at the crossing were flashing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 14:00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Post-Elway Era Off to Rough Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The powerful offense looked ordinary. The  
risk-taking defense looked vulnerable. The usually reliable special 
teams? Don't even go there. 
</P>
<P>
	After one game, it's clear that life is going to be more  
difficult for the Denver Broncos without longtime leader John 
Elway. 
</P>
<P>
	``We let everyone down,'' linebacker Bill Romanowski said after  
Denver's season-opening 38-21 loss to the Miami Dolphins. ``We 
weren't playing for John Elway. He won't be forgotten, but he's not 
playing anymore. We have to play for everyone in this locker 
room.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even Elway, who engineered 47 game-winning or game-tying  
fourth-quarter drives in 16 seasons, would have been hard-pressed 
to make the Broncos look like two-time defending Super Bowl 
champions Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	His successor, second-year pro Brian Griese, was serviceable,  
but Denver repeatedly broke down defensively and had big problems 
with its kicking game. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Elam, one of the NFL's most consistent kickers the past  
five seasons, had a field goal blocked and missed a 41-yard attempt 
that would have pulled Denver within two scores in the fourth 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Miami blocked a punt and averted trouble when the  
Broncos failed to pounce on a muffed punt by Terrell Buckley in the 
first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The resulting debacle -- Denver's worst home loss in five seasons  
under coach Mike Shanahan -- left many Broncos players stunned. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what happened,'' defensive end Harald Hasselbach  
said. ``We felt great before the game. The atmosphere was great. 
Then, I just don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Broncos weren't lacking motivation. They were playing on the  
night Denver retired Elway's jersey and inducted him into the 
team's Ring of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver also was trying to preserve its streak of 24 straight  
regular-season home wins. As it turns out, the Broncos fell three 
games short of the NFL record held by Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	So much for any remaining air of invincibility.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's no sense of doubt,'' said fullback Howard Griffith,  
``but we can't just show up at home and think that's going to do 
it. We have to take a good hard look at ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Broncos have a short week to prepare for Sunday's game at  
Kansas City, and Shanahan is confident Denver will recover from the 
Miami loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quite frankly, I expect our team to play at a higher level,''  
he said. ``I believe we're capable of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If nothing else, the Broncos learned that Griese can handle the  
pressure of replacing Elway. 
</P>
<P>
	Facing an aggressive pass rush, Griese completed 24 of 40 passes  
without an interception and played well enough to head off any talk 
of losing his job to Bubby Brister, who was demoted after four 
exhibition games. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was my first game. I got into the fire. Nobody can say I  
don't have at least one game of experience anymore,'' Griese said. 
``From here on out, it can't get much harder than that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expect to get a lot better and our team to get a lot better.  
This team has character. I guarantee you, we'll be back.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
