<DOCNO> APW19990914.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 14:36:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Still Not Viable for NFL Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The nation's second-largest city is back  
where it started six months ago -- without an NFL team or a place to 
play. 
</P>
<P>
	An initial deadline to reach a stadium plan for Los Angeles had  
been set by the league for Wednesday. But that deadline is passing 
without action. 
</P>
<P>
	With great fanfare last March, the NFL spurned Houston and  
announced its intention to put an expansion team in the Los Angeles 
area. But there had to be an acceptable stadium and financing 
proposal by Sept. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	The following month, the league turned its back on one of the  
two competing sites in Southern California -- Carson -- and chose the 
Coliseum as the preferred spot. 
</P>
<P>
	That relationship soured in July, when the NFL complained about  
a lack of public funding for the project at the Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	The league then encouraged other suitors in the area to step up.  
Houston, which waited patiently while the NFL attempted to work out 
the LA deal, now seems to be back in the forefront of the muddled 
picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``This thing has more lives than a cat,'' said Zev Yaroslavsky,  
a member of the Los Angeles Coliseum Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The league's deadline wasn't much of a deadline, with the NFL  
expected to entertain offers until the owners' meetings in Atlanta 
the week of Oct. 5 -- and possibly beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the expansion franchise goes to Houston, the league  
still hopes to put a team in Los Angeles at some point. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the bottom line for the NFL's 31 owners appears to be  
just that -- they want as much money for a team as they can get. 
</P>
<P>
	A new owner would have to pay the league a franchise fee, which  
could reach $600 million or more for the expansion team, in 
addition to the costly investment for a new stadium or for 
revamping an old one. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollywood dealmaker Michael Ovitz, who initially backed a  
stadium-shopping mall complex in Carson and later joined the 
Coliseum effort, noted early on that the league's team owners 
didn't get where they are by being bad businessmen. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles City Councilman Joe Wachs said the team owners  
``want to get their first billion-dollar deal here. It's not going 
to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Public funds aside, the league might eventually do its first  
billion-dollar deal in LA since three billionaires seem eager to 
bring a team to town. 
</P>
<P>
	Grocery magnate Ron Burkle is a member of the team headed by  
Ovitz, who at one time seemed favored by the league as a potential 
team owner. 
</P>
<P>
	Backing the idea of renovating the Coliseum was Eli Broad, who  
made his money in housing construction. 
</P>
<P>
	Oilman Marvin Davis joined the game later, approaching the  
league about building a stadium at Hollywood Park, reviving another 
old proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	After representatives from LA and Houston met separately with  
NFL officials in New York this week, league spokesman Greg Aiello 
said it was still a ``four-horse race'' for the new franchise. He 
noted that because of the land and parking around Hollywood Park, 
it was the ``most doable'' of the three LA sites. 
</P>
<P>
	No one outside the NFL, however, seems certain what the league  
will do. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard for them to predict where 31 people are going to  
come from, especially this group of 31,'' Carson City Manager Jerry 
Groomes said recently. 
</P>
<P>
	Ed Roski, co-owner of the NHL's Los Angeles Kings and leader of  
the drive to build the New Staples Center downtown, revived the 
idea of bringing the NFL back to the Coliseum, without an NFL team 
since the Raiders following the 1994 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he and Broad have asked NFL officials to tell them  
exactly what they need to make a deal happen at the Coliseum, 
apparently the only firm demand was for more tax money -- something 
out of their control. 
</P>
<P>
	Roski, a real estate developer, is familiar with the negotiating  
process. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every deal I've done has it's ups and downs,'' he said  
recently. ``You just have to keep going forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also thinks there are several alternatives for the league.  
</P>
<P>
	``They can award the team to Houston. They could move another  
team into the Los Angeles market. They could say to Houston, `Build 
a stadium and we will either give you the 32nd team or relocate a 
team,''' Roski said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
