<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *Sony Corp., up 11 11/16 at 148 3/16    	
</P>
<P>
	The electronics company unveiled a successor to its highly  
profitable PlayStation video-game machine for the Japanese market. 
Nikko Salomon Smith Barney raised its rating on the stock. 

</P>
<P>
 *Federal-Mogul Corp., down 9 at 30 3/8    	
</P>
<P>
	The automotive supplier said earnings for the third quarter and  
full year are expected to fall short of expectations. Company 
officials cited softness in the replacement auto parts market and 
production problems. 

</P>
<P>
 *Estee Lauder Companies, up 2 15/16 at 43 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	Analysts at Merrill Lynch and Salomon Smith Barney raised their  
ratings on shares of the cosmetics company. 

</P>
<P>
 *Tosco Corp., up 1 1/8 at 27 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	Tosco, a petroleum refiner and marketer, will replace Mercantile  
Bancorp in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index after the close of 
trading Friday. Stocks added to the index often rise, as managers 
of mutual funds designed to mirror the index's performance buy 
shares. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Qualcomm Inc., up 17 1/8 at 170 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	The wireless communications company expects to meet or exceed  
analysts' estimates that it will earn 87 cents a share in the 
fourth quarter. Qualcomm said demand is up for its chipset and 
phone units. The company also expects higher royalty payments. 

</P>
<P>
 *Herbalife International Inc., Class A shares up 3 1/8 at 15 1/8; Class B  
shares up 5 17/32 at 14 11/16 
</P>
<P>
	The founder, chairman and chief executive of Herbalife is  
planning to take the company private, buying all the shares he 
doesn't already own or control for about $500 million. Herbalife 
sells weight-management, personal-care and nutritional products. 

</P>
<P>
 *Smart Modular Technologies Inc., up 11 1/16 at 35 3/8  
</P>
<P>
 *Solectron Corp., up 1 1/16 at 75 7/16 on the NYSE 
</P>
<P>
	Solectron will acquire Smart Modular for about $2 billion in  
stock. The deal would be the largest to date in the rapidly 
consolidating electronics-outsourcing industry. Both companies make 
components and devices for larger technology companies. 



  	   	
</P>
