<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Nurses Upset Over Reprimands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Five years after a Boston Globe columnist died  
from a chemotherapy overdose at the prestigious Dana-Farber Cancer 
Institute, 13 nurses have been formally reprimanded by the state, 
even though they were delivering a dosage prescribed by a doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	The nurses agreed to accept the reprimands, which force them to  
undergo retraining or re-certification. Three others involved in 
the case are fighting the charges, and two more accepted probation. 
</P>
<P>
	Nurses elsewhere said the punishment just increases the  
demoralization in a grueling profession. ``It's not right and it's 
not fair,'' said Margaret O'Malley, a nurse in Gloucester. 
</P>
<P>
	Dana-Farber officials have stood steadfastly behind the nurses,  
saying there was no way they could have known the medications were 
incorrect. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, two patients were given four times the appropriate  
dosages of a radical chemotherapy treatment. The overdoses killed 
Globe health columnist Betsy A. Lehman and damaged the heart of 
North Andover teacher Maureen Bateman, who later died of cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Distel, Lehman's husband, received a multimillion-dollar  
settlement from the hospital. The Batemans sued Dana-Farber and 
settled out of court for an undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	The Massachusetts Board of Registration in Nursing cited 18  
Dana-Farber nurses who were connected with the overdoses. While 13 
agreed this summer to accept a reprimand, the three who are 
fighting the charges face a disciplinary hearing scheduled for Oct. 
6. 
</P>
<P>
	Two more accepted a year's probation to avoid formal charges and  
a full-scale hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly there was a bad result in the treatment of these two  
patients,'' said Anne Collins, general counsel for the Division of 
Registration, which oversees the nursing board. ``It's the board's 
concern that doesn't happen again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No external or internal reviews -- including one by the state  
Department of Public Health -- found the nurses to be at fault, and 
Dana-Farber has since taken steps to prevent similar mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Reardon, an attorney who represents the nurses, said the  
13 agreed to the sanctions because they wanted the matter to 
finally end. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he said, ``There is a general sense that they shouldn't  
be held responsible for this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The physician who wrote the erroneous chemotherapy order, Dr.  
James Foran, was training in oncology at the time and did not 
reapply for his license to practice medicine in Massachusetts. He 
now does cancer research in London. 
</P>
<P>
	The state pharmacy board also reprimanded three Dana-Farber  
pharmacists. 
</P>
<P>
	Nurses elsewhere said the reprimands make a tough job tougher.  
They pointed to the grueling aspects of nursing: long hours, dirty 
and often unappreciated work and low pay. The average pay for 
Massachusetts nurses is $40,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Karen Daley, president of the 20,000-member Massachusetts  
Nurses Association: ``It's a very tough time to be a nurse.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 11:20:27 </DATE_TIME>
