<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Biggest Italia Insurer Wants No. 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- Italy's biggest insurance company,  
Assicurazioni Generali, on Tuesday made an unsolicited bid for the 
country's No. 2 insurer, INA, the Italian stock market regulatory 
body said. 
</P>
<P>
	Generali, saying it was going after all of the share capital in  
INA, or Istituto Nazionale dalle Asicurazioni SpA, in a deal valued 
at about $12.7 billion. It said it would offer the euro equivalent 
of 86 cents plus 0.7 of a Generali share for each INA share. 
</P>
<P>
	Generali called an extraordinary shareholders meeting for Nov.  
4-6 to approve a capital increase to cover the offer. It said it 
wants two-thirds plus one share of INA's capital but would consider 
amounts as small as 34 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last week San Paolo IMI, Italy's largest bank in terms of  
assets, and INA had said they agreed to work rapidly at studying a 
possible merger. INA already controls Banco di Napoli SpA. 
</P>
<P>
	Should either of the mergers come off, it would create Italy's  
largest banking-insurance group. 
</P>
<P>
	Generali's move was immediately branded as hostile by INA.  
</P>
<P>
	The bid is ``hostile from the start,'' said INA chairman Sergio  
Siglienti. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Unicredito Italiano bettered its position for a  
takeover of Banca Nazionale del Lavoro by signing on as one of the 
banks which would finance Generali's takeover attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	INA owns 7.4 percent of Banca Nazionale del Lavoro, and should  
Generali win a takeover battle against San Paolo, Unicredito's 
bonus could be INA's stake in Banca Nazionale del Lavoro. 
</P>
<P>
	Banca di Roma last April rejected an unsolicited takeover offer  
from San Paolo. That sparked speculation that San Paolo would shift 
its sights to INA and its Banco di Napoli holding. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
