<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nazi Slave Labor Talks Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Compensation negotiations with 16 German  
companies that used Nazi slave labor will go forward despite the 
dismissal of several related lawsuits, a top Treasury Department 
official said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The companies have assured us formally that they wish to  
continue participating,'' Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart E. 
Eizenstat told a hearing of the House Banking Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Eizenstat said that while the companies want a legal conclusion,  
they also have always viewed it as ``primarily a moral issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In two separate rulings Monday, federal judges dismissed cases  
against Ford Motor Co. and two German companies. But under 
international negotiations being overseen by Eizenstat, German 
industry and the German government are planning to set up two 
foundations or funds to handle survivor claims -- a system Eizenstat 
said would be faster and cover more people than pending litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	And he urged both the companies and attorneys for survivors to  
compromise on a settlement amount, a figure on which he said they 
remain ``far apart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The German companies have time and again denied any legal  
liability in U.S. courts, but have clearly indicated their moral 
responsibility for the gross abuses inflicted on millions of forced 
and slave laborers,'' Eizenstat said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is now time that they make a proposal to settle the suits  
in a fashion consistent with their moral responsibility,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He declined to describe the amounts of money under negotiations  
but said the two sides will have to ``give considerably.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for survivors at one time reportedly demanded $20  
billion. German industry has offered $1.7 billion to compensate for 
using Nazi camp inmates for slave labor during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that plaintiffs' attorneys are aware that the initial  
monetary demands they have put forward in this negotiation are not 
considered realistic by German industry or the German government,'' 
Eizenstat said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those attorneys will need to show flexibility if these cases  
are to be settled within the lifetimes of the survivors they 
represent,'' he said. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 11:50:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jags Not Overconfident After Rout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- The Jacksonville Jaguars face one  
mind-numbing question: How do they top that? 
</P>
<P>
	Only minutes after the Jaguars left the field following a 41-3  
pounding of San Francisco, coach Tom Coughlin and the rest of the 
team started trying to figure it out. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team is terrified of complacency,'' defensive lineman  
Seth Payne said. ``I'm sure we'll come out and practice twice as 
hard this week as we did last week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That could be a good idea for a team that has traditionally had  
trouble dealing with such resounding success. 
</P>
<P>
	A few examples from last season include:  
</P>
<P>
	--A 17-16 loss at Buffalo in the game that triggered Flutiemania.  
It came on the heels of an emotional Monday night victory over 
Miami that pushed the Jaguars to 5-0. 
</P>
<P>
	--A 30-15 loss at Pittsburgh after a come-from-behind win at home  
over Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	--A 34-24 playoff loss at the Jets after winning the first home  
playoff game in team history over New England. 
</P>
<P>
	This week sets up very much the same. The Jaguars will be big  
favorites when they play the Carolina Panthers in their home 
opener, a game in which defensive coordinator Dom Capers will face 
the team that fired him as head coach after last season. 
</P>
<P>
	It comes after the biggest blowout in the team's five-year  
history, a victory that did nothing but feed the Super Bowl 
aspirations that were already flowing freely. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is no time to be reflective,'' Coughlin said. ``We can be  
happy, excited about a good victory. But we've got to keep it in 
perspective. It's a 16-game season. There are still 15 more 
mountains to climb.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of them are bound to be steeper than what the Jaguars faced  
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a second half that will be long remembered in this town,  
Jacksonville outscored the five-time Super Bowl champions 35-0. 
Capers' revamped defense made future Hall of Famers Steve Young and 
Jerry Rice look old and average. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Brackens began the final year of his contract in style with  
a sack and a forced fumble on one play, a key fourth-down tackle of 
Young on another. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornerback Aaron Beasley had two interceptions and six pass  
deflections against what was supposed to be the best trio of 
receivers in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	San Francisco gained only 205 yards and converted just one of 14  
third downs. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you win the way we won, you don't want to get  
lackadaisical, you don't want to have a letdown,'' said rookie 
cornerback Fernando Bryant, who held Rice to two catches. ``I've 
heard this team has had a thing about getting complacent after 
having a good showing. They've had trouble putting a good run 
together. We want to put a good run together this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About the only bad news to come out of the game was a sprained  
left foot sustained by running back Fred Taylor. He limped around 
Monday wearing an air cast. Coughlin said it was too early to tell 
how severe the injury was. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
