<DOCNO> APW19990914.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 14:38:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Considers Delaying Tax Credits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans are considering delays in  
mailing tax credit checks to millions of poor families as part of a 
search for money to help pay for big spending bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than receiving their earned-income tax benefits in a lump  
sum after they file -- as most of the 20 million recipients 
currently do -- people receiving the payments would get them in 
quarterly or monthly installments. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't hurt anybody,'' said John Feehery, spokesman for  
House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. ``It's just spreading out the 
payments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration officials and congressional Democrats  
accused Republicans of unfairly taking money from low-income 
American families to finance federal agencies' budgets. 
</P>
<P>
	They said the GOP idea would hurt the poor because many of them  
rely on the lump-sum payments to buy used cars and other big-ticket 
items. The proposal would force many of them to rely instead on 
costly loans, Democrats said. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal is ``tantamount to a tax increase on working  
families,'' said Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since the president will not let the Republicans dramatically  
cut taxes on the rich, they have decided to get back at Democrats 
in Washington by raising taxes on the hard-pressed working 
families,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., referring to 
President Clinton's promised veto of the GOP's 10-year, $792 
billion tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan drew a mixed reaction from Senate Republicans, casting  
doubts on its viability. While some conservatives embraced the 
idea, moderates criticized it. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,  
said he considered the idea ``dead on arrival,'' saying, ``I don't 
think we should ration things like'' the earned income credit. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever its fate, the proposal underlined the lengths to which  
Republicans are hunting for ways to pay for must-pass spending 
bills without spending the Social Security surplus, which both 
parties have pledged to leave untouched. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, Congress has sent Clinton just two of the 13 annual  
spending bills for fiscal 2000, which begins Oct. 1. Their overall 
price tag is more than $500 billion, or nearly one-third of the 
overall federal budget, and Republicans need to find tens of 
billions in savings for bills that can pass Congress and get 
Clinton's signature. 
</P>
<P>
	To pay for the measures, GOP leaders have already said they will  
use all $14 billion of the projected budget surplus excluding 
Social Security. Their desire to avoid using Social Security money 
for the spending bills -- until now a routine Washington practice 
for decades -- has led them to plans like delaying the earned income 
credit. 
</P>
<P>
	Another idea popular with Senate Republicans for coping with the  
spending problem is so-called forward funding. 
</P>
<P>
	Under this perennially used practice, money is approved that is  
mostly not available until the following fiscal year. That has the 
effect of pushing spending pressures from one year into the next. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said that Clinton's 2000 budget proposed $19 billion  
of such expenditures and that there was $11.6 billion of such money 
in this year's budget. Stevens said Republicans would slightly 
exceed that amount for 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	House GOP leaders have also been hoping to reap savings by  
getting unspent money back from the states for welfare, Medicaid 
and other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Governors have been reluctant to return the money, but might do  
so if Congress increases states' flexibility to use federal funds, 
said Clinton Keyes, executive director of the Republican Governors' 
Association. Keyes said some GOP governors plan to discuss the 
situation Thursday with congressional leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Enacted in 1975 under President Ford, the earned income credit  
is designed to discourage low-income families from falling back 
onto welfare. Its benefits have been improved several times, and 
the program has been a frequent battleground between liberals 
trying to expand it and conservatives hoping to curtail it. 
</P>
<P>
	The credit averages $1,890 annually for families with children,  
and is expected to cost nearly $32 billion next year, according to 
Treasury Department figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Feehery said the GOP proposal would save up to $8.7 billion in  
fiscal 2000, which begins on Oct. 1. The savings would come mostly 
from delaying some of the payments into the following fiscal year, 
a problem lawmakers would have to deal with then. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 16:20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricanes Work Out Before Floyd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CORAL GABLES, Fla. (AP) -- The early Hurricanes get the work.  
</P>
<P>
	Racing to beat the effects of Hurricane Floyd's passing, No. 8  
Miami was on the practice field shortly after dawn Tuesday to get 
in a full workout in preparation for Saturday's showdown against 
No. 3 Penn State. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh man,'' said tackle Robert Hall, who estimated he got four  
hours of sleep before hitting the practice field at 7:30 a.m. ``I 
didn't do too well today. But I think overall we had a good 
practice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It marked the second straight day the Hurricanes adjusted their  
practice schedule to account for Floyd, a massive storm looming off 
Florida's Atlantic coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Butch Davis called an unscheduled workout for Monday  
afternoon, usually a day off, before giving the team an early 
wakeup call Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not always easy ... to take the time this morning, get up  
early and come in and take this small window of opportunity with 
the weather and have as good a practice as we possibly could 
have,'' Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though tropical storm-force winds and scattered rain arrived  
around midday, Floyd proved to be little threat to the campus. 
Hurricane warnings were reduced to tropical storm warnings by late 
afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis said the Hurricanes would resume their usual practice  
schedule Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tricky,'' quarterback Kenny Kelly said of the changes.  
``You never know what tomorrow's schedule is going to be. So we 
play and see what happens tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly and his teammates certainly don't seem to be fazed by  
hurricane upheaval. 
</P>
<P>
	Last September, the threat of Hurricane Georges forced Miami  
into a last-minute postponement of its game against UCLA. 
Rescheduled for early December, Miami handed the Bruins their first 
loss with a 49-45 upset. 
</P>
<P>
	``To some extent, last year's UCLA preparation was a little bit  
of a dry run for these kind of situations,'' Davis said. ``All of 
our players got an opportunity to get home last night, help their 
families board up if they needed to and spend some time with 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If anything, the UCLA win has led to lighthearted suggestions  
that hurricane postponements could be something of a secret weapon 
for Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	At last month's kickoff luncheon, Davis joked that he and  
athletic director Paul Dee were discussing which game on the 
schedule needed to be moved to the end of the season. And earlier 
this week, Dee referred to the first Saturday in December as ``our 
annual hurricane makeup day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis took a more serious tone Tuesday. He recalled the 1996  
season, when preparations for a game against East Carolina were 
hampered by four days of rain and lightning. Miami lost 31-6. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the most atrocious weather that you've ever seen,''  
Davis recalled. ``We tried to watch film, we tried to practice in 
the gym, we had a halfway sloppy practice one day, then we went 
back to the gym the next day. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got beat and I vowed then that whatever we had to do --  
practice at 6 a.m., midnight, whatever -- we were going to practice. 
You don't play very well if you don't prepare well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And what would it have taken for Davis to forgo practice  
Tuesday? 
</P>
<P>
	``The National Guard dragging us off the field,'' Davis said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 10:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Names Peoria Correspondent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ill. (AP) -- Jay Hughes, a newsman in the Oklahoma City  
bureau of The Associated Press, has been named the news 
cooperative's correspondent in Peoria. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointment was announced Tuesday by James Wilson, chief of  
bureau for Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes joined the AP in Jackson, Miss., in 1998 and transferred  
to Oklahoma City later that year. 
</P>
<P>
	Before joining the AP, Hughes spent more than five years working  
at daily newspapers in Mississippi, including The (Jackson) 
Clarion-Ledger, The Vicksburg Post and The (Columbus) Commercial 
Dispatch. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes, 29, succeeds Christopher Thorne, who was named AP  
correspondent in Dover, Del. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
