<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Group Sues To Oppose School District </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Several community groups and individuals contend  
a takeover of the city's troubled school system stripped them of 
their right to vote and are asking a federal judge to declare the 
replacement of the elected school board as unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit filed Monday in U.S. District Court here seeks an  
injunction halting efforts by the reform-minded school board 
authorized by the state Legislature and appointed by Mayor Dennis 
Archer earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago and Cleveland have gone through similar school  
takeovers. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, the lawsuit contends the state's takeover of  
the district illegally counteracted residents' voting rights by 
replacing the city's elected school board with Archer appointees. 
</P>
<P>
	Reforms proposed by the new board were among the issues at the  
heart of a teachers strike that delayed the start of school for a 
week. Last Wednesday, the teachers voted to return to school while 
awaiting results of a vote on a new contract proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``The citizens of Detroit have a right to vote for their school  
board members just like everyone else in the state,'' said Sharon 
McPhail, an attorney representing the plaintiffs, who include a 
teacher, a parent and a group of Baptist ministers. 
</P>
<P>
	In approving the takeover in March, Gov. John Engler said the  
nation's 10th-largest city needed the reform plan because of 
lagging test scores, chronically low attendance and graduation 
rates, and fiscal mismanagement. 
</P>
<P>
	Defendants of the lawsuit include Engler, Archer and the chief  
executive of Detroit schools, David Adamany. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
