<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet OKs Gas Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand's Cabinet gave the green light  
Tuesday to a joint venture with Malaysia for a 220 mile gas 
pipeline from a field in the Gulf of Thailand. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai Industry Minister Suwat Liptapanlop said the state  
Petroleum Authority of Thailand will enter the $1 billion project 
on a 50-50 basis with Malaysia's state Petroliam Nasional Bhd., or 
Petronas. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the largest investment by a Thai government agency  
since the country fell into economic crisis after the flotation of 
the Thai currency in July 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The pipeline, to be built under an agreement between the two  
state petroleum companies in 1997, will deliver natural gas from an 
offshore field in a shared territory known as the Thai-Malaysia 
joint development area. Construction is to begin in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Gas will be piped to a separation plant at Songkhla province in  
southern Thailand, close to Malaysia's northern border, and on to 
Thai users and to Malaysia's northern state of Kedah. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmentalists in southern Thailand fear that the project,  
which has yet to undergo an environmental impact assessment, will 
hurt local communities, the ecosystem and tourism. They also argue 
that Thailand has a surplus of power since the economic crisis 
dampened demand. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
