<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rangel Resigns From Apollo Theatre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Rep. Charles Rangel has resigned as chairman of  
the board of the Apollo Theatre, bringing the troubled Harlem 
landmark a step closer to a deal that would put Time Warner in 
charge of its revival. 
</P>
<P>
	Actor Ossie Davis was expected to succeed Rangel.  
</P>
<P>
	Rangel's resignation, announced Monday, was among conditions  
state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer set last month when he 
tentatively agreed to drop a lawsuit alleging financial 
mismanagement by the board of the famed theater, which has launched 
the careers of a legion of black stars. 
</P>
<P>
	Board directors also voted Monday to accept nine Time  
Warner-recommended members -- on top of four added last month -- 
giving the company control of the 22-member board. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a major step forward,'' said Charles Gargano, chairman  
of the Empire State Development Corp., the state agency that owns 
the theater. ``Now that these issues have been largely cleared up 
we can see the money starting to flow, we can see a stronger 
management team there, and with that we can expect great things to 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Apollo opened in 1914, featuring live entertainment. For  
many years, every Wednesday night was Amateur Night. Among the 
winners who went on to stardom were Billie Holiday, Ella 
Fitzgerald, Leslie Uggams, Joe Tex, Jackie Wilson, the Coasters, 
Gladys Knight and the Pips, the Ink Spots, and the Shirelles. 
</P>
<P>
	It was turned into a movie theater in the 1970s and reopened for  
live shows in 1983. More recently, it was the venue for a 
television show, ``It's Showtime at the Apollo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Attorney General Dennis Vacco filed a lawsuit last year  
accusing Rangel and five other board members of failing to collect 
some $4 million owed to the theater by the Inner City Theater 
Group, which is run by Rangel's longtime friend and political ally 
Percy Sutton. 
</P>
<P>
	Spitzer, who succeeded Vacco, said in August he would drop the  
suit if at least $1 million was paid to the foundation that 
oversees the Apollo, new members were added to the board and Rangel 
stepped down as chairman. The money has not yet been paid. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Spitzer said he was pleased by Rangel's  
resignation but that more still needed to be done before the 
lawsuit could be dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Capel, Rangel's chief of staff, said the congressman had  
planned his resignation for some time, but wanted to wait until 
Spitzer's investigation was over. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
