<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Sept. 14, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	109 Killed in Moscow Explosion  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Dozens of people were missing and believed buried  
under tons of wreckage Monday after a suspected bomb pulverized an 
eight-story apartment building in Moscow, killing at least 109 
people. Authorities blamed terrorists for the pre-dawn blast, and 
appealed for help finding a man who allegedly rented space in that 
building and another that was blown up four days earlier. More than 
200 people have died in explosions in Russia during the past two 
weeks. The government ordered a massive security operation in the 
capital and other cities. 

</P>
<P>
	Israelis, Palestinians Open Talks  
</P>
<P>
	EREZ CROSSING, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Launching talks on a final  
peace accord Monday with a pledge to meet an ambitious one-year 
deadline, the top Palestinian and Israeli negotiators each set 
demands that could torpedo the talks from the outset -- were it not 
for their declared determination for a breakthrough after years of 
stagnation. A week after working through side issues -- including 
prisoner releases and land handovers -- Israelis and Palestinians 
are confronting the key issues that have long defined each side's 
sense of nationhood. In addition to Jerusalem and the return of 
territory, they will address refugees, settlements and Palestinian 
statehood. 

</P>
<P>
	State of Emergency Declared As Storm Nears  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- As Hurricane Floyd charged toward Florida with  
potentially catastrophic 155 mph winds, Gov. Jeb Bush declared a 
state of emergency Monday night and more than 1 million people were 
told to evacuate the Atlantic coast. Floyd was much larger than 
Hurricane Andrew, which caused $25 billion in damage, killed 26 
people and left 160,000 homeless in 1992. Floyd's winds -- at least 
74 mph -- extended for 125 miles, whereas Andrew's winds extended 
about 25 or 30 miles. Forecasters said Floyd would brush past the 
Bahamas overnight and could hit land in the next couple of days 
between central Florida and South Carolina. 

</P>
<P>
	Waco Evidence in 1995 Said Overlooked  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sifting through thousands of pages of  
documents provided four years ago to a congressional panel 
investigating the 1993 Waco tragedy, a House Democrat has turned up 
evidence that the Justice Department did notify Congress about the 
FBI's use of potentially incendiary tear gas. That evidence, Rep. 
Henry Waxman charged Monday, was overlooked by Rep. Dan Burton, the 
House Republican who is leading a new inquiry into the government's 
deadly standoff with the Branch Davidians -- and who has accused 
Attorney General Janet Reno and the Justice Department of possibly 
concealing the truth from Congress and the public. 

</P>
<P>
	Indonesia Wants Peacekeeping Force Soon  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Indonesia wants an international  
peacekeeping force sent to violence-ravaged East Timor as quickly 
as possible, and it is putting no conditions on what countries' 
forces should be included, Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas 
said Monday. The statement seemed to open the way for Australia to 
play a leading role in the peacekeeping operation. A top Indonesian 
military official had said earlier that the military won't accept 
Australian involvement in the East Timor force, but Alatas said 
``it's all up to the United Nations to determine the composition.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Ecuador Hunts for Foreign Hostages  
</P>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Nearly 1,000 police officers and soldiers  
combed Ecuador's rugged northeast jungle on Monday in search of 12 
North Americans and Europeans taken hostage over the weekend by an 
armed group. One American and seven Canadians -- employees of a 
Canadian oil contracting company, United Pipelines Systems -- were 
in the isolated jungle province of Sucumbios, 30 miles from the 
Colombian border, on Saturday morning when they were seized by 
about 25 heavily armed assailants, officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Close Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei closed down 132.07 points to close at  
17,777.22. 

</P>
<P>
	Astros 13, Phillies 2  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Mike Hampton joined teammate Jose Lima in the  
20-win club, and the Houston Astros set a club record by winning 
their 11th straight game, 13-2 over the Philadelphia Phillies on 
Monday night. Hampton won his 11th consecutive decision since a 
June 24 loss to Cincinnati, allowing two runs and six hits in seven 
innings with six strikeouts. 

</P>
<P>
	Dolphins 38, Broncos 21  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- With major help from the special teams, who  
blocked a punt and a field goal to set up 10 points, the Miami 
Dolphins beat the Denver Broncos 38-21 Monday night, spoiling Brian 
Griese's coming out party as John Elway's successor in the Broncos' 
first game in pursuit of a third straight Super Bowl title. It also 
put a damper on the halftime ceremony in which Elway's name and 
number were placed in the Broncos' Ring of Fame. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
