<HEADLINE> SingTel, Lycos in Asian Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- Singapore Telecom and U.S. Web media company  
Lycos announced a $50 million joint venture on Tuesday to tap into 
Asia's burgeoning Internet market. 
</P>
<P>
	Lycos Asia, as the 50-50 venture was named, will launch local  
language content sites this year in 10 countries across Asia, 
including India and China. It plans to add an additional four 
countries later. 
</P>
<P>
	The venture gives both companies a chance to grab a piece of the  
fast-growing Internet business in Asia while building on their 
respective strengths, analysts said. Lycos has an Internet brand 
name, while SingTel offers funds and regional expertise. 
</P>
<P>
	Lycos, based in Waltham, Mass., will provide its search,  
navigation and community technologies to the venture, while SingTel 
will manage day-to-day operations. 
</P>
<P>
	For SingTel, the move is part of a broader effort to diversify  
and find new sources of income as it prepares for the loss of its 
fixed-line domestic telecommunications monopoly in April, when 
international consortium StarHub starts operations in the island 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	Lycos Asia will be SingTel's first venture into the Internet  
business outside Singapore. At home, its Internet-related 
businesses include SingNet, an access service; National Computer 
Systems, and SingTel Internet Exchange, which connects 40 service 
providers in 20 countries. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
