<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed lower Tuesday,  
with the key indexes in Tokyo and Hong Kong falling on worries over 
the surging Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 132.07  
points, or 0.74 percent, to 17,777.22. On Monday, the average 
closed up 198.27 points, or 1.12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices fell as the yen surged against the greenback, rekindling  
concern that Japan's fledging economic recovery could be curbed by 
the rising yen. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen leads to lower profits for Japan's exporters, since  
it makes their products more expensive and therefore less 
competitive overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar was quoted at 106.56 yen, down  
1.22 yen from Tokyo's late Monday level of 107.78 yen, but above 
its late New York level of 106.44 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	In earlier Tokyo trading, the dollar fell as low as 106.00 yen,  
its lowest level since May 15, 1996, when it traded at 105.77 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stocks closed generally lower Tuesday, pushed down by  
the weakness in the Japanese market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, lost 56.82 points, or 0.4 percent, closing at 
13,804.03. On Monday, the index had gained 4.9 points, or 0.03 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said the Hong Kong market was hit by selective  
profit-taking in reaction to the fall on the Tokyo Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian shares closed lower on continued uncertainty over an  
international force to stem the violence in East Timor and threats 
by international lenders to freeze loans over a bank scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Asian Development Bank announced Monday that it would defer  
approval of about $500 million of loans to Indonesia because of 
alleged financial irregularities. 
</P>
<P>
	The scandal centers on a $80 million transfer from Bank Bali to  
a company controlled by a senior official in the ruling Golkar 
party. Golkar opponents claimed the funds were meant to finance 
President B.J. Habibie's re-election campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jakarta Stock Exchange's Composite Index fell 7.593 points,  
or 1.3 percent, to 562.059. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed lower on profit-taking after five  
straight sessions of advances. The market's key Weighted Stock 
Price Index fell 86.67 points, or 1.1 percent, to 8,092.02. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed slightly higher. The  
benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index edged up 1.90 points to 2,120.97. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed mixed, with a technical rebound  
on some blue chips buoying the main index after three straight days 
of losses. The Philippine Stock Exchange index of 30 selected 
companies rose 12.51 points, or 0.5 percent, to 2,101.21. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian stock market closed fractionally lower,  
with losses in resources stocks just outweighing gains in the 
industrial sector. The benchmark All Ordinaries Index closed at 
2,975.9, down 0.7 of a point. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: The main index fell 1.3 percent on profit-taking after  
three straight sessions of gains. The Korea Composite Stock Price 
Index fell 12.37 points to 968.54. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed mixed. The benchmark Straits  
Times Index rose 3.27 points, or 0.15 percent, to 2,142.50. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed lower amid a lack of  
corporate news. The Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip 
stocks, closed at 729.05, down 8.39 points, or 1.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed slightly lower. The Thailand  
SET Index fell 1.12 points, or 0.25 percent, to 443.82. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
