<HEADLINE> Universo Online Gets Expansion Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Universo Online, a large Brazilian Internet  
company, announced a $100 million deal Tuesday with a group of U.S. 
institutional investors to help fund its planned expansion in Latin 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	The investors, led by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Private Equity,  
will take a 12.5 percent stake in the company. Brazilian publishers 
Folha Group and Abril Group, who started the Sao Paulo, 
Brazil-based company in 1996, will continue to own 87.5 percent of 
UOL. 
</P>
<P>
	UOL says it is Latin America's largest online service and  
biggest private Internet access provider, with about 500,000 
subscribers in 106 cities. The company says it intends to launch 
Spanish services in Mexico, Chile, Colombia and Venezuela by early 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The new investor group also includes Blackstone Capital Partners  
III, Providence Equity Partners Inc., Credit Suisse First Boston 
Garantia Private Equity Funds, DB Capital Partners Latin America, 
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, Latinvest Asset Management and Reuters Group 
PLC. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
