<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GIs' Remains To Be Disinterred </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In his first letter home after arriving in  
South Korea in late August 1950 amid some of the bloodiest fighting 
of the Korean War, 19-year-old Robert E. Mitchell tried to sound 
reassuring. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hello Mom, Pop and Sis,'' he began. ``I'm making it just fine,  
but pray a lot because it will come in handy. If you don't hear 
from me very often don't worry because I'll make it okay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letter, postmarked Aug. 23, arrived at the Mitchell home in  
Garner, Ark., on Sept. 5. The next day he was missing. Nearly half 
a century later the family still doesn't know quite what happened. 
</P>
<P>
	Like thousands of other American soldiers who never returned  
from Korea, Mitchell is presumed to have died in battle. Like 
precious few of those sad mysteries, however, there is a glimmer of 
hope in the Mitchell case -- not that he survived but that his 
family may one day be able to bury his remains. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell's name has been tentatively linked to a set of remains  
in the National Memorial Cemetery of the Pacific in Hawaii, 
although it is not yet clear whether they can be positively 
identified. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, two sets of Korean War servicemen's remains will  
be disinterred from the cemetery in Honolulu, and the Army's 
Central Identification Laboratory there will take mitochondrial DNA 
from the bones and attempt to match it with DNA samples offered by 
family members. 
</P>
<P>
	It is possible, though not certain, that one of those sets of  
remains may be Mitchell's, Pentagon officials said Monday. The 
officials would not disclose the names associated with the two sets 
of remains. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon spokesman Larry Greer said members of 10 families  
thought to have a link to sets of remains at the Hawaii cemetery 
have provided the Central Identification Laboratory with DNA 
samples. 
</P>
<P>
	One of those people is Beth Adams, the only sister of Robert  
Mitchell. She was notified by the Pentagon on Saturday that two 
sets of remains would be removed from the Hawaii cemetery this 
week. She is not sure what the chances are, but she hopes that one 
of those sets turns out to be her brother's. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were so many years when we didn't know anything'' about  
his fate, she said in a telephone interview from her Garner, Ark., 
home. ``I'm glad to do anything that would help us know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is the first time the Pentagon has removed remains from a  
Korean War cemetery to attempt DNA identification. It has used DNA 
to identify remains of servicemen killed in the Vietnam War, 
including Air Force Lt. Michael Blassie, whose remains had been in 
the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier until last year. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Blassie success, the Pentagon decided this year it  
would attempt to identify remains from the National Memorial 
Cemetery of the Pacific, commonly called the Punchbowl, which 
contains 866 remains of servicemen from the Korean War. The remains 
were turned over to the United States by North Korea after the war 
ended in 1953, but were buried without being positively identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually as many as 70 remains from the Punchbowl may be  
disinterred and tested for DNA matching. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
