<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Moving To OK Soft Money Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the second consecutive year, the House  
appears ready to brush aside the objections of Republican leaders 
and approve a ban on the unlimited ``soft money'' campaign 
donations so prized by the national political parties. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the moment of truth for all who support reform to our  
corrupt campaign finance system,'' Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., 
said Monday at a news conference where backers of the bipartisan 
measure expressed optimism about today's vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a debate that is long overdue.''  
</P>
<P>
	It was also a debate with a familiar ring.  
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the House approved similar legislation that included  
a ban on soft money for national parties and for state parties 
seeking to influence federal elections. The vote then was 252-179, 
and came after a strenuous campaign of opposition waged by the 
leadership of the House Republican majority. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill died in a Senate filibuster last year, and opponents  
have promised to try and kill it again when it reaches the floor in 
October. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to banning soft-money donations, which are not  
regulated by the federal government, the bill would place curbs on 
certain political advertising. Broadcast commercials within 60 days 
of an election that made use of the name or likeness of a candidate 
would have to be paid for with regulated contributions. So, too, 
would any print or broadcast commercial that contained an 
``unmistakeable or unambiguous'' appeal for the election or defeat 
of a federal candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Those provisions are designed to crack down on thinly veiled  
attack ads that are now paid for with soft money. 
</P>
<P>
	A House Republican leader ridiculed the measure on Monday as an  
infringement on the First Amendment's free-speech guarantee. 
</P>
<P>
	For the bill to be constitutional, said Rep. J.C. Watts,  
R-Okla., the First Amendment would have had to be written so it 
didn't apply to speech that ``supports or opposes a cause, or is 
made anonymously, or occurs in September or October of an 
even-numbered year... 
</P>
<P>
	``Since they didn't write it this way I hope you'll join me in  
opposing'' the bill, Watts urged his Republican colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Constitutional issues aside, Republicans fear they will be hurt  
politically if soft money is banned and there are no similar curbs 
on the activities of labor unions. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Party Chairman Jim Nicholson and Rep. Tom Davis, the  
Virginian who chairs the Republican House campaign committee, 
cautioned the rank and file this summer that a ban on soft money 
could wipe out a $40 million soft money advantage the GOP enjoyed 
in the last campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	According to GOP sources, the two men said the bill's proposed  
ban on soft money would leave GOP candidates vulnerable to 
unlimited expenditures by unions and other groups working to 
overturn the narrow Republican majority in the House. 
</P>
<P>
	``During the 1998 election cycle, soft money helped fund over 32  
million phone bank calls, over 27 million GOTV (get out the vote) 
mail pieces, over 18 million absentee ballots and over 4.5 million 
issue and GOTV calls,'' said material prepared for the two men's 
presentation. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Republican used soft money to transfer $34.3  
million to state parties and to make $5.8 million in direct 
contributions to state and local candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Soft-money contributions to the Republican National Committee  
and the GOP Senate and House campaign committees totaled more than 
$130 million in the 1997-1998 election cycle, according to material 
presented to the lawmakers in August. By contrast, Democrats took 
in under $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Democrats know that eliminating soft money will give them an  
electoral advantage,'' the material went on to say. ``They will 
always have massive union funds and manpower to make up the 
difference.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
