<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Move Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices were lower today  
in early trading on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn prices were pressured by the fall harvest, with traders  
saying yields in the eastern corn belt have been better than 
anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	A sale of U.S. corn to Iran and interest from South Korea was  
limiting the price decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans dipped for a second straight day after a week-long  
rally, amid concern that the recent runup in prices would hurt U.S. 
exports. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar concerns about wheat exports pushed prices for that  
commodity lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 2 1/4 cents to $2.72 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1/2 cent to $2.15 1/2 a bushel; December oats fell 1/4 
cent to $1.15 1/2 a bushel, and November soybeans fell 5 1/4 cents to 
$5.05 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were lower on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while pork futures plummeted on signs of rising supply at a time 
when retail demand is down. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle fell .12 cent to 67.25 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle fell .02 cent to 79.60 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs tumbled 1.47 cents to 41.50 cents a pound; February 
frozen pork bellies fell .57 cents to 53.55 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
