<HEADLINE> Former Inmate To Get New Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A man cleared of a double murder after spending  
more than 15 years on death row now has a shot at erasing from his 
record charges stemming from a $2 armed robbery. 
</P>
<P>
	Anthony Porter, 43, freed from death row in February after  
another man confessed, was granted a new trial Monday for the 
robbery committed the night of the 1982 slayings. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter initially was tried before the same jury on the murder  
and armed robbery charges. 
</P>
<P>
	His attorney contended that testimony about the murders likely  
biased jurors who also found Porter guilty in the robbery. 
</P>
<P>
	Circuit Judge Thomas Fitzgerald agreed Monday in deciding that  
Porter should be retried on the three remaining charges -- armed 
robbery, unlawful restraint and unlawful use of a weapon. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if he is convicted a second time in the robbery of Henry  
Williams, Porter likely will not be sent back to prison because he 
already has served enough time for robbery. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors insist the new trial is worth the cost and effort.  
</P>
<P>
	``We think he is a robber and a stickup man and we owe it to the  
community that we serve to see that it's protected,'' Assistant 
State's Attorney Thomas Gainer said after the new trial was 
granted. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter was released after a Milwaukee laborer, Alstory Simon,  
admitted he was responsible for the 1982 fatal shootings of Marilyn 
Green, 19, and Jerry Hillard, 18, in a park on the South Side. 
</P>
<P>
	Simon made the admission under questioning by a private  
detective working with a Northwestern University journalism class. 
Simon has since pleaded guilty and been sentenced to 37 years in 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter attorney Daniel Sanders said the next step could be a  
fight over the admissibility of a dead man's testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, who testified against Porter at the 1983 trial, died  
in a fire several years ago. Sanders said it could be hard to 
convict Porter unless a transcript of what Williams told the court 
16 years ago is allowed into evidence. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
