<HEADLINE> Mayor Wants Mile High Stadium Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Mayor Wellington Webb wants the new Denver Broncos  
stadium to keep the old one's name. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter Monday, Webb urged the Metropolitan Football Stadium  
District to keep Mile High Stadium as the ``stand-alone name'' of 
the stadium being built. 
</P>
<P>
	``As an elected official who is typically called upon to be a  
steward of citizen tax dollars, my first inclination was to find a 
way to lessen the tax burden of the new stadium by considering 
corporate naming rights,'' Webb said in a press release. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I've spoken with fans who remember the Broncos of the  
striped-socks era and I've spoken with fans who endured the 
blistering snowstorms to watch the team play at Mile High. 
</P>
<P>
	``Traveling around the world, there are few things that are  
synonymous with the City of Denver and the Rocky Mountain region'' 
than the Broncos and Mile High Stadium, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the groundbreaking for the stadium last month, Broncos owner  
Pat Bowlen said he also wants the home of the two-time Super Bowl 
champions to retain its name. 
</P>
<P>
	The final decision rests with the Stadium District, which  
oversees the taxpayers' three-quarters share of the $364.2 million 
project. 
</P>
<P>
	A sale of naming rights could bring an estimated $50 million in  
help for public costs. Last month, board member Joy Burns said 
although everyone loves the name Mile High Stadium, there is not 
such a significant attachment to it that would preclude a name 
change. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the district begins to take bids, it must by law survey  
residents in the six-county Denver area about retaining the name. 
Board members said last month that the survey will probably be done 
in the next six months. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
