<HEADLINE> Treasury Urges Holocaust Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A top U.S. Treasury official today urged  
German companies to offer a bigger payment to survivors of Nazi 
slave labor camps, saying it is time for them to meet ``their moral 
responsibility'' for wartime abuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart E. Eizenstat told the House  
Banking Committee that survivors also must reduce their demands in 
order to reach agreement by year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	``The German companies have time and again denied any legal  
liability in U.S. courts, but have clearly indicated their moral 
responsibility for the gross abuses inflicted on millions of forced 
and slave laborers,'' Eizenstat said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is now time that they make a proposal to settle the suits  
in a fashion consistent with their moral responsibility,'' 
Eizenstat said of the 16 companies. 
</P>
<P>
	He declined to say what amounts of money are being negotiated  
but said the two sides are far apart and will have to ``give 
considerably.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for survivors at one time reportedly demanded $20  
billion. German industry has offered $1.7 billion to compensate for 
using Nazi camp inmates as slave labor during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``By the same token, I hope that plaintiffs' attorneys are aware  
that the initial monetary demands they have put forward in this 
negotiation are not considered realistic by German industry or the 
German government,'' Eizenstat said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those attorneys will need to show flexibility if these cases  
are to be settled within the lifetimes of the survivors they 
represent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The companies and the German government are planning to set up  
two foundations or funds to handle survivor claims, a system 
Eizenstat said would be faster and cover more people than pending 
U.S. lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had received assurances from companies that they will  
continue to negotiate a settlement despite court rulings Monday in 
which U.S. federal judges dismissed two separate cases against an 
American and two German companies. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because while the companies want ``legal closure,'' on  
the issue of compensation, it was ``always viewed as primarily a 
moral issue,'' Eizenstat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
