<HEADLINE> Fredericks Qualifies for 100 Meters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Frankie Fredericks of Namibia  
qualified Tuesday for the 100-meter finals as the All Africa Games 
rolled into high gear with the start of track and field events. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigerian Deji Aliu supplied the major competition for  
Fredericks, actually clocking a faster 10.11 in the same semifinal 
as the Namibian. Fredericks' 10.27 was only the fourth-fastest 
qualifying time for Wednesday's final. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Assefa Mezgebu of Ethiopia won the 10,000 meters in  
28:12.15. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 5,000 athletes from 52 countries are participating in the  
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	There was some excitement at a basketball game between Angola  
and Ethiopia. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Awoture Eleyae, head of the Supreme Council of Sport in  
Africa, said guns were taken from Angolan spectators who live in 
South Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't comprehend why people would want to watch a basketball  
with guns,'' Eleyae said. 
  	   	
