<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CART Race Will Return to Cleveland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- CART and IMG Motorsports agreed Tuesday to  
bring a race back to Cleveland for the next three years, reversing 
CART's decision earlier this summer to pull out of the local grand 
prix. 
</P>
<P>
	IMG and Championship Auto Racing Teams had argued over the  
sanctioning fee for the race. But they agreed on a deal that will 
put the circuit's championship series back at the temporary course 
at Burke Lakefront Airport through 2002, IMG spokesman Denny Young 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the new deal were not disclosed. IMG president Bud  
Stanner said in June that CART's sanctioning fee had jumped from 
$1.6 million to about $2 million, which was more than his company 
wanted to pay. 
</P>
<P>
	The less expensive Indy Racing League had planned to take CART's  
place, backed by IMG. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mayor Michael R. White withdrew his support for the IRL race  
on Sept. 3, citing rumors that CART and IRL might merge. The IRL 
race's oval course also would have required construction at the 
airport. 
</P>
<P>
	White then asked IMG and CART to return to the negotiating  
table. 
</P>
<P>
	``CART will be back in Cleveland next summer and for many years  
to follow,'' White said. ``This is great news for the city of 
Cleveland, CART and racing's most loyal fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CART spokesman Ron Richards said the mayor's actions helped  
bring the two sides together.	   ''We always recognized that Cleveland's a great place to race,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman from IRL referred back to a statement earlier this  
month from Leo Mehl, IRL's executive director, who said it was 
unfortunate the IRL won't be able to race in Cleveland. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
