<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ellen Tracy Spring Fashion Unveiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For its spring 2000 wardrobe, the Ellen Tracy  
fashion company is offering women a little something - and the 
emphasis is on little. 
</P>
<P>
	With hems on skirts -- and on pants, too -- rising so high, and  
with belly-baring waistlines riding so low, wearers might need to 
tone ankles as well as abs. 
</P>
<P>
	Seldom do designers accomplish so much with so little.  
</P>
<P>
	A fabric shortage? Perhaps. But Ellen Tracy's Fashion Week  
runway show Tuesday made a case for clothes in pint-size 
proportions. Low-slung khaki linen trousers cropped on the calf 
combined with abbreviated T-shirts that showed slivers of stomach. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellen Tracy is a $250 million company that typically tracks the  
trends while catering to a stylish customer who demands 
comfortable, corporate clothes. Now the company is sizing up spring 
with a little sizzle. 
</P>
<P>
	``The return of the shorter length is going to be newer,'' says  
Linda Allard, the company's head designer. ``It puts a whole new 
emphasis on the shapes and on the figure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other looks, such as satin raincoats in tropical garden colors,  
and gauze tunics, offer body-friendly coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere on the runways Tuesday, Oscar de la Renta, ever the  
perfectionist, saw to it that the sky was gloriously blue for his 
spring preview - even if it was only a projected, celestial 
backdrop with cottony clouds. 
</P>
<P>
	So much the better to show off his favorite blue: denim.  
</P>
<P>
	Denim? From de la Renta? Granted, it's not exactly the blue-jean  
rodeo-queen variety. The Dominican-born designer has built his 
business dressing well-heeled women who populate the social pages. 
His rendition of the true-blue American fabric promises to show up 
at important soirees. Take, for instance, his white cotton evening 
gowns paired with impeccably tailored denim jackets. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really mostly about the mixture of the unmixable,'' says  
de la Renta. ``That's what fashion is all about today. You can take 
a daytime element and mix with evening elements for a wonderful 
look.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other eye-catchers: de la Renta's enormous, silk tulle ballerina  
ball skirts, approximately three feet in diameter. Make room for 
that new closet. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicole Miller conjured up ``an eclectic hodgepodge,'' she said,  
which touches on trends including florals, crayon brights, ruffles, 
and sheer and shine. 
</P>
<P>
	Like de la Renta, her mind is on the mix.  
</P>
<P>
	``I like the contrast of more modern items, like a rubber top,  
with more vintage items, like a beaded floral print '70s skirt,'' 
says Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller's chaos theory also showed up in the form of animal  
prints, surprisingly cast in turquoise or magenta. Unlike anything 
you'd find in the forest, they're ideal for the urban jungle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
