<DOCNO> APW19990914.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 11:10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Details of Atlanta Games Bid Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The IOC will request details of any improprieties  
during Atlanta's bid for the 1996 Olympics and refer any serious 
cases to its ethics panel for possible action, a spokesman said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Olympic Committee will write the U.S. Olympic  
Committee on Tuesday or Wednesday, asking for information on the 
lobbying tactics contained in Atlanta's bid files, spokesman 
Franklin Servan-Schreiber said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once we get the information, it will be passed on to the  
ethics commission. Right now, the only document the IOC has is what 
it reads in the press. For us, it's still at a level of 
allegations,'' Servan-Schreiber said. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously secret records turned over to U.S. congressional  
investigators have revealed that Atlanta bidders offered or 
considered lavish favors, gifts and perks for IOC members and their 
families during their successful campaign for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents uncovered so far contain no evidence of the  
scholarships, cash payments and other bribery associated with Salt 
Lake City's winning bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the rules on gifts (value limit of $200) and travel  
(one trip for two people) were often ignored. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten IOC members either resigned or were expelled in connection  
with the Salt Lake scandal. The top two officials of the Salt Lake 
organizing committee also lost their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything that we have seen so far in the press shows that  
the bid from Atlanta did not cross the line that was crossed in 
Salt Lake City,'' Servan-Schreiber told The Associated Press by 
telephone from Sydney, Australia, where he is attending meetings 
related to the 2000 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything that we have read shows that Atlanta actually  
pushed those favors and gifts onto the IOC members under the 
pretext of friendship,'' he said. ``The members weren't used to 
this systematic approach to lobbying. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly this is the kind of activity the IOC is trying to  
refrain from. This is why the IOC reforms are taking place. We 
don't want it to happen again. We want the public to have full 
confidence in the IOC process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In February, at the height of the Salt Lake scandal, the IOC  
sent letters to national Olympic committees asking for details of 
any ethical misconduct during bids for the games from 1996 to 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	Servan-Schreiber said no serious cases were reported to the IOC,  
including from Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``The letter we are sending to the USOC will ask why the IOC was  
not informed earlier of the information coming out now,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Any allegations meriting investigation would be dealt with by  
the new IOC ethics commission, which was set up in the wake of the 
Salt Lake affair. The eight-member panel is headed by IOC vice 
president Keba Mbaye and includes former Sen. Howard Baker. It is 
scheduled to meet again Sept. 27. 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta Journal-Constitution reported Sunday that bid  
documents show Atlanta bidders helped the sons and daughters of IOC 
members get into colleges in Georgia, offered to help them find 
jobs and paid for trips to New York and Disney World in Orlando, 
Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN reported it had obtained documents indicating that Atlanta  
organizers believed IOC members could be ``bought.'' One memo in 
the files reportedly describes one IOC member's tastes this way: 
``Gifts are OK. Gift of female OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CNN also reported that the wife of IOC president Juan Antonio  
Samaranch and a friend were flown to Atlanta and taken on a side 
trip by private jet to Charleston, S.C., in 1990 -- at a total cost 
of more than $11,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``We found it very surprising,'' Servan-Schreiber said. ``It  
probably fell through the cracks. Normally, the IOC pays for the 
president and his wife when they travel. I have no idea why the 
Atlanta bid committee paid for that. Should we reimburse that? I 
don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The spokesman said Samaranch and his wife don't fall within the  
bid-limit rules because he does not vote in the selection of host 
cities and holds a position ``similar to a head of state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's normal to extend hospitality to his wife,''  
Servan-Schreiber said. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that the friend accompanying Mrs. Samaranch was her  
cousin, whom he described as her habitual traveling companion. 
</P>
<P>
	Two current IOC members have been cited in the Atlanta records  
as receiving special favors. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the documents examined by the Journal-Constitution,  
Atlanta officials arranged for the son of Rampaul Ruhee of 
Mauritius to enroll at Georgia Tech in fall 1990. They also helped 
him settle into an apartment, with leased furniture and rent paid 
five months in advance, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	It also cited documents indicating that Atlanta Olympics chief  
Billy Payne helped the son of Russian member Vitaly Smirnov get a 
job at a ski resort in Colorado. Newsweek magazine, meanwhile, 
reported that Smirnov received travel and favors worth a total of 
$8,500 from Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Smirnov was one of five IOC members who received a ``serious  
warning'' earlier this year for their role in the Salt Lake 
scandal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
