Silver(final) -   $5.100  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.

</P>
<P>
	Trade Deficit Sets Quarterly Record  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's trade deficit soared to another  
record high, but the overall economy remained unfazed as consumers 
went on a buying binge in August. The Commerce Department reported 
today that retail sales jumped 1.2 percent last month, the biggest 
increase in six months, as consumers snapped up new cars, furniture 
and clothing at a rapid clip. In a second report, the government 
said the U.S. current account trade deficit climbed to an all-time 
high of $80.7 billion in the April-June quarter of this year. That 
was up 17.5 percent from a first-quarter deficit of $68.7 billion, 
the previous record. 

</P>
<P>
	Qualcomm Shares Rise 11 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Shares of communications company Qualcomm Inc.  
rose more than 11 percent today after the firm announced it was 
seeking a buyer for its mobile phone manufacturing unit and that 
fourth-quarter earnings would meet or beat estimates. Shares of 
Qualcomm, which for months had been the subject of rumors that it 
would sell the phone manufacturing business, rose 17 1/8 to 170 1/2. 
Spokesman Christine Trimble said Qualcomm will focus on licensing 
its CDMA technology to other phone manufacturers and will continue 
designing and manufacturing CDMA chips. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Household Moving Firms To Merge  
</P>
<P>
	FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) -- North American Van Lines Inc. plans to  
merge with Allied Van Lines in a $450 million deal that will create 
the world's largest moving company. NA Holding Corp., which will be 
based in Fort Wayne, would have more than $2 billion in annual 
revenues, locations in 36 countries and a network of 1,100 agents 
throughout North America. The merger would establish it as the 
clear leader in a business that's been very competitive, said 
analyst Doug Rockel of ING Barings LLC. 

</P>
<P>
	Deadline Nears for Auto Workers  
</P>
<P>
	AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Contract talks between the United  
Auto Workers and automakers intensified today as agreements 
covering 407,000 workers were due to expire at midnight. The union 
appeared to be negotiating hardest with DaimlerChrysler AG. 
Officials met at the German-American automaker's U.S. offices in 
Auburn Hills late into last night and resumed talks today. 
Negotiations are also under way with General Motors Corp. and Ford 
Motor Co. 

</P>
<P>
	Credit Protection Schemes Decried  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators say credit card protection  
scams have become big business for fraudulent operations who target 
people unaware of the rights they already have. The Federal Trade 
Commission was announcing cases against several such companies 
today. They are accused of bilking consumers out of $25 million by 
exploiting concerns about card theft, loss or Y2K-related problems. 
Attorneys general in Illinois, Ohio, Arizona, Florida, West 
Virginia and Wisconsin planned similar actions. Credit card holders 
already are entitled to certain protections without having to pay 
for them. 

</P>
<P>
	Securities Fraud Alleged in Japan  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Several Japanese companies face possible losses  
from bonds they purchased from a Tokyo-based securities firm whose 
head is facing charges for allegedly bilking Japanese investors out 
of up to $1 billion. Martin Armstrong, 50, was charged yesterday 
with securities fraud by federal prosecutors and the Securities and 
Exchange Commission for allegedly swindling investors through 
corporations he controlled -- including Tokyo-based Cresvale 
International Ltd. -- in attempt to make up for trading losses. The 
Maple Shade, N.J. man was released on $5 million bail after an 
appearance in federal court in Trenton, N.J. 

</P>
<P>
	Practical Cars at Frankfurt Show  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Automakers unveiled a number of boxy  
family cars at the Frankfurt auto show today, offering a glimpse of 
Europe's automotive future that looks decidedly practical. 
Volkswagen's new Polo, new versions of Ford's Fiesta, the Audi A2 
and concept vehicles by Opel and Chrysler all have a similar shape 
-- drawing cues from the minivan with their conventional car hoods 
and a hatchback-style rear. There were also new advances at the 
high end of the market as Mercedes showed its S600, a V-12 luxury 
car, and a coupe version of its SLR super sports car. BMW showed 
off its Z8 roadster and an X5 ``sports activity vehicle'' that 
combines design elements of a station wagon and sports utility 
vehicle. 

</P>
<P>
	Gov't Offering Y2K Warnings Abroad  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In what promises to be the best road map yet  
for identifying global problems caused by the Year 2000 technology 
glitch, the State Department today said it was preparing 
country-by-country warnings for Americans living or traveling in 
194 nations. While there is no reason yet to issue any specific 
warning, Kevin Herbert, director of overseas citizens services at 
the department, said Americans could face ``potential 
difficulties'' in obtaining medical services, proper water and 
other facilities as a result of malfunctioning computers. Herbert 
said technology warnings would be routinely issued along with 
familiar travel advisories. 

</P>
<P>
	Universo Online Gets Expansion Funds  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Universo Online, a large Brazilian Internet  
company, announced a $100 million deal with a group of U.S. 
institutional investors to help fund its planned expansion in Latin 
America. The investors, led by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Private 
Equity, will take a 12.5 percent stake in the company. Brazilian 
publishers Folha Group and Abril Group, who started the Sao Paulo, 
Brazil-based company in 1996, will continue to own 87.5 percent of 
UOL. 

</P>
<P>
	Health Care Companies Curb Service  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some home health care companies say new  
Medicare payment caps have prompted them to curb services to 
elderly and disabled patients with expensive medical problems, such 
as diabetes or congestive heart failure. Results of a survey 
covering 28 home care companies in nine states found steps being 
taken include turning away patients likely to need longer-term or 
repeat care, particularly diabetics, or intensive short-term care 
such as those such as those who leave the hospital with intravenous 
drips. Virtually all of the companies said they were also pushing 
to discharge existing Medicare patients with chronic diseases, such 
diabetes or multiple sclerosis, into nursing homes or family care. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Gov'ts Ignore IMF Warnings  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Critics often blame the International Monetary  
Fund for failing to predict or prevent financial crises, but a new 
report concludes that governments do not heed IMF warnings designed 
to fend off economic turmoil. The independent report, commissioned 
by the agency, also says, however, that IMF monitoring of the 
economies of its 182 member nations has failed to keep pace with 
the globalization of financial markets and the increased importance 
of billions of dollars moving around the world every day. 

</P>
