<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Merger May Form Largest Moving Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) -- North American Van Lines Inc. plans to  
merge with Allied Van Lines in a $450 million deal that will create 
the world's largest moving company. 
</P>
<P>
	NA Holding Corp., which will be based in Fort Wayne, would have  
more than $2 billion in annual revenues, locations in 36 countries 
and a network of 1,100 agents throughout North America. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger would establish it as the clear leader in a business  
that's been very competitive, said analyst Doug Rockel of ING 
Barings LLC. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are two heavyweights within a relatively modest niche  
inside the trucking industry,'' Rockel said. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger is expected to be completed by the end of the year,  
pending regulatory approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal calls for Clayton, Dubilier &AMP; Rice Inc., the New York  
investment firm that owns most of North American, to pay Allied's 
London-based parent, NFC PLC, $400 million in cash and $25 million 
in preferred and common stock that represents a 20 percent stake in 
NA Holding Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	NFC will receive warrants to acquire an additional 10 percent  
stake in the company. 
</P>
<P>
	CD&AMP;R will hold on to 55 percent of NA Holding. The remainder  
will be held by North American management and agents. 
</P>
<P>
	About 18 months after merging, the combined company will realize  
annual savings of $20 million to $30 million through greater 
efficiencies, said R. Barry Uber, North American's president and 
chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	No layoffs are expected since the two companies overlap little  
geographically, Uber said. 
</P>
<P>
	North American specializes in moving high-end merchandise such  
as computers, medical equipment and commercial products, while 
Allied specializes in households. 
</P>
<P>
	``We bring together two outstanding teams with an agent network  
unmatched in the industry,'' Uber said. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger would represent a major consolidation in the  
household moving industry at the time when six years of housing 
growth is threatened by the higher interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	But Uber said North American's analysis of recent recessions  
showed the moving industry did not contract nearly as much as the 
economy as a whole. 
</P>
<P>
	``If things were bad in a marketplace, people move to get jobs  
in another part of the country. This is a very mobile society,'' 
Uber said. 
</P>
<P>
	All of Allied's moving-services business -- Allied in the United  
States and Canada, Pickfords in the United Kingdom, and Allied 
Pickfords in Europe, Australia and Asia -- would keep those brand 
names in the combined company. 
</P>
<P>
	James W. Rogers, a principal in CD&AMP;R, will serve as chairman of  
the combined company. 
</P>
<P>
	Allied Van Lines, established in 1928, employs 4,000 people  
worldwide and moved 338,000 shipments last year. North American, 
founded in 1933, employs about 3,200 people worldwide and moved 
more than 440,000 shipments last year. 






  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
