<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans, Grains Mostly Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures fell sharply Tuesday on the  
Chicago Board of Trade, while grain futures were mostly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second straight day that soybean prices declined  
after a long price rally that had been fueled by bone-dry weather 
in the Midwest and expectations of a shrinking crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are concerned that the surge in the price of soybeans  
will hurt the demand for U.S. exports. 
</P>
<P>
	Positive signs from the fall harvest of corn sent prices for  
that commodity lower. Fair weather is expected through the week, 
helping producers, and moisture levels are said to be low, enabling 
harvesting to begin in key states. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat was pressured by weak export sales, but potential losses  
were offset by the anticipation that freezes in the northern Plains 
states and the Canadian prairie could cause problems for the spring 
wheat crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery was unchanged at $2.88 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1 1/4 cents to $2.14 3/4 a bushel; December oats fell 
1 cent to $1.14 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans fell 8 1/2 cents to 
$5.01 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures rose on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while pork  
futures were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose .50 cent to 67.87 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle rose .75 cent to 80.37 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs rose .13 cent to 43.10 cents a pound; February frozen 
pork bellies fell .05 cent to 54.07 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
