<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italian, Deutsche Telecoms at Odds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- The shareholders of the Wind telecommunications  
consortium on Tuesday effectively voted to oust Deutsche Telekom's 
two board members. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote technically was in favor of a motion of  
``accountability'' against the Deutsche Telekom representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the move, Deutsche Telekom is not obliged to sell its  
stake in Wind, a fixed-line and cellular telephone operator, 
according to a source close to the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	Wind is 51 percent owned by the Italian state electricity group  
Enel SpA, with the remainder evenly divided between France Telecom 
and Deutsche Telekom. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote over accountability was in response to Deutsche  
Telekom's move to enter alliance negotiations with Telecom Italia 
SpA, which is Italy's main cellular phone operator a a bit 
competitor of Wind. 
</P>
<P>
	Enel and France Telecom claim the alliance talks violated  
shareholder covenants. The alliance talks failed. 
</P>
<P>
	The accountability motion required the approval of holders of at  
least 20 percent of shares. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Deutsche Telekom said the ``move represents an  
abuse of law'' and that it would take necessary legal steps to 
counter it. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, a Rome court ruled that Deutsche Telekom damaged Wind  
when it entered into alliance talks with Telecom Italia. The court 
imposed the symbolic punishment of requiring Deutsche Telekom to 
publish the ruling in three major Italian newspapers. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
