<DOCNO> APW19990914.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 16:00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Hits Three-Year Low vs. Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell to a three-year low against the  
Japanese yen Tuesday amid news that America's trade deficit soared 
to another record high in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 105.79 yen in late New York trading,  
down from 106.44 yen on Monday and the lowest level since May 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the dollar rose against other major currencies. The  
euro was quoted at $1.0354, down from $1.0411 on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the third straight losing session against the yen for the  
dollar, which has been hurt by optimism that a budding Japanese 
recovery may be a better investment than the U.S. economy -- 
especially with the Federal Reserve trying to slow it with higher 
interest rates as a precaution against inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Those pressures were compounded Tuesday by a report revealing  
that the U.S. current account trade deficit climbed to $80.7 
billion in the April-June quarter. That was up 17.5 percent from a 
first-quarter deficit of $68.7 billion, the previous record. 
</P>
<P>
	The current account is the broadest measure of trade because it  
tracks not only goods and services but also investment flows and 
U.S. foreign aid payments. The second-quarter's deterioration came 
in all areas as a slight rise in exports was swamped by a big jump 
in imports, led by sharply higher foreign oil prices. 
</P>
<P>
	A jump in imports weighs on the dollar because foreign companies  
selling products in the United States take their U.S. revenues and 
convert them to other currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Tuesday, the dollar was quoted at 1.5486 Swiss  
francs, up from 1.5420 on Monday, and 1.4745 Canadian dollars, up 
from 1.4697 a day earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound fell to $1.6072 from late Monday's quote of  
$1.6080. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8890  
German marks, up from 1.8785 on Monday; 6.3353 French francs, up 
from 6.3003; and 1,870 Italian lire, up from 1,860. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
