<HEADLINE> Securities Fraud Alleged in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Several Japanese companies face possible losses  
from bonds they purchased from a Tokyo-based securities firm whose 
head is facing charges for allegedly bilking Japanese investors out 
of up to $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Armstrong, 50, was charged Monday with securities fraud  
by federal prosecutors and the Securities and Exchange Commission 
for allegedly swindling investors through corporations he 
controlled -- including Tokyo-based Cresvale International Ltd. -- in 
attempt to make up for trading losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Maple Shade, N.J. man was released on $5 million bail after  
an appearance in federal court in Trenton, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	In Japan, resin maker Gun Ei Chemical Industry Co. said Tuesday  
it will post a special loss of 11.79 billion yen ($111.3 million) 
in the quarter ending Sept. 30 in connection with the write-off of 
its Cresvale bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the company said, it will omit its dividend and  
cancel plans to buy back shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Truck assembler Showa Aircraft Industry Co. said its Cresvale  
bond holdings have a book value of about 2.39 billion yen ($22.5 
million). 
</P>
<P>
	Showa faces a ``significant impact'' on its earnings for the  
fiscal year ending March 2000 if it must write off the holdings, 
the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Daiseki Co., which provides industrial garbage  
collection services, said its Cresvale bond holdings total 400 
million yen ($3.7 million), while restaurant chain operator 
Saizeriya Co. and Towa Pharmaceutical Co. each said they has 500 
million yen ($4.7 million). Advertising agency Asatsu-DK Inc. said 
it held 3 billion yen ($28.6 million). 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of several midsize Japanese companies, including metal  
worker Amada Co. and stereo maker Alps Electric Co., fell Tuesday 
after they announced that they, too, may have to record losses 
because of Cresvale investments. 
</P>
<P>
	Alps said it may have to write off 21.8 billion yen ($200.5  
million) of investments made by two subsidiaries, while Amada said 
it holds 6 billion ($57 million) of bonds that it may have to take 
losses on. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Japan's Financial Supervisory Agency ordered Cresvale  
International to halt sales of the bonds temporarily. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong controls Princeton Global Management Ltd. and its  
parent company, Princeton Economics International Ltd. He also 
controls several securities agencies, including Cresvale. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
