<HEADLINE> Teacher Balks at Wearing Tie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN, Pa. (AP) -- A high school teacher who says his neck is  
painfully scarred because of surgery for Hodgkin's disease is suing 
to challenge a school dress code that requires him to wear a tie. 
</P>
<P>
	The operation 10 years ago left Anthony Slatcoff with  
``extensive rope-like scars, a source of extreme pain when wearing 
clothing that exerts pressure on the neck,'' according to his 
federal lawsuit against the Berlin-Brothersvalley school district. 
</P>
<P>
	The biology teacher wants a judge to order an exemption in the  
dress code for him. He went without a tie from Aug. 30 to Sept. 2 
at Berlin-Brothersvalley High and got verbal and written warnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Slatcoff also has filed a discrimination charge with the Equal  
Employment Opportunity Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides are negotiating a settlement, said Wayne  
Henderson, the school district superintendent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
