<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 07:30:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Campaigns Thrive in Current System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With Congress considering legislation to  
regulate managed-care health plans, the health and insurance 
industries gave $3.3 million in unregulated soft money to the 
Republican and Democratic parties -- contributions that would be 
eliminated under legislation moving to the House floor this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP received $2.6 million and the Democrats $1.7 million  
from health and insurance interests, according to the advocacy 
group Common Cause. The banking and securities industries, pushing 
for legislation overhauling Depression-era banking regulations, 
gave $3 million to the GOP and $2.5 million to the Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	That continues the Republican Party's traditional edge in soft  
money contributions, the unregulated amounts from labor unions, 
individuals and businesses that do not fall under contribution 
limits but cannot be used as direct aid to federal candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Party committees raised $30.7 million in soft money  
during the first half of 1999 compared with $24.5 million raised by 
Democratic committees, Common Cause said. During the 1998 
elections, the Republicans raised $131.6 million in soft money, 
compared with the Democrats' $92.8 million, Federal Election 
Commission records show. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders have urged Republican lawmakers to defeat the  
campaign finance bill that would ban soft money. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, an alternative proposal, sponsored by Rep. John  
Doolittle, R-Calif., would not ban soft money but would eliminate 
federal funding of presidential campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican front-runner for the  
2000 presidential nomination, reported last week that he had raised 
a record $49 million. Bush is not accepting public financing for 
his campaign, allowing him to avoid spending limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Except for publisher Steve Forbes, who is paying most of his  
campaign expenses himself, the other Republican candidates and both 
Democratic hopefuls are seeking federal funds to help finance their 
campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	House Republican leaders, who oppose overhauling campaign  
finance laws, have flourished under the current system. Speaker 
Dennis Hastert of Illinois, and Majority Leader Dick Armey and 
Majority Whip Tom DeLay, both of Texas, raised more than $3 million 
during the first six months of 1999 for their campaign committees 
and for the separate political action committees they control. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
