<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Fall on Inflation Worries / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury bond prices fell Tuesday on renewed  
inflation fears after a government report of unexpectedly strong 
retail sales in August. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong consumer demand for retail products can push prices  
higher stirring up inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 31/32  
point, or $9.68 3/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, rose to 6.12 percent from Monday's 6.05 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasurys got off to a bad start early in the trading session  
following the lead of the dollar, which continued its slide against 
the Japanese yen, despite another effort by the Bank of Japan to 
slow the yen's rise by buying dollars Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds also fell as the Commerce Department announced that retail  
sales rose 1.2 percent in August, well above economists' 
expectations of a 0.7 percent increase. The news renewed concerns 
among traders that the Federal Reserve may raise interest rates for 
a third time this year in an effort to slow down the United States 
economy and stave off inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders will have to contend with additional inflation-related  
news Wednesday, when the Consumer Price Index for August is 
released. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of short-term Treasury securities fell 3/32 to 1/8 point,  
and intermediate maturities declined 1/4 to 7/16 point, reported 
Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.81 percent as the  
discount rose 0.02 percentage point from Monday's weekly auction to 
4.68 percent. Six-month yields were 5.11 percent, as the discount 
fell 0.01 percentage point from the auction to 4.91 percent. 
One-year yields were 5.26 percent as the discount rose by 0.02 
percentage point from late Monday to 4.99 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, remained unchanged at 5.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/2 point to 113 1/8. The average yield to 
maturity rose to 5.86 percent from 5.82 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
