<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MGM Reclaims Some Broadcast Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- MGM, making plans to launch a cable or  
satellite TV network, is regaining some broadcast rights to about 
800 movies it licensed to Turner Broadcasting System. 
</P>
<P>
	The studio said Tuesday it will reclaim full television rights  
to 200 titles and is getting non-exclusive rights on the other 600. 
MGM will be able to air the movies as early as next September on 
any network the studio owns or operates. 
</P>
<P>
	Films that MGM and Turner will share include ``West Side  
Story,'' ``Annie Hall'' and ``The Magnificent Seven.'' Films it 
will regain exclusively include ``Lenny'' and some of the ``Pink 
Panther'' movies. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner swapped the film rights in exchange for an extension of  
up to two years on its broadcast rights to the 600 titles it will 
share. Under the 1990 licensing deal, Turner's rights to those 
movies were to expire at various times between 2000 and 2007. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
