<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amtrak Testimony Contradictory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Federal investigators have grown pessimistic that  
witness testimony can provide concrete answers into what caused the 
deadly collision between an Amtrak train and a truck in March. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Transportation Safety Board is searching for clues  
into the crash that left 11 passengers dead and 122 injured after a 
truck was struck by the City of New Orleans train in Bourbonnais, 
about 50 miles south of Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-day hearing into the March 15 crash continues today  
with testimony from Amtrak executives. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday was a day of conflicting testimony.  
</P>
<P>
	Luis A. Nieves, who testified he was driving the second of two  
cars stopped behind John R. Stokes' tractor-trailer, said through 
an interpreter that he saw warning lights and heard bells as Stokes 
drove through the railroad crossing. 
</P>
<P>
	Nieves said he also saw a crossing gate strike Stokes' truck as  
he attempted to drive it around the barrier, shortly before it was 
struck in the rear by the train. 
</P>
<P>
	But truck driver Aubrey Fosburgh, who was picking up cargo about  
75 to 100 yards from the crash site, said the crossing gate was up 
when Stokes crossed the railroad, adding that he ``never (saw) the 
gate down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also described the ball of flame that shot into the air  
shortly after the crash. ``It was a mess,'' Fosburgh said, who 
rushed to the scene to help passengers escape a mangled train car. 
</P>
<P>
	The conflicting accounts did little to clear up two key  
questions: Was Stokes trying to drive his fully loaded truck around 
the railroad's crossing gates and beat the oncoming locomotive? Or 
did the crossing's warning signals activate too late -- or not at 
all -- leaving him unaware that the train was rumbling toward him at 
79 mph? 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know that there's anything that is clear one way or  
another as a result of today,'' said George Black, the NTSB member 
who is chairing the hearing into the fiery collision. 
</P>
<P>
	Black said the NTSB probably won't make any final determinations  
until March. 
</P>
<P>
	Stokes, who was not hurt in the crash, refused to testify  
Monday. He told authorities after the crash that he didn't see the 
train approaching, and claimed the crossing's warning bells, lights 
and gates activated after he was on the tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	In other testimony Monday, train engineer Angel Flores said he  
sounded the whistle and activated the emergency braking system as 
the train neared the truck, but said he didn't remember whether 
lights at the crossing were flashing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
