<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Savannah Protecting Historic Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) -- Thousands were evacuated Tuesday from this  
coastal city to escape Hurricane Floyd, leaving behind Georgia's 
most picturesque and historic downtown, with its antebellum 
mansions, lush public squares and century-old oaks dripping with 
Spanish moss. 
</P>
<P>
	Savannah's haunting beauty makes it Georgia's second most  
popular tourist destination, behind Stone Mountain. Tourists come 
to visit places they have read about in ``Midnight in the Garden of 
Good and Evil'' or seen in movies such as ``Forrest Gump.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So while city officials said their first concern was moving  
residents safely inland, they also acknowledged that saving 
historic Savannah was priority No. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``A whole lot of people are really worried right now that the  
character of the city will not be the same,'' said City Manager 
Michael Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	The Georgia Emergency Management Agency predicted Floyd would  
rake Savannah and other coastal cities with 125 mph winds late 
Wednesday, with the eye of the storm passing over Tybee Island 20 
miles to the east. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the stately antebellum homes in the historic district  
were unprotected by plywood or duct tape. Residents said the 
downtown layout, with homes huddled close together around the 
squares, would shield them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I figure if it's been here over 100 years and it's withstood  
it without any problems, it'll probably withstand this one -- 
hopefully,'' said Dr. David Thomas, an obstetrician-gynecologist 
drinking orange juice on the steps of his three-story, 1889 home on 
Montery Square. 
</P>
<P>
	Businesses, hotels and homes built in the 1800s were shuttered  
and boarded. Museums packed away their china and other fragile 
artifacts. 
</P>
<P>
	At Bonaventure Cemetery, featured on the cover of ``Midnight in  
the Garden of Good and Evil,'' a few people removed statues from 
the graves of relatives. Bonaventure, where songwriter Johnny 
Mercer and other leading citizens of Savannah are buried, sits on 
the Savannah River and could flood. 
</P>
<P>
	The monument for Revolutionary War hero Casimir Pulaski, which  
had been on display at the Coastal Heritage Museum, was put in 
storage. 
</P>
<P>
	On Lafayette Square, workers rushed to remove 112 feet of  
scaffolding from the twin spires of St. John the Baptist Cathedral, 
Savannah's oldest cathedral at 200-plus years. The scaffolding was 
erected to repair the church's stucco surface. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess it's like losing a child. We put a lot of hard work  
into getting that stuff up there and it's kind of tough to have to 
watch them have to take it down,'' said foreman Don Green. 
</P>
<P>
	Other historic sites include the house where Girl Scouts of  
America founder Juliette Gordon Low was born in 1860, and the 
former Cotton Exchange building, where traders set world cotton 
prices from the 1880s until the 1930s. 
</P>
<P>
	Chatham County ordered all 250,000 residents to evacuate before  
Tuesday afternoon. A few people remained in the historic district. 
Some were boarding up their businesses before leaving town. Others 
were bellying up to the bars. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm trying to get all the drunks out of here so I can leave  
myself,'' said Patsy Williams, bartender at McDonough's Bar. 
</P>
<P>
	Savannah's historic district sits on a bluff above the Savannah  
River, 20 miles inland and high enough to keep most of downtown 
from flooding, city officials said. Their main worry was that wind 
and debris could breach old homes and buildings, letting water seep 
in from heavy rains. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Savannah residents worried most about damage to the  
towering oaks that give the city some of its distinctive natural 
beauty. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know a majority of the trees will be gone. And that's what  
we're known for,'' said Natalie Allmon, who was boarding up windows 
at the Planters Inn, where she is general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	City officials expect many of the oaks will stand up to the  
storm. Many were planted in the 1890s, and the city went through 
five years ago and removed trees that were dead or dying. 
</P>
<P>
	Savannah wasn't the only place in Georgia worried about  
protecting its historic buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers on Jekyll Island shuttered the ``millionaire cottages''  
built by the Rockefellers and Pulitzers and shut off power and 
water to the mansions. 
</P>
<P>
	At Fort McAllister, where Gen. William T. Sherman ended his  
March to the Sea after burning Atlanta, state workers removed 
military artifacts, including small arms and artillery shells. 
</P>
<P>
	On St. Simons Island, resident James Armstrong, 61, said he  
wasn't worried about the historic lighthouse, which survived a 
powerful hurricane in the 1800s. Gleaming white, it stands 
overlooking the Atlantic Ocean and the Port of Brunswick. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ain't nothing going to happen to that lighthouse,'' he said.  
``In fact, that's a good place to hide.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
