<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Moving Fast on E. Timor Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council is moving fast to  
draft a resolution authorizing deployment of an international force 
to East Timor and troops could be on the ground by the weekend, 
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Annan met the foreign ministers of Indonesia, Portugal and  
Australia, and Britain offered a draft resolution authorizing a 
multinational force for East Timor at a hurriedly called Security 
Council meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think we should just keep going until it's done,'' U.S.  
Ambassador Richard Holbrooke told reporters before the Security 
Council meeting started today. 
</P>
<P>
	At Indonesia's request, the draft says the force will operate  
under a unified command. But Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas 
told reporters the U.N.-authorized international force would be in 
command on the ground, with Indonesian troops playing an advisory 
and liaison role. 
</P>
<P>
	East Timor independence advocate and Nobel Peace Prize winner  
Jose Ramos Horta demanded today that Indonesia withdraw all troops 
from the territory, saying their presence is likely to ignite a 
bloodbath. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once we have an international force on the ground and  
Indonesian troops are still there, it's going to be impossible to 
control the emotions of our people. The security must be entirely, 
exclusively in the hands of the multinational force,'' he told 
reporters before the council meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	But Alatas said Indonesian soldiers would not be withdrawn  
immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	Militiamen in East Timor began their rampage after results were  
announced Sept. 4 from a U.N.-supervised ballot on the future of 
the former Portuguese colony, which Indonesia invaded in 1975. 
Voters overwhelmingly chose independence. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the draft resolution, the multinational force will  
have a four-month mandate. It will be charged with securing order, 
facilitating humanitarian assistance when possible and with 
protecting the U.N. mission in Dili, East Timor's provincial 
capital. The U.N. evacuated all but a skeleton staff to the 
northern Australian city of Darwin early today. 
</P>
<P>
	With a growing humanitarian crisis and looting, burning and  
violence continuing in East Timor, pressure intensified for quick 
agreement on the composition and mandate of the force and its 
leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope to have elements on the ground by the weekend,'' Annan  
told reporters this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well we hope so too,'' said Alatas as he arrived at the United  
Nations for another meeting with Annan. 
</P>
<P>
	Annan and Alatas agreed Monday to move ahead as quickly as  
possible following Indonesia's decision Sunday to ask multinational 
troops for help, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said. 
</P>
<P>
	The secretary-general hopes to work out details of the  
deployment by late today, Eckhard said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want the quickest decision possible (by the Security  
Council), today, probably tomorrow,'' said Portugal's Foreign 
Minister Jaime Gama. ``We need very quick action ...to restore 
security and avoid the atrocities and killings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alatas said he wanted to discuss the composition and command of  
the multinational force with Annan, reiterating that Indonesia 
preferred participation by fellow countries in the Association of 
Southeast Asian Nations, but stressing ``we have no 
conditionalities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Annan has asked Australia to lead the force, but Indonesia's  
armed forces and a parliamentary committee have voiced strong 
objections. 
</P>
<P>
	Alatas met with Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer at  
the United Nations today and said afterwards that Australia is 
``the party that is the best prepared to send their contribution of 
troops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Australia has assembled 4,500 soldiers and equipment on 24-hour  
alert in Darwin, an hour's flight from East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Security Council resolution drafted by Britain would deploy  
the multinational force under Chapter 7 of the U.N. Charter, which 
would authorize the use of force to restore law and order in East 
Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	It calls for an immediate end to the violence by armed militia  
and Indonesian security forces and for a halt to the forced 
displacement of East Timorese. It demands that those responsible be 
brought to justice, stressing that ``persons committing such 
violations bear individual responsibility.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
