<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Past USOC Chief Simon Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Calling it ``one of the great honors of my  
life,'' former U.S. Olympic Committee president William Simon 
received the USOC's second Gen. Douglas MacArthur Award on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Simon, 71, headed the USOC from 1980-84, taking over after the  
boycott of the 1980 Moscow Games and running the organization 
during the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 1984 Summer Games will go down in history as the most  
successful of all,'' Simon said during a luncheon. 
</P>
<P>
	He was lauded by Nancy Kissinger, the wife of former Secretary  
of State Henry Kissinger, and by former Olympic swimmer Donna de 
Varona, a former USOC board member. 
</P>
<P>
	New York Yankees owner George Steinbrenner, a former USOC vice  
president, was scheduled to speak but canceled because of Hurricane 
Floyd, which is approaching Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only person that's ever tamed George Steinbrenner is Bill  
Simon,'' de Varona said. 
</P>
<P>
	The MacArthur Award was first given last year, when it was  
presented to two members of the 1936 U.S. Olympic track team, Marty 
Glickman and the late Sam Stoller. The pair, the only Jewish 
athletes on the U.S. team at the Berlin Games, were replaced on the 
400-meter relay squad at the last minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, former USOC marketing head John Krimsky, who attended the  
luncheon, said he will be be part of a task force to raise the $125 
million still needed for the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	Krimsky quit in April to become president of Relationship  
Management Programs Inc., which runs United Airlines' senior 
frequent-flier program. He said Peter Larson, the chairman and CEO 
of Brunswick bowling, and Xerox CEO Paul Allaire will be on the 
task force. 
</P>
<P>
	Krimsky's old job was split in two after he left.  
</P>
<P>
	Marilyn Dunn was hired last month as deputy executive director  
for development and will be responsible for individual donations. 
She had been with the the University of Washington for 24 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Ogrean, the USOC's deputy executive director for marketing,  
is in responsible for corporate sponsorships. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
