<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Cable News Stresses Content </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A new generation of local cable newscasts is  
helping to change the image of local television news as shallow and 
crime-sodden. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the cable news operations that have sprung up quickly in  
the past few years are trying to compete with bigger broadcasters 
by emphasizing substance over sizzle, a study concludes. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the best news channels, like Las Vegas One and New York  
One, pack more information into their newscasts than broadcast 
network affiliates, said a report by Rocky Mountain Media Watch. 
</P>
<P>
	The media watchdog group has criticized local broadcast  
newscasts throughout the 1990s for heavily emphasizing crime news 
and entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I sense that a lot of people in the industry feel that the  
traditional local newscast is vulnerable to change,'' Paul Klite, 
the group's executive director, said Tuesday. ``The old format has 
gotten tiresome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Klite's group studied the newscasts of 21 cable stations on a  
fairly typical news day -- June 23, 1999. Overall, the programs had 
more news stories and fewer commercials than local newscasts did 
when measured in a separate, similar study. The cable newscasts had 
25 percent less news about violent crime, Klite said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable news operations generally have fewer soft features, less  
banter between anchors, and are also more willing to try different 
approaches, such as doing four short weather forecasts in an hour. 
Many cable newscasts feature one anchor instead of two, possibly 
because it's cheaper, Klite said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report cited Cable Pulse 24, a Toronto news station, as  
``without a doubt the most information-packed newscast in North 
America.'' Its screen is divided into seven separate information 
windows that deliver stock figures, sports scores, news headlines, 
the time, local weather, local traffic and a traditional newscast. 
</P>
<P>
	The newscast takes up 35 percent of the screen. Many stories ran  
for two minutes, unusually long in local news, and covered the 
environment, financial news, politics and health. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sort of grew out of looking at an Internet screen,'' said  
Stephen Hurlbut, the station's vice president and general manager. 
``We seem to be evolving into a culture that can process multiple 
sources of information at the same time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While some viewers initially responded negatively when the  
format was introduced a year and a half ago, it is now popular and 
imitated, mostly in Canada, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Not all cable stations followed the trend, the report said.  
Miami station WAMI's twice-nightly newscast, while trying to 
present an alternative to crime-heavy local broadcasts, 
concentrated on ``fluff'' like celebrity gossip and relationship 
advice, Klite said. 
</P>
<P>
	WAMI complained the media watchdog group studied a newscast that  
was not typical, Klite said. WAMI's news director did not 
immediately return a telephone call on Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
