<HEADLINE> LPGA To Play in Hawaii Twice  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- Hawaii will play host to a second women's golf  
tournament, the LPGA Takefuji Classic, in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Takefuji Corp., a Japanese consumer finance company, announced  
Tuesday a 3-year sponsorship agreement for the 54-hole event which 
will be held March 2-4 at the Kona Country Club on the island of 
Hawaii. 
</P>
<P>
	The full-field event will include 130 tour players, plus two  
sponsor exemptions. Two Japanese regulars on the LPGA Tour, Hiromi 
Kobayashi and Akiko Fukushima, are expected to compete for the 
$800,000 in prize money. 
</P>
<P>
	However, another big name Japanese star, Mayumi Hirose, is not  
expected to compete because of the start of the Japan LPGA Tour 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	On the LPGA Tour calendar, the Takefuji Classic will follow the  
Hawaiian Ladies Open at Kapolei and the tour's one-time stop in 
Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Takefuji president and chief executive officer Yasuo Takei said  
the tournament ``opens the door to not only American players, but 
also other top players from Europe, South America, Asia and 
Oceania.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tournament will be telecast to Japan via TV-Tokyo.  
Negotiations are continuing with The Golf Channel for showing in 
the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the two LPGA tournaments, Hawaii plays host to  
the PGA's Mercedes Championships, Sony Classic and PGA Grand Slam 
of Golf and the Senior PGA Tour's Kaanapali Classic, MasterCard 
Championship and Senior Skins. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
