<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Emmy Voters Gunshy on 'Sopranos' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *AP Photo NY129    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The Sopranos'' may have been the critical  
darling of the Emmys, but the mafia drama faced enough hurdles to 
fill the trunk of a mobster's car by the time the ceremony rolled 
around. 
</P>
<P>
	The HBO series about a New Jersey crime family led the field  
with 16 nominations yet came away with just four Emmys, two at the 
Sunday awards show and two technical awards given earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first cable program nominated for best dramatic  
series, but lost to last year's winner, ABC's legal drama ``The 
Practice.'' David E. Kelley, creator of ``The Practice,'' also went 
home with the award for best comedy series, ``Ally McBeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Sopranos'' went into the awards with great reviews and  
hardcore fans among HBO subscribers. But its dark tone and cast of 
unsavory characters may not have played well with television 
academy voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``What drives the shows that win Emmys is sentiment,'' said  
Thomas O'Neil, author of ``The Emmys.'' ``The thing that makes 'The 
Sopranos' work so well is cynicism, not sentiment, while David E. 
Kelley is a master of sentiment and impacting voters and grabbing 
hold of voters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Emmy voters generally look for characters and situations they  
can relate to, and a mob drama laced with graphic violence and 
profanity doesn't quite fit the bill, O'Neil said. 
</P>
<P>
	David Chase, creator and producer of ``The Sopranos,'' said  
Monday the show ``does flaunt some pretty basic rules about 
television, like the likeability factor. I don't know that our 
characters are very huggable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The series had five acting nominations, yet won just one -- for  
the most upright ``Sopranos'' character. Edie Falco, who plays a 
soul-searching mob wife, took home the award for best actress in a 
drama series. 
</P>
<P>
	``Emmy voters in general want to like who they're voting for,''  
O'Neil said. ``Look who did win. Edie Falco, the woman who is the 
moral center of that series, the moral center of that immoral 
world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other major award ``The Sopranos'' won Sunday was for  
dramatic writing, a category the series dominated with four of the 
five nominations. 
</P>
<P>
	Voters who pick Emmy winners also tend to gravitate more toward  
the familiar and traditional. The three other drama nominees, 
``NYPD Blue,'' ``ER'' and ``Law &AMP; Order,'' all have been perpetual 
nominees, and each has won the dramatic series award in past years. 
</P>
<P>
	Veteran series also dominated the acting awards, with such  
perennial winners as Dennis Franz of ``NYPD Blue'' and Helen Hunt 
of ``Mad About You'' going home with more awards. 
</P>
<P>
	``The television academy membership does tend to be reasonably  
conservative in terms of embracing new media,'' said Gerald 
Isenberg, a former producer who is a film and television professor 
at the University of Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Albrecht, HBO president of original programming, said  
there may have been some backlash against ``The Sopranos'' because 
of the wide press coverage the show had gained. The explicit 
violence, language and sex also may have worked against the series, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``More than likely there are people who are offended by some of  
that content when they're in the voting room,'' Albrecht said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet even ``The Practice'' creator Kelley conceded afterward that  
he had gone into the Emmys with a hunch ``The Sopranos'' would win 
best drama. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's such a terrific show,'' Kelley said. ``I don't think  
it's one that approximates anything that I've seen before on 
television or anything that I've done before.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
