<DOCNO> APW19990914.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 19:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holan's Comeback Ends With Thrashers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Milos Holan, attempting to return to the NHL four  
years after being diagnosed with leukemia, was released Tuesday by 
the Atlanta Thrashers. 
</P>
<P>
	Holan, 28-year-old defenseman, was among nine players cut by the  
Thrashers before their exhibition game at St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Forwards Kirby Law, Sean Ritchlin, Bryan Adams, Reggie Berg and  
Jeff Martin; defensemen Lawrence Nycholat; and goalie Scott 
Fankhouser were assigned to the Thrashers' minor-league affiliate, 
the Orlando Solar Bears of the International Hockey League. 
</P>
<P>
	Defenseman Mike Muzechka was returned to his junior team, the  
Tri-City Americans of the Western Hockey League. 
</P>
<P>
	Holan was formally assigned to Vitkovice, the team in his native  
Czech Republic where he played last season. But he already had said 
he would retire as a player if he didn't make it with the 
Thrashers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just doing my best and then I will see what happens,''  
Holan said last week. ``If that's good enough, I'll stay. If not, 
I'll go home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He had not played in the NHL since undergoing a high-risk  
bone-marrow transplant during the 1995-96 season, a few months 
after he was diagnosed with leukemia during a routine physical 
while playing for the Anaheim Mighty Ducks. 
</P>
<P>
	Holan was hospitalized for eight months and lost 60 pounds while  
enduring numerous complications involving his heart, kidney and 
gall bladder. He missed two full seasons before attempting a 
comeback with the Mighty Ducks last year, but was cut without ever 
playing an exhibition game. 
</P>
<P>
	Holan was part of the Thrashers' traveling roster for two  
exhibition games last weekend, but he didn't make enough of an 
impression to earn a longer look. Defense is already is one of the 
team's strongest positions. 
</P>
<P>
	Holan plans to go into coaching in the Czech Republic, where he  
will rejoin his wife, Irena, and their two children: 7-year-old 
Veronica and 3-year-old Milos Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	The Thrashers have 44 players remaining in camp. They will cut  
that number in half prior to their first regular-season game, Oct. 
2 against New Jersey. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 15:50:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Top Jockey Gall To Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLLINSVILLE, Ill. (AP) -- Dave Gall, fourth on the jockeys'  
career victory list with 7,389, said Tuesday he will retire at the 
end of the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The 57-year-old Gall has been racing at Fairmount Park near St.  
Louis since 1959. Gall, who led the country in victories in 1979, 
trails only Willie Shoemaker, Laffit Pincay Jr. and Pat Day on the 
career list. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's about time, isn't it?'' said Gall, whose last day of  
racing will be Saturday night. ``It's been a long, long time. I 
decided early this spring that I was going to finish the meet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gall said he would train horses next year and ``do other  
things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what I can do well,'' he said. ``I haven't done  
anything else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gall has been slowed by injuries in recent years, including a  
broken jaw, ankle and collarbone. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll enjoy not having to be here at exactly the right times  
and all that,'' Gall said. ``I've only been taking vacations when I 
get hurt, and that's not much fun.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 14:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Kurt Warner Impresses Rams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- When the quarterback went down at Central  
Florida, his center knew the team was in big trouble. When the same 
thing happened with the St. Louis Rams, center Mike Gruttadauria 
had exactly the opposite feeling. 
</P>
<P>
	Gruttadauria just knew untested Kurt Warner would be fine, and  
he was right about Sunday's opener. Warner threw for 309 yards and 
three touchdowns in his first career start as the Rams beat 
Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	``The second-teamer came in and he was a freshmman and he just  
was tripping over his words,'' Gruttadauria said of his college 
experience. ``Kurt, he comes in like he's been running this offense 
and we don't have anything to worry about. Business as usual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Warner led NFL Europe, which has a 10-game season, with 2,101  
yards passing and 15 touchdowns for the Amsterdam Admirals in 1998. 
Before that, he amassed 10,164 yards and 183 touchdowns in three 
seasons for the Iowa Barnstormers of the Arena Football League. 
Before that, he was the Gateway Conference player of the year at 
Northern Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	But before this season he had thrown only 11 NFL passes in a  
mop-up role in last year's finale, and had only one preseason start 
to get ready after Trent Green went out with a season-ending knee 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	After the opener, he's not such an unknown anymore. Warner got a  
game ball and tears of joy from coach Dick Vermeil, whose gamble 
not to sign a veteran backup before training camp seems to have 
paid off. 
</P>
<P>
	``His overall composure and awareness in all phases of what he  
was doing was far better than anybody could expect,'' Vermeil said. 
``There are a lot of quarterbacks that were first-round picks that 
have been given all the opportunities, all the coaching, all the 
money, all the everything, and they're on their third team -- and 
they're still going to fail -- because they don't have that 
composure, that poise under pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And that humility. The first thing Warner said to his teammates  
after the game was an apology of sorts. He told them he'd get 
better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to read too much into this one, because I know I  
made some mistakes out there,'' said Warner, who was intercepted 
twice -- one was not his fault -- and lost a fumble. ``But it does 
give you a lot of confidence to go out and get a victory, and to 
make some plays. I always believed I could be here and that I could 
do this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Warner, 28, admitted to a few anxious moments after Green was  
injured Aug. 28 and the job fell into his lap. He said recently 
he's been waking up in the middle of the night and thinking about 
what exactly he'd do on third-and-5 with the blitz coming. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the anxiety vanished the night before, and take it from  
Gruttadauria, the hands that reached down for the ball were not 
shaking at any time. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has that innate confidence that guys just respect,''  
Gruttadauria said. ``When he's in the huddle, he does all the 
little things that make you feel good and make you want to 
follow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Warner has often said he needs to be a facilitator as much as a  
playmaker. The Rams are loaded with speedy receivers like Isaac 
Bruce (eight catches for 92 yards and a TD), Torry Holt (three for 
34 and a TD) and Az Hakim (five for 63), plus he has the 
multidimensional Marshall Faulk (72 yards receiving, 54 yards 
rushing). 
</P>
<P>
	Warner's passing yardage was adjusted from 316 yards after the  
Elias Sports Bureau reviewed the game. It's the third-highest 
yardage total by a rookie in the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to help Kurt,'' Bruce said. ``He hasn't been in that  
situation before and it's up to guys like myself to help Kurt out, 
so he doesn't have the feeling he's the only general on the 
field.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 14:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
