<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Said Spending $47B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler AG reportedly plans to invest  
$47 billion over the next three years to develop and produce new 
cars and trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	The German-American automaker was expected to unveil the plan  
Tuesday at the Frankfurt International Motor Show, the Financial 
Times of London reported in Tuesday's editions, citing an internal 
company document. Excerpts from the report were released by the 
newspaper's New York office on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan calls for DaimlerChrysler to roll out 64 new passenger  
cars and commercial vehicle models by 2004, the newspaper said. 
That would average about one new model a month. 
</P>
<P>
	The new models could include versions of its `Smart' two-seater  
and a mid-size Chrysler car for Europe, the Times said. 
</P>
<P>
	The optimistic outlook is based on better-than-expected cost  
savings realized following last year's merger of Diamler-Benz and 
Chrysler, the newspaper said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
