<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cowboys' Coryatt Retires Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- The injury-plagued career of Quentin  
Coryatt ended Tuesday with the linebacker telling the Dallas 
Cowboys he won't be joining them this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Coryatt, whom Indianapolis took with the No. 2 pick in the 1992  
draft, sat out last season after being released by the Colts late 
in training camp to try and get over the aches and pains that had 
dogged him for years. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas wanted to sign him last fall, but waited until April. He  
was immediately penciled in as the starting strongside linebacker. 
</P>
<P>
	But the former Texas A&AMP;M star never even made it into an  
exhibition game. He reaggravated an old Achilles' tendon problem 
and also was having trouble with his surgically reconstructed left 
shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're obviously disappointed,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones  
said. ``I respect his decision. He's been an outstanding football 
player throughout college and the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our plans were for him to really make an impact for us  
defensively, so we'll be challenged to pick up the slack without 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said the team is not in the market for a linebacker,  
meaning they will stick with second-year player Darren Hambrick, 
who has been playing the strong side. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Chan Gailey said Hambrick played fine Sunday in Dallas'  
season-opening victory over Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``He made a few things happen,'' Gailey said. ``For the most  
part he played fairly well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys lost Coryatt the same day they learned Pro Bowl  
defensive tackle Leon Lett will miss seven more games as punishment 
for his fifth violation of the league's substance abuse policy. 
Dallas also is waiting for cornerbacks Deion Sanders and Kevin 
Smith to return from injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Technically, Coryatt hasn't retired -- yet. His agent, Stephen  
Zucker, was working out the financial arrangements with the Cowboys 
before the team made a roster move. 
</P>
<P>
	Zucker said the 29-year-old Coryatt was disappointed things  
didn't work out because he enjoyed being in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	``He told me earlier that he wished he'd found the Cowboys when  
he was coming out of college,'' Zucker said. ``He loved it. He 
tried as hard as he could.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
