<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Web Site Offers Direct Car Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- In another step toward selling cars over the  
Internet, a new Web site allows car buyers to pick out specific 
cars from a dealer's inventory and agree to a price online. 
</P>
<P>
	Unveiled Monday, Uautobid.com is one of several sites vying for  
online car buyers, competing against companies such as Autoweb.com, 
Microsoft Corp.'s CarPoint, Autobytel.com Inc. and major 
automakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Several sites allow consumers to get online bids from  
participating dealers on new cars and trucks. After a request for a 
price is submitted, the dealer contacts the consumer and handles 
the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	A few sites, including CarsDirect.com and megadealer  
AutoNation's new Web site, AutoNationDirect.com, also try to sell 
cars directly to online buyers. Customers choose a make and model, 
then agree to a price online. The sites then find vehicles that 
match those terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Uautobid, based in New York, links buyers with a specific  
vehicle on a dealer's lot. Dealers who post cars on the site have 
agreed to sell the vehicle for a certain price. When a customer 
submits a bid that meets the price, the purchase is confirmed with 
a $250 deposit. The customer then has 48 hours to finish the deal 
at the dealer. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers bid based on a suggested retail price or in an  
auction. They will not see the selling price agreed to by the 
dealer. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is a venture of Interstate National Dealer Services  
Inc., which sells service contracts and extended warranties to 
vehicle dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	James McQuivey, a senior analyst at Forrester Research Inc.,  
said his firm estimates that by 2003, about 500,000 vehicles will 
be bought directly over the Internet out of 16 million sold 
nationwide. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
