<DOCNO> APW19990914.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 10:45:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corinth Museum Pieces Found in Fla. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- More than 200 ancient objects stolen from  
a Corinth museum nine years ago were found in a Florida storage 
area by the FBI and Greek authorities, Greece's culture minister 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was one of the biggest, if not the biggest, antiquities  
thefts,'' Culture Minister Elisavet Papazoi said. ``We are happy 
that they were found in good condition, and they will soon be back 
in Greece.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Acting on a tip last week, authorities discovered all but three  
of the 271 stolen objects. They were wrapped in plastic and masking 
tape and hidden in fish crates in a storage area in Miami, Athens 
Police Chief Pavlos Roubis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Roubis would not give any details of the exact location or  
provide further details of the bust. No arrests have been made. 
</P>
<P>
	Archaeologists on Monday identified the antiquities as those  
stolen in April 1990 from the Archaeology Museum in Corinth, 50 
miles southwest of Athens. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, police said at least four people broke into the  
building, tied up the guard, cleaned out most of the museum's 
displays, loaded the objects onto trucks and disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like moving a whole museum,'' Papazoi said. The museum  
has since been fitted with an alarm system. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, the Greek culture ministry received information that  
the stolen artifacts had been transported to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The stolen antiquities include such rare pieces as a 5th century  
B.C. marble head of a young man known as a Kouros; a small marble 
statue of Pan, the pastoral god of fertility; 13 marble sculpted 
heads dating back to the Hellenistic and Roman periods; and 164 
varied pouring vessels, urns and wine jugs. 
</P>
<P>
	The three items still missing are a marble bust of Julius  
Caesar, thought to have been carved after his death in 44 B.C., and 
carved marble heads of Eros and the Ptolemaic god Serapis. 
</P>
<P>
	The antiquities were taken to FBI offices in New York and should  
be returned to Greece within two months, Papazoi said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 22:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Drafts Pesticide Regulations / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- With a big judicial nudge, California  
pesticide regulators are drafting the first statewide regulations 
governing the use of methyl bromide, a fumigant treasured by 
farmers but poisonous to humans. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a court order, the state Department of Pesticide  
Regulation must shape a set of formal guidelines by June 2000, 
incorporating public opinion and the views of other stakeholders 
throughout the rule-making process. 
</P>
<P>
	A coalition of environmental groups, which in a lawsuit accused  
the agency of failing to obey a 10-year-old state law requiring 
clear, uniform and enforceable regulations, wanted a quicker 
timetable. 
</P>
<P>
	But, the groups say they are encouraged that DPR Director Paul  
E. Helliker has actively solicited watchdog groups for input as his 
department formulates a plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Helliker ``is making steps in the right direction for reducing  
the impact of toxins in California,'' said Susan Kegley, a staff 
scientist for the Pesticide Action Network in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	Methyl bromide, an odorless, colorless gas, is used worldwide,  
mostly by strawberry and tomato growers, to purge soil of insects, 
mites, rodents and weeds before plantings. A potent pest killer 
also used by exterminators, the fumigant is highly poisonous to 
humans and has been blamed for damaging the Earth's protective 
ozone layer. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the most recent state data, 361 people were  
definitely or probably poisoned by methyl bromide from 1982 to 
1996; of these, 248 involved farm uses. Environmentalists believe 
the toll is much greater because many people suffering from 
pesticide poisoning assume they have the flu or another common 
ailment. 
</P>
<P>
	The chemical also has caused 19 deaths since 1982, all of them  
occurring off farms, when people entered fumigated buildings before 
the gas had dissipated. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an amendment to the Clean Air Act, the pesticide must be  
reduced 25 percent this year in the United States, 50 percent in 
2001, 70 percent in 2003, and fully banned by 2005. Millions of 
public and private dollars are being spent in a race to find an 
alternative before the phase-out. 
</P>
<P>
	California already has the strictest system for regulating  
highly toxic pesticides. It's the only state requiring users of 
such materials to obtain both special training and site-specific 
permits from county agricultural commissioners. 
</P>
<P>
	But a main contention in the lawsuit against DPR was that permit  
guidelines could be changed without notice and that enforcement was 
subject to local discretion, leaving too many inconsistencies. 
</P>
<P>
	To remedy the problem, the DPR announced Monday that it may  
force methyl bromide users to provide buffer zones around schools 
and neighborhoods. The agency also is reevaluating whether 
statewide rules are needed for other high-risk pesticides. 
</P>
<P>
	DPR must submit proposed regulations to the Office of  
Administrative Law by the end of the year. A formal comment period 
is required for public input. And the state must submit regular 
reports to the judge until he determines the agency has complied. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we'd like to do is get a lot of input from a lot of  
people before we propose anything,'' said DPR spokeswoman Veda 
Federighi. ``That way we can put them in place more quickly.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 08:00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pacific Century To Cut 1,015 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- The parent company of Hawaii's largest bank  
plans to cut 1,015 positions, or one-fifth of its work force, as 
part of a corporate restructuring aimed at boosting its sagging 
stock. 
</P>
<P>
	But Pacific Century Financial Corp. officials said Monday that  
fewer than 266 workers actually will lose their jobs since most of 
the reductions will come from a hiring freeze begun last year, 
early retirement and attrition. 
</P>
<P>
	The Honolulu-based corporation expects to generate $21 million a  
year in new revenue and save $43 million annually in operating 
expenses when the redesign is fully implemented by the fourth 
quarter of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The corporation's board also authorized the repurchase of up to  
300,000 shares of common stock per quarter beginning in the fourth 
quarter of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Pacific Century, a $14.6 billion financial services company  
whose main subsidiary is Bank of Hawaii, employs 5,200 people in 
Hawaii, California, Arizona, Asia, Guam, the Northern Mariana 
Islands and the South Pacific. 
</P>
<P>
	About 80 percent of the 1,015 targeted positions are in Hawaii.  
The remaining 20 percent are in the Western Pacific and Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	``In today's world, it's all about creating value and being able  
to compete globally, and for many years here in Hawaii I don't 
believe that companies had to worry too much about value and 
competing globally,'' said Lawrence Johnson, chairman and chief 
executive of Pacific Century and Bank of Hawaii. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
