<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 13:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Gov'ts Ignore IMF Warnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Critics often blame the International Monetary  
Fund for failing to predict or prevent financial crises, but a new 
report concludes that governments do not heed IMF warnings designed 
to fend off economic turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
	But the independent report, commissioned by the agency, says IMF  
monitoring of the economies of its 182 member nations has failed to 
keep pace with the globalization of financial markets and the 
increased importance of billions of dollars moving around the world 
every day. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF assembled a group of experts headed by John Crow, former  
governor of the Bank of Canada, to look at IMF economic monitoring, 
or ``surveillance,'' in 12 countries and recommend how to improve 
the process. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12 countries included Thailand, where the global financial  
crisis began in July 1997, Korea and Brazil. All received 
multibillion dollar IMF rescue packages as their economies neared 
collapse over the next 20 months. 
</P>
<P>
	One problem the report found is that the IMF lacks the political  
clout to enforce its recommendations. As an international financial 
institution, it recommends remedial actions to keep countries out 
of economic trouble but can't force them to act. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a disjunction between what the rest of the world  
thinks the IMF can do'' in a crisis ``and what insiders think,'' 
Crow said, presenting the report at a news conference a week before 
the Washington-based IMF holds its annual meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``The IMF is never a primary influence, but it can play a role  
in a debate'' on what to do, he said. ``Political considerations 
almost always dominate over fund warnings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	These considerations can include an impending presidential  
election or a government protecting companies or individuals with 
whom it has close ties, a practice known as crony capitalism. 
</P>
<P>
	Crow also said the IMF was slow to apply in the Asian crisis in  
late 1997 lessons learned when the it stepped in to bail out Mexico 
in 1995 during the peso crisis, particularly involving 
vulnerabilities in domestic financial systems. 
</P>
<P>
	The report stressed ``the need to focus surveillance more  
directly on the international aspects of a country's situation, the 
linkages across countries and the lessons countries can learn from 
other experiences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It recommended that IMF surveillance should focus only its core  
specialty areas of exchange-rate policy and directly associated 
macroeconomic policies and leave social and labor issues to 
organizations such as the World Bank and the International Labor 
Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Both IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus and members of the  
IMF's executive board said the recommendation runs counter to 
demands of IMF members and the world at large. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional critics of the IMF, among others, have demanded  
that the agency increase emphasis on the interaction between 
economic policy and issues such as labor reform and protection of 
the environment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
