<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 15:21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thomas Looking To Add IBA to CBA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) -- A group headed by Isiah Thomas is  
negotiating to buy the nine-team International Basketball 
Association, league officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas, a former Detroit Pistons star in the NBA, purchased the  
nine-team CBA last month and now is eyeing the IBA, which has teams 
in Canada and six states. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a league, we are committed to trying to make our league the  
best it can be and high profile, and we're entertaining any kind of 
discussion that might be potentially beneficial to us,'' said Shawn 
Coates, communications director for the IBA in St. Paul, Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have approached us and we're open to any offer that helps  
our league to gain prominence or exposure,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Messages to Isiah International in Birmingham, Mich., weren't  
immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	IBA president Bill Sorensen, of Bismarck, N.D., said the deal  
could create a developmental league for the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	The parties won't reveal financial terms or other details until  
negotiations are completed, said Sorensen, the Bismarck mayor who 
is owner or part owner of two IBA teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas wants the IBA teams to maintain their ties to the  
community, Sorensen said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants the existing owners to have some minority ownership,  
so he has some local ties. We may not be out entirely, but we'll 
have to wait and see what unfolds,'' Sorensen said. 
</P>
<P>
	IBA teams are located at Rapid City, S.D.; Billings, Mont.; Des  
Moines, Iowa; Minot, N.D.; Bismarck, N.D.; Fargo, N.D.-Moorhead, 
Minn.; Rochester, Minn.; Youngstown, Ohio, and Winnipeg, Manitoba. 
</P>
<P>
	The IBA begins its fifth season in late November.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
