<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Teams Lining Up for Buckeyes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- From 1934 until 1992, Ohio State did not  
lower itself to play football against another school from within 
the state's boundaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, all of a sudden, the Buckeyes are the host of an unofficial  
Ohio college tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	For the next two weeks, the nation's 13th-ranked team gains  
little, but risks a lot when it welcomes Ohio University and the 
University of Cincinnati into Ohio Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	It'll be the first time the Buckeyes have played consecutive  
games against in-state schools since 1926. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State coach John Cooper is behind the good neighbor policy,  
but not because Ohio University is 0-2 and lost to Division I-AA 
Northern Iowa last week, while Cincinnati (1-1), 2-9 a year ago, 
lost to Troy State on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm in favor of it,'' Cooper said Monday. ``The philosophy to  
do it is good. It's keeping the money in the state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added, ``Of course, I like to play them at home, there's no  
question about that. I like to have another home game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Buckeyes have won their last 22 games against in-state  
schools, dating back to a 7-6 loss to Oberlin in 1921. That string 
includes two victories over Bowling Green and another over Toledo 
this decade -- by a combined score of 110-19 -- after athletics 
director Andy Geiger ended almost six decades of separation between 
Ohio State and other schools inside the border. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio University gets $350,000 and Cincinnati gets $200,000 in a  
deal where it makes three trips to Columbus, and Ohio State must 
come to Cincinnati once. Next year, Miami of Ohio visits Ohio 
Stadium, with Akron making the trip in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like they're not getting a benefit out of it,''  
Cooper said. ``Certainly, they're the underdog. But it's a good 
recruiting tool, it's good for their budget and it's also a great 
opportunity for those kids to get a chance to compete against a 
bigger team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio University coach Jim Grobe jumped at the chance to play the  
Buckeyes when it was proposed by athletics director Tom Boeh. In 
recent years, the Bobcats have had to travel to North Carolina, 
Kansas State and Wisconsin to get a big payoff. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Tom came to me, and Ohio State had offered to play us in  
football, I thought that was a no-brainer. I don't care how much 
money was involved,'' Grobe said. ``We have over 70 kids from the 
state of Ohio in our program. They would love to play that game. 
What a great experience for our program and our kids. I just 
thought it was an easy decision, and I appreciate Ohio State giving 
us an opportunity to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State (1-1), which ripped 14th-ranked UCLA 42-20 Saturday  
night, is a 40-point favorite. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're favored by 40 points, then let's get up on them by 40  
points then,'' offensive guard Ben Gilbert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State fullback Matt Keller, who may not play because of a  
sprained ankle, is a Cincinnati native who said he had an idea what 
the Bobcats will encounter. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got a lot of guys from Ohio,'' he said. ``They grew up  
watching Ohio State and it's going to be a great opportunity for 
them to play in from of a big crowd, and they'll have a lot of 
family there. That's a big motivating factor for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is no other in-state university of similar size or stature  
to Ohio State, such as Cincinnati would be in men's basketball. 
Cooper was asked if he would still be in favor of scheduling one if 
there was. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't touch that,'' he said with a grin.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
