<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Cable News Stresses Content </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hold the blood and guts. A new generation of  
local news programs on cable TV is trying to compete with bigger 
broadcasters by emphasizing substance over sizzle, a study 
concludes. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the best news channels, like Las Vegas One and New York  
One, pack more information into their newscasts than broadcast 
network affiliates, said a report by Rocky Mountain Media Watch. 
</P>
<P>
	The media watchdog group has criticized local broadcast  
newscasts throughout the 1990s for heavily emphasizing crime news 
and entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I sense that a lot of people in the industry feel that the  
traditional local newscast is vulnerable to change,'' Paul Klite, 
the group's executive director, said Tuesday. ``The old format has 
gotten tiresome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the past few years, there has been rapid growth in cable news  
operations, often running 24 hours a day. 
</P>
<P>
	Klite's group studied the newscasts of 21 cable stations on a  
fairly typical news day -- June 23, 1999. Overall, the programs had 
more news stories and fewer commercials than local newscasts did 
when measured in a separate, similar study. The cable newscasts had 
25 percent less news about violent crime, Klite said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable news operations generally have fewer soft features, less  
banter between anchors, and are also more willing to try different 
approaches, such as doing four short weather forecasts in an hour. 
Many cable newscasts feature one anchor instead of two, possibly 
because it's cheaper, Klite said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report cited Cable Pulse 24, a Toronto news station, as  
``without a doubt the most information-packed newscast in North 
America.'' Its screen is divided into seven separate information 
windows that deliver stock figures, sports scores, news headlines, 
the time, local weather, local traffic and a traditional newscast. 
</P>
<P>
	The news report takes up 35 percent of the screen. Many stories  
ran for two minutes, unusually long in local news, and covered the 
environment, financial news, politics and health. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sort of grew out of looking at an Internet screen,'' said  
Stephen Hurlbut, the station's vice president and general manager. 
``We seem to be evolving into a culture that can process multiple 
sources of information at the same time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While some viewers initially responded negatively when the  
format was introduced a year and a half ago, it is now popular and 
imitated, mostly in Canada, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Not all cable stations followed the trend, the report said.  
Miami station WAMI's twice-nightly newscast, while trying to 
present an alternative to crime-heavy local broadcasts, 
concentrated on ``fluff'' like celebrity gossip and relationship 
advice, Klite said. 
</P>
<P>
	WAMI complained the media watchdog group studied a newscast that  
was not typical, Klite said. WAMI's news director did not 
immediately return a telephone call on Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 02:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Close Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks closed lower Tuesday on concern the  
rising yen is threatening Japan's nascent economic recovery. The 
dollar fell to a 40-month low against the Japanese currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed down 132.07  
points, or 0.74 percent, to 17,777.22 at the end of the day's 
trading. On Monday, the average closed up 198.27 points, or 1.12 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 106.56 yen at midafternoon, down 1.22 yen from  
Tokyo's late Monday level of 107.78 yen, but above its late New 
York level of 106.44 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	In earlier Tokyo trading, the dollar moved as low as 106.00 yen,  
its lowest level since May 15, 1996, when it traded at 105.77 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices fell as the yen surged against the  
greenback, rekindling concern that Japan's fledging economic 
recovery could be curbed by the rising yen. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen leads to lower profits for Japan's exporters, since  
it makes their products more expensive and therefore less 
competitive overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Exporters were supposed to break even at 112 yen to the  
dollar,'' said Robert Sasaki, head of the quantitative strategy 
group at Jardine Fleming Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 566 million shares, down from 597 million shares 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Decliners outnumbered advancers 786 to 421, while 137 issues  
were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section closed down 10.44 points, or 0.68 percent, to 
1,524.79. The TOPIX closed up 20.37 points, or 1.34 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York overnight, the Dow Jones industrial average rose  
1.90 points to close Monday at 11,030.33. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, a low-key intervention in the foreign  
exchange market by the Bank of Japan gave the dollar a slight 
afternoon boost, but the greenback remains under downward pressure, 
dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign exchange traders say that the BOJ intervened via a few  
foreign banks and Japanese city banks. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank pushed the dollar up about 1 yen to around  
107.30 yen, said a dealer at a European bank in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ministry of Finance's top bureaucrat, Nobuaki Usui,  
confirmed that Japanese monetary authorities intervened in support 
of the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks, the yen has been in strong demand, especially  
by foreign investors who want to buy into Japanese financial 
markets amid hopes for an economic turnaround. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar traded between 106.00 yen and 107.30 yen in Tokyo  
trading on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 110.24 yen in late  
afternoon trading, down from 111.60 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.7100 percent from Monday's finish of 1.7600 percent, driving 
the price up 0.43 point to 101.62. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
