<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bengals' Smith Blames Self for Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- As he lay in bed the night after his first NFL  
game, Akili Smith was filled with remorse. 
</P>
<P>
	The quarterback wished he hadn't missed so much of training camp  
because of a contract holdout. He thought he'd let the Cincinnati 
Bengals down by not knowing the offense when they were on the verge 
of an exhilarating win. 
</P>
<P>
	He felt awful.  
</P>
<P>
	``This week I promise you it won't happen again,'' Smith said.  
</P>
<P>
	How is he going to keep his promise? By studying more.  
</P>
<P>
	The first-round draft choice missed virtually all of training  
camp. He signed less than two weeks before the season-opener in 
Tennessee and had a lot to learn. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though he still didn't know the playbook, the Bengals  
installed him as Jeff Blake's backup. The only other alternative 
was seventh-round draft pick Scott Covington. 
</P>
<P>
	When Blake went down with leg cramps in the fourth quarter  
Sunday in Tennessee, Smith made his debut and wasn't prepared. 
After two series without a first down, coach Bruce Coslet went to 
Covington for the final series because the other rookie knew the 
offense better. 
</P>
<P>
	Covington did no better, failing to get a first down, and the  
Titans rallied for a 36-35 win. 
</P>
<P>
	That's all Smith could think about that night.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was laying in bed thinking that I put a lot of pressure on  
myself,'' Smith said. ``I felt I lost a game for my team. This week 
I've got to step it up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't all his fault. The Bengals' decision not to keep an  
experienced backup quarterback put a lot of pressure on Smith, and 
the long holdout put him way behind. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the development of a young quarterback,'' Coslet said.  
``He has no idea what it takes to prepare for a football game. 
He'll learn it. Every quarterback has to go through this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith plans to spend a lot more time with the playbook.  
</P>
<P>
	``I guess I spend an hour and a half every night,'' Smith said.  
``I've got to step it up and go two or three hours. I've got to be 
ready to do a lot more studying.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
