<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> E. coli Outbreak Sickens 281 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- What did you eat? Where did you sit?  
Did you wash your hands? Did you wade in the pond? Who was with 
you? 
</P>
<P>
	Health investigators have been interviewing hundreds of people  
who attended a Sept. 4 concert and cookout, hoping some pattern 
will emerge to explain an E. coli outbreak that has now sickened at 
least 281 people. 
</P>
<P>
	While they work the phones, other health workers were performing  
lab tests or gathering samples. 
</P>
<P>
	All they know for sure is that the people who fell ill were  
among the 1,800 people at the event in a cow pasture near 
Petersburg. Twenty were sick enough that they had to be 
hospitalized. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe the E. coli bacteria lurked in the beef served at the  
event. Maybe bacteria was in the water, or on the hands of a food 
server, or hiding someplace else entirely. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're no different from detectives on a crime scene. We kind  
of tear apart everything we can to come up with the clues that may 
give us an answer,'' Thomas Schafer, spokesman for the Illinois 
Department of Public Health, said Monday. ``We still are going to 
have to be a little lucky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	E. coli is a bacteria usually found in the intestines or manure  
of cattle. People who ingest it can suffer severe cramps, bloody 
diarrhea and, in extreme cases, kidney failure. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest job for investigators is interviewing people who  
attended the concert, dubbed Cornstock '99. 
</P>
<P>
	Schafer said investigators have the names of about 900  
partygoers and have spoken to 551 -- asking what they ate and drank, 
where they sat, whether they washed their hands, what they did. 
</P>
<P>
	All the answers -- from sick people and healthy alike -- are fed  
into a computer that will search for patterns. If most of the sick 
people ate the same things or did the same things, it narrows the 
field, Schafer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other investigators were working in the field -- literally. They  
visited the farm near Petersburg, about 25 miles northwest of 
Springfield, where Cornstock was held to gather water and manure 
samples. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd at the free concert ate and drank in a field that had  
been used as a cow pasture. Owner Tom Baird had raked and cleaned 
the field of manure, although some traces probably remained. 
</P>
<P>
	But Schafer said those traces were unlikely to be the source of  
contamination, since E. coli will not survive long outside a host 
animal. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, investigators have taken manure samples from Baird's  
herd. If they were carrying E. coli, it suggests the contamination 
probably came from the cow Baird donated to be cooked at the event, 
Schafer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Results of the first tests won't be available until later this  
week, Schafer said. It could be weeks, or even months, before the 
health department finishes its investigation, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 17:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Voting on Campaign Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation to curb the influence of money in  
political campaigns moved toward likely House passage Tuesday night 
despite vociferous complaints from conservative Republicans that 
the bill violates freedom of speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reach and influence of special interests have grown out of  
control,'' argued Rep. Marge Roukema of New Jersey, one of numerous 
Republicans to join with Democrats in support of the measure. ``As 
a consequence, people believe their elected officials are bought 
and paid for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. John Doolittle, R-Calif., said the measure, with its  
ban on unregulated ``soft money'' contributions and restrictions on 
certain campaign ads, would ``abridge our precious God-given right 
to speak.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House Republican leadership backed efforts to derail the  
measure or rework it after concluding it could disadvantage GOP 
candidates and leave them vulnerable to attacks by organized labor. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the hours leading to a vote on final passage, supporters  
of the bill easily defeated what they described as ``poison pill'' 
amendments that threatened to unravel their bipartisan coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them were proposals to triple the 25-year-old limits on  
contributions, allowing donors to give up to $3,000 to individual 
candidates and $75,000 overall for any campaign cycle. Both were 
rejected by margins of more than 2-1, indicating that supporters of 
the legislation had the votes to prevail on the final roll call, as 
well. 
</P>
<P>
	One amendment that cleared would require non-office holders who  
campaign for office to reimburse the government for the costs of 
transportation. Democrats complained the provision was aimed solely 
at First lady Hillary Clinton, who is making the rounds in her 
unannounced New York Senate campaign with a complement of Secret 
Service agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Passage would mark the second time in as many years that  
campaign finance legislation, co-sponsored by Republican Rep. 
Christopher Shays of Connecticut and Democratic Rep. Martin Meehan 
of Massachusetts and backed by the White House, had cleared the 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, as in 1998, GOP opponents of the measure in the  
Senate are ready with a filibuster, and prospects for final passage 
are uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	As drafted in the House, the bill would ban the use of soft  
money in federal campaigns. Unlike hard money donations, which are 
restricted in size, soft money donations are unlimited and 
unregulated by the federal government. Increasingly, they are 
prized by political parties and certain politicians. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the bill would impose limits on certain types of  
political advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadcast commercials within 60 days of an election that made  
use of the name or likeness of a candidate would have to be paid 
for with hard money contributions, which are limited in size. So, 
too, would any print or broadcast commercial that contained an 
``unmistakable or unambiguous'' appeal for the election or defeat 
of a federal candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Those provisions are designed to crack down on thinly veiled  
attacks ads that are now paid for with soft money. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation produced a spirited debate on the House floor  
that ranged from bedrock constitutional issues to matters of overt 
partisan politics. 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Whip Tom DeLay argued that the measure  
represented ``the mother of all government regulation'' and would 
erode the First Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Roger Wicker of Mississippi agreed, and added that for  
``liberal advocates this bill is really about party politics. The 
big labor bosses use the forced dues of their union members to 
further their political goals,'' he added, and the legislation 
would do nothing to change that. 
</P>
<P>
	Meehan dismissed the complaints about the First Amendment as  
ungrounded. ``When they say free speech, they mean big money,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shays said the measure was designed to enforce a ban on  
corporate campaign donations that has been on the books since 1907, 
and a similar ban on the use of union dues dating to 1947. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Mike Castle, R-Del., said, ``It should concern every one of  
us that there are corporations, there are labor unions, there are 
organizations out there'' whose members make six-figure 
contributions. ``If anyone thinks they're doing it because they 
believe in good government, then they need to look at the 
underlying legislation they're supporting,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shays and Meehan had wanted to have the debate last spring, to  
give their Senate allies more time to battle the threatened 
filibuster there. 
</P>
<P>
	But House GOP leaders successfully delayed the measure, and  
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., stared down rebels in his own 
rank-and-file who had pressured him to step up the timetable. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind the scenes, the GOP hierarchy also emphasized the  
political threat to Republican candidates. The party chairman, Jim 
Nicholson, and Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, who heads the Republican 
campaign committee, met privately with GOP lawmakers last month and 
told them the party enjoyed a $40 million soft money advantage over 
Democrats in the 1997-1998 election cycle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
