<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Co. Sold Missile How-To to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The U.S. Defense Department will examine  
whether a Pennsylvania company damaged national security by selling 
technology to China that could help the accuracy of its missiles. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Attorney Michael Stiles said Defense officials will  
scrutinize the actions of Orbit/FR, which has agreed to plead 
guilty in U.S. District Court to violating the Arms Export Control 
Act. Papers declaring the company's intent were filed in court on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Orbit/FR, headquartered in Horsham, about 15 miles north of  
Philadelphia, will be fined $600,000 and could be banned from 
exporting products for up to 10 years, Stiles said. Charges against 
at least one company official are likely to follow, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The company had agreed to a $1 million deal with Chinese North  
Industries Corp., a major military systems manufacturer for the 
Chinese army. 
</P>
<P>
	The software and equipment sold to China were designed to  
measure the effectiveness of antennas in the nose cones of 
missiles. The system was capable of measuring accuracy within 10 
feet over a distance of 10 miles, said Joe Alkus, a Customs Service 
supervisor. 
</P>
<P>
	No money changed hands. Although the Chinese got the technology,  
it is not fully operational. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials would not discuss whether American security  
was compromised. But ``the results of this investigation have been 
turned over to the Defense Department to make that determination,'' 
Stiles said. 
</P>
<P>
	William A. Torzolini, the company's chief financial officer,  
declined to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Orbit/FR is owned primarily by Orbit-Alchut Technologies Ltd.,  
an Israeli company. The technology in question was originally 
developed for the Israeli armed forces, Stiles said. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
