<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Taxes Deemed Not Popular </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A commission made up of government and business  
representatives that is studying how to tax purchases over the 
Internet could hit some heavy public opposition, judging from a 
survey released on the first day of the group's meeting in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a third of registered voters who are active Internet  
users, or 36 percent, would be less likely to vote for a political 
candidate who supports taxes on Internet purchases, according to 
the poll, released Tuesday by the Gallup Organization and (at)plan, 
an online market research firm. All told, 73 percent of active 
Internet users oppose an Internet sales tax, compared to 14 percent 
in favor. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll also found that 58 percent believe taxing goods and  
services bought online would hurt the growth of Internet commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings suggest why the 19-member Advisory Commission on  
Electronic Commerce, created last year by Congress, remains divided 
on key issues seven months before it is scheduled to make tax 
policy recommendations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Registered voters are saying it may become an issue with  
political traction,'' said Mark Wright, chief executive of 
(at)plan, based in Stamford, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress formed the commission last October as it imposed a  
three-year moratorium on any new state or local taxes on Internet 
access or sales. The commission is composed of representatives from 
eight businesses, eight state and local governments and three 
appointed by the Clinton administration. The group has until next 
April to make recommendations, which could result in legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Many members of the group have voiced support for some form of  
taxation as long as the system makes it easy for companies to 
collect. Paramount among the considerations is gaining agreements 
from governments to adopt a single tax rate for each state, or to 
adopt new technologies that would allow businesses to figure out 
any tax rate. 
</P>
<P>
	But such a single-tax system could mean sweeping changes in how  
states and localities handle taxation. Currently, thousands of 
jurisdictions levy a wide range of taxes based on where the item is 
purchased. Taxing an out-of-state purchaser adds a new and vexing 
level of complexity. 
</P>
<P>
	Some group members, including the commission's chairman, Gov.  
James Gilmore of Virginia, are not convinced that an Internet tax 
is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say the commission is not in agreement on that,''  
Gilmore said in a telephone interview before the start of the 
two-day gathering. 
</P>
<P>
	He termed the poll results ``constructive,'' and pointed to them  
as evidence of the need for further study. He said the commission 
may not end up reaching the two-thirds consensus needed to make a 
unified policy recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the groundswell for Internet taxation is powerful. State  
and local governments are worried about losing billions of dollars 
in sales taxes as the Internet takes off. And retailers that sell 
most of their products in stores, so-called ``brick-and-mortar'' 
businesses, contend that Internet taxes level the playing field. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the government's job to make sure all levels of retailing  
are taxed equally,'' said Malachy Kavanagh, a spokesman for the 
International Council of Shopping Centers, a trade group of 38,000 
shopping center owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallup and (at)plan conducted the telephone survey of 1,000  
randomly chosen frequent Internet users in the United States 
between Aug. 26 and Aug. 31. The poll has a margin of error of plus 
or minus 3 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	During its 2-day meeting that started Tuesday, the commission  
plans to hear presentations from businesses and others, but won't 
make any decisions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
