<HEADLINE> Ruth Leads All-Century Outfield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Babe Ruth moved ahead off Hank Aaron for the  
first time in the latest results of the baseball's All-Century team 
voting released on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruth, whose record of 714 career home runs are second to Aaron's  
755, leads the voting in the outfield by 838 votes over Aaron. Ruth 
has 1,108,286 votes to Aaron's 1,107,448 in the closest race on the 
ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	Ted Williams is third with 1,077,862, followed by Willie Mays,  
who has 1,068,473. 
</P>
<P>
	Pete Rose, baseball's career hits leader, but who is on the  
sport's permanently disqualified list because of gambling, is ninth 
with 602,240. 
</P>
<P>
	In balloting sponsored by MasterCard that ends Sept. 19, fans  
vote for two players at each infield position, two catchers, six 
pitchers and nine outfielders. 
</P>
<P>
	Other leaders are catcher Johnny Bench (966,713), first baseman  
Lou Gehrig (1,156,278), second baseman Jackie Robinson (754,795), 
shortstop Cal Ripken Jr., (640,995), third baseman Mike Schmidt 
(818,792) and pitchers Nolan Ryan (949,600) and Sandy Koufax 
(929,066). 
  	   	
</P>
