<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 15:40:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pioneer Flour Changes With Times </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) -- Carl Hilmar Guenther aimed to serve  
his own little community when he founded Pioneer Flour Mills next 
to the San Antonio River in the 1850s. 
</P>
<P>
	Today his descendants are doing that and much more.  
</P>
<P>
	Pioneer Flour Mills, which recently resurrected its corporate  
name, C.H. Guenther &AMP; Son Inc., touts itself as the oldest 
continually owned family flour-milling operation in the country, 
and it still makes the basic grain products it has turned out for 
generations. 
</P>
<P>
	But the privately held company has also become a major producer  
of biscuit and gravy mixes, and fills niches in other modern-day 
food markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``In order to stay in business 150 years, you must be  
competitive,'' said Rich DeGregorio, president and chief executive 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The producer of Pioneer brand wheat and corn flour, the company  
also makes White Lily, a soft, white flour popular in food stores 
in the South and sold nationally through the catalog of the upscale 
Williams-Sonoma kitchen stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Guenther &AMP; Son acquired White Lily, based in Knoxville, Tenn.,  
about five years ago. The company also operates Pioneer Frozen 
Foods in Duncanville, acquired in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Its San Antonio plant is just south of downtown and can be  
recognized by its old, tall white grain elevator, a landmark in the 
historic King William district. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, the company employs about 800 workers.  
</P>
<P>
	Although professional managers like DeGregorio have been hired  
from other food companies, Guenther &AMP; Son considers itself a family 
business. Dozens of Guenther's descendants remain shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	It has gained a national reputation in the food-service industry  
as a supplier to restaurant chains and is one of the nation's 
largest white gravy producers, DeGregorio said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sold dry in ready-to-make packets, Pioneer gravies include  
biscuit, country, old-fashioned turkey, chicken, brown and assorted 
no-fat varieties. Cajun brown, roasted garlic and jalapeno gravies 
were introduced this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Pioneer produces biscuit, cornbread, pancake, waffle and  
tortilla mixes, frozen dough, and chili and taco seasoning. It also 
sells flour tortilla dough balls. 
</P>
<P>
	In the company's massive warehouse, pallets are stacked high  
with packaged foods ready for shipment to well-known restaurants 
and groceries. For proprietary reasons, DeGregorio wouldn't allow 
the clients to be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	In a typical year, Guenther &AMP; Son processes nearly 3 million  
bushels of wheat and corn, DeGregorio said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a lot of grain. That's a lot of rail cars,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	And that's a long way from the simple mill Guenther established  
in 1851, first in Fredericksburg next to Live Oak Creek, then at 
the San Antonio River site in 1859. 
</P>
<P>
	Carl Hilmar Guenther was part of an established family in  
Germany but apparently sought the thrill of making it on his own in 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guy was an adventurer, just to leave a family situation  
when they were already successful,'' DeGregorio said. ``In many 
ways, quite the American story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guenther oversaw the mill himself until 1902 before passing it  
down to a son. 
</P>
<P>
	These days the company takes pride in its ability to adapt in  
the constantly changing food marketplace, DeGregorio said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not the gorilla,'' he said. ``But we know how to fit  
into the niches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company knows how to highlight its history, too.  
</P>
<P>
	A picturesque, limestone house that Guenther built next to the  
San Antonio plant in 1860 was restored in the late 1980s and opened 
to the public as a restaurant, store and museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Guenther family photos and memorabilia are on display along with  
a collection of Dresden china anniversary plates that the mill 
commissioned each year and gave to grocer customers until 
production of the German dishes ended during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	An average of 150 to 200 people per day visit the Guenther House  
during the peak spring and fall seasons, said director Donna 
Vaughan. 
</P>
<P>
	Not coincidentally, the indoor-outdoor restaurant features the  
types of food produced by the Pioneer plant, offering such 
breakfast items as biscuits and gravy and southern sweet cream 
waffles. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no other waffle like our waffle. It's wonderful and  
addicting,'' Ms. Vaughan said. 
</P>
<P>
	To keep customers loyal to Pioneer products, the company prides  
itself on its quality assurance program, which relies in part on 
strict laboratory and kitchen testing as well as taste testing, 
DeGregorio said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We trade on that and live on that,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	As C.H. Guenther &AMP; Son approaches its sesquicentennial,  
DeGregorio believes the company is well-positioned for the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in a very competitive situation today,'' he said. ``We  
can perpetuate our business for quite a few years to come.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
