<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A drop in shares of financial services and banks,  
prompted by concern that the European Central Bank might tighten 
interest rates to strengthen the euro, caused European stocks to 
close lower overall Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro fell to $1.0298, its weakest since July 20, and hit a  
record low of 109.75 against the Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies  
fell 2.14 points, or 0.7 percent, to close at 314.68. The Dow Jones 
Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies in countries that 
joined the single currency, closed down 2.15 points, at 331.95. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index fell 29.08 points to 3,858.01,  
while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed down 45.71 points at 3,741.96. 
</P>
<P>
	In domestic markets, Germany's Xetra DAX index closed with a  
loss of 0.7 percent to 5,446.91 but dealers said the decrease -- 
sparked by the euro's marked slump against the dollar -- was 
contained by an options expiry coming up Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	SAP shares closed with a gain of 3.91 euros to 446.01 euros  
after the company announced it would launch an Internet-based 
product that should account for a significant chunk of its business 
in years to come. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, the FTSE 100 index closed down 0.4 percent, to  
6,169.0. News that Vodafone and Bell Atlantic are in talks, 
however, caused shares of Vodafone AirTouch to climb 60 pence to 
1,253 pence. 
</P>
<P>
	The Paris CAC-40 index fell 0.6 percent to 4,716.78, Amsterdam's  
AEX index fell 0.7 percent to 587.59, and Milan's MIBtel index 
closed with a loss of 0.4 percent to 34,546. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
