<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> States Rewarded As Unwed Births Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In most of the country, the proportion of  
babies born to unwed parents continues to rise, but 12 states have 
cut these rates. And the federal government has rewarded the top 
four and the District of Columbia with $20 million each in extra 
welfare money. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1996, when Congress offered $100 million to the states  
that did the best job reducing births to unwed parents, states have 
been devising programs to so, mostly aimed at teens. 
</P>
<P>
	The first set of winners are California, Michigan, Alabama,  
Massachusetts and the district, which recorded the largest drops in 
out-of-wedlock births without increasing the number of abortions, 
the Department of Health and Human Services said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationally, about one in three babies is born to unwed parents,  
a rate that didn't change between 1994-95 and 1996-97. 
</P>
<P>
	The competition, little noticed as Congress was enacting its  
far-reaching welfare law, includes all births outside marriage -- 
intended and unintended, to teens and adults, to families on and 
off welfare. 
</P>
<P>
	California led the nation, with its rate falling 5.7 percent. It  
was followed by the District of Columbia, which dropped 3.7 
percent; Michigan, 3.4 percent; Alabama, 2 percent; and 
Massachusetts, 1.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The winners are a diverse group, geographically, culturally and  
otherwise, and no one is sure how to explain their success. 
Moreover, while all their rates declined, the district has the 
nation's highest out-of-wedlock birth rate; Massachusetts has one 
of the lowest. 
</P>
<P>
	In its first year, the contest was based on data from 1996-97 --  
too early for programs passed in the wake of welfare reform to have 
had an impact. 
</P>
<P>
	``More evidence is needed to fully understand the range of  
factors contributing to the decrease ... in these particular 
states,'' the department said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The one-time windfall, which will be awarded to the top five  
states each year, must be spent on aid to the poor; it cannot be 
used for schools, roads or tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama officials have been talking about the bonus as they  
consider how to use $30 million in unspent regular welfare money, 
said Joel Sanders, who runs the state's welfare reform program. 
</P>
<P>
	Getting the extra money, he said, makes it easier for officials  
to consider raising spending, knowing that they have a deeper 
cushion. They are considering, for instance, raising their monthly 
welfare benefit; Alabama now pays just $164 for a family of three, 
the lowest in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sanders said the state is also considering expanding  
Alabama's teen pregnancy prevention program, which now gets less 
than $1 million per year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got the bonus because of that rate coming down, and we  
would like to see it keep coming down,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Massachusetts and Michigan officials said they had no idea  
how they would use the money. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationally, out-of-wedlock birth rates range from 16 percent in  
Utah to 45 percent in Mississippi. Cities generally have higher 
rates, and in Washington, D.C., it is 65 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Teens account for only one in three unwed births, though most  
state programs focus on them since teen moms are at high risk of 
joining the welfare rolls and dropping out of school. Advocates 
hope the winners use their bonus money to boost these programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will quickly be sending them all a big packet saying,  
`Please use this money to reinvest in teen pregnancy prevention,''' 
said Tamara Kreinin of the National Campaign to Prevent Teen 
Pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
	The winners have a variety of explanations for their success,  
including strong welfare reform programs, increased access to birth 
control and declining acceptance of out-of-wedlock pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
	But most of the programs instituted after the 1996 law did not  
have enough time to affect the first year's bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	The district may have benefited from demographics. The rate of  
unwed births among black women has been dropping across the 
country, and the district's population is overwhelmingly black. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationally, the unwed birth rate peaked in 1994 at 32.6 percent  
and has been relatively stable since then, after climbing 
dramatically through the late 1980s and early 1990s. In 1985, it 
was just 22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	To reduce the out-of-wedlock rate, the number of illegitimate  
births must fall more quickly than births to married women. That is 
tricky, given that all births -- including marital births -- are 
dropping across the country. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
