<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Embraces Hispanic Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore bounded on stage  
Tuesday to the hot-salsa sounds of Ricky Martin while aides passed 
around a 15-page list of 521 Latino activists endorsing Gore's 
presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lo acepto,'' Gore grinned. I accept.  
</P>
<P>
	The pep rally was staged as a formal launch to Gore's effort to  
build a groundswell of support in the exploding Hispanic community. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president made the most of his Spanish as he embraced  
supporters beneath the banner, ``Ganamos con Gore'' -- We win with 
Gore -- at the same Capitol Hill hotel where the Congressional 
Hispanic Caucus Institute was holding its annual convention. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic presidential candidate talked of a ``kinship''  
with Latinos. ``We have had successes together, we have had the 
same enemies,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing the community's disproportionately high school dropout  
rates and problems getting health care, Gore repeated the refrain, 
``I'm not satisfied. Nuestras familias merecen lo mejor. (Our 
families deserve better.)'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign aides boasted ``over 700'' Latino elected officials and  
other prominent community leaders on Gore's endorsement list but a 
precise counting tallied 521. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday night, Gore joined former ``NYPD Blue'' actor Jimmy Smits  
and the National Hispanic Foundation for the Arts to deplore the 
lack of diversity in mainstream movie and TV roles. On Wednesday, 
he addresses the caucus' gala dinner and on Thursday, he speaks to 
the Latino Chamber of Commerce in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic officials confirmed that, with Gore's input, Hispanic  
activist Lydia Camarillo, executive director of the Southwest Voter 
Registration Education Project, was a top contender to oversee next 
summer's Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles and could be 
announced as such this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's Republican rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, has also  
fiercely courted Latinos. 
</P>
<P>
	New census data released Tuesday showed the Hispanic population  
grew by more than 35 percent to about 30.3 million between 1990 and 
1998, increasing their share of the total population from 9 percent 
to 11 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	With a riff on pop star Martin's hit single, Gore supporters on  
Tuesday ridiculed any inroads Bush has made with the Hispanic 
community. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's all this talk about George W. Bush and the Latino  
community? I mean they talk about this guy like he's Ricky Martin 
or something,'' said California Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anybody thinks that George W. Bush is good for Latinos,  
they ARE living 'La Vida Loca' (The Crazy Life).'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Bustamante's endorsement of Gore sounded a bit  
backhanded: ``Many months ago I decided -- maybe it wasn't the smart 
political thing to do but I think it was the right thing to do -- to 
support Al Gore for president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president slammed Bush's education proposals, which he  
said could shift public funds from public schools to private 
schools with selective admissions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Strangest education platform I've ever seen because they're  
claiming they can add by subtracting and dividing,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	In his campaign for the GOP nomination, Bush has proposed  
stripping federal funds from the worst-performing schools and 
making the money available to parents for private schools or other 
education alternatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's lone rival for the  
Democratic presidential nomination, is also competing for minority 
voters in next year's primaries. And on Monday, the Bradley camp 
announced endorsements from a host of Brooklyn political leaders, 
including several influential members of the New York borough's 
black community. 
</P>
<P>
	At Gore's rally, New Jersey Rep. Robert Menendez introduced Gore  
by taking a poke at Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	``I judge people in the political context. I come from New  
Jersey. There's another candidate from that state you might be 
aware of,'' Menendez said to hisses from some in the small hotel 
ballroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Menendez hastened to add that Bradley is ``a great guy, but the  
vice president is willing to put his prestige and his political 
capital on the line.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
