<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 14:51:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orange Juice Futures Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	With all eyes on Hurricane Floyd stalking the southeastern U.S.  
coastline, orange juice futures were buffeted around in a volatile 
day of trading Tuesday before slipping lower on the New York 
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, crude oil futures fell after six straight  
gains and cocoa rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors appeared as edgy as Florida residents, sending orange  
juice futures rocketing to almost $1 a pound early in the trading 
session on fears the storm will severely damage groves in the 
Sunshine State. 
</P>
<P>
	Packing a top sustained wind of 140 mph, Floyd potentially poses  
the greatest threat to Florida and its orange groves since much 
smaller Hurricane Andrew slammed into South Florida in 1992, 
causing $25 billion in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	With the latest forecasts calling for the hurricane to strike  
land in Georgia or the Carolinas, sparing the bulk of Florida's 
citrus crop, the market pulled back later Tuesday. Orange juice 
futures finished down 45 cents for the day at 96.55 cents a gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	But concerns lingered that high winds would have an impact on  
orange juice groves, likely knocking fruit off trees in eastern 
portions of the key producing region Tuesday night and Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never know with hurricanes,'' said Elizabeth Steger,  
president of Citrus Consulting International in Orlando. ``We've 
had hurricanes without damage and hurricanes with damage. We'll 
just have to wait and see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She noted, however, that with the start of the harvest still  
some three months away, the small size of the oranges now on trees 
makes it less vulnerable to damage. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, crude oil futures dropped in cautious trading  
ahead of a report on U.S. crude inventories by the American 
Petroleum Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were anticipating another slight decline in  
inventories, which have fallen 9 percent since the Organization of 
Petroleum Exporting Countries committed to increased production 
cuts last spring. 
</P>
<P>
	API reported after the close of the market that U.S. crude oil  
stocks fell 1.297 million barrels in the week ended Sept. 10, on 
the low side of analysts' expectations. U.S. gasoline stocks fell a 
less-than-expected 578,000 barrels. 
</P>
<P>
	October crude fell 35 cents to $23.86 a gallon; October heating  
oil fell 1.14 cents to 61.06 cents a gallon; October unleaded 
regular gasoline fell 1.26 cents to 68.42 cents a gallon; October 
natural gas fell 14.5 cents to $2.636 cents per 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent crude oil for delivery in October  
rose 23 cents to $23.71 a barrel on the International Petroleum 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures pushed up nearly 4 percent on concerns over crops,  
the military conflict in Indonesia and the uncertainties of 
liberalization in the Ivory Coast and Ghana. 
</P>
<P>
	The cocoa harvest is beginning in West Africa, and while the  
weather has been favorable the political climate is cloudy. 
</P>
<P>
	The conflict in Indonesia, the world's No. 3 cocoa producer, has  
stirred worries over its impact on movement of the product in that 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia's currency continues to be vulnerable to the unrest. A  
United Nations peacekeeping force is headed to troubled East Timor 
this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Growers and exporters in Ivory Coast are struggling to adapt to  
changes associated with political liberalization, and the overall 
effect is unknown. 
</P>
<P>
	December cocoa rose $33 to $974 per ton on the Coffee, Sugar &AMP;  
Cocoa Exchange division of the New York Board of Trade. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
