<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Fails on HMO Patient Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republican leaders failed Tuesday to  
produce a strategy on patient protection legislation, leaving the 
GOP struggling on the politically popular issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Members had hoped to emerge from a closed meeting united behind  
legislation aimed at giving patients new rights in dealing with 
restrictive health maintenance organizations and other managed-care 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	As they came out, however, participants made clear that deep  
disagreements over whether injured patients should get new rights 
to file lawsuits prevented any agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Republican House leaders prefer only limited new HMO  
regulations, with no new right to sue. They fear a proliferation of 
lawsuits that would drive up the cost of insurance and prompt 
employers to drop coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to keep his fractured party together, House Speaker  
Dennis Hastert promised last month to bring a bill to the floor 
written by Reps. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., and John Shadegg, R-Ariz., 
that would include a right-to-sue provision. When they introduced 
it last week, it did. 
</P>
<P>
	Since promising a vote, the speaker has been distancing himself  
from their effort, refusing to endorse the bill or even say what he 
thinks of it. Coburn and Shadegg said last week they expected an 
endorsement after they had met with him. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting, Tuesday in Hastert's Capitol office, adjourned  
without any such endorsement. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert, R-Ill., kept his public silence. Asked if he would talk  
to reporters about the issue, he said from a distance, ``Not right 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House GOP leaders are in a tough spot. Twenty Republicans have  
joined with Democrats in the House to back a sweeping bill, giving 
it more than enough support to pass on the floor if Democrats stick 
together, as expected. 
</P>
<P>
	It's unclear what alternatives Republicans have to the  
Coburn-Shadegg legislation. While GOP leaders like it better than 
the Democratic bill, they don't like it much. 
</P>
<P>
	``I described it as the least worst way to do the wrong thing,''  
Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas., said after Tuesday's meeting. 
Coburn recalled that Armey also described the legislation as ``like 
driving over a skunk and putting it in your trunk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Coburn and Shadegg said they will not back down on the right  
to sue, known as the liability provision. 
</P>
<P>
	``They can stick their head in the sand, but the fact is,  
whatever passes the House is going to have some type of 
liability,'' Coburn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Their bill would allow lawsuits, but only in federal court and  
only after a patient goes through the health plan's review process. 
Patients also would have to take their cases to more doctors for 
assessment of injuries and a determination whether a decision by 
the plan had caused the injury. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would cap damages patients could collect and  
contains a variety of provisions that virtually every other HMO 
bill has: allowing easier access to emergency rooms and specialists 
and giving patients access to more information about how plans 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	Coburn and Shadegg said they will continue to build support  
among colleagues for their legislation. Meanwhile, Republican Whip 
Tom DeLay, R-Texas, planned to determine how much support exists 
among Republicans for new rights to sue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
