<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Games Confident for Sponsors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The Sydney Olympics will meet its reduced goal for  
raising money through sponsorship, the head of the organizing 
committee said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Though an outside marketing company was hired to help attract  
new sponsors, the organizers still are on course to meet their 
target, according to SOCOG president Michael Knight. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight said his committee had raised $515 million through  
sponsorships, and was ``still chasing'' another $90 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that we will reach our targets with the sales of  
assets such as corporate boxes,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight made his comments on the eve of the official  
``one-year-to-go'' date for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG cut its sponsorship target by $32 million after the Salt  
Lake City bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Though it recently reorganized its revenue-raising operations to  
help meet the new target, Knight said he was confident there won't 
be a shortfall. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have turned the corner,'' after the Salt Lake City scandal,  
Knight said. ``The fact that ticket sales have been such a success 
has excited sponsors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Transportation, though, remains a problem.  
</P>
<P>
	Sydney's rail network will work around the clock to handle the  
estimated 500,000 spectators and workers who will travel to the 
main Olympic site on the busiest days. 
</P>
<P>
	``Transport is probably the biggest concern, and after Atlanta,  
technology must always be a concern too,'' Knight said. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting when Sydney won the 2000 Olympics six years ago  
organizers knew that smooth running at the games hinged on an 
effective transportation network. 
</P>
<P>
	It concern was magnified by problems at Atlanta in 1996 where a  
complicated hub transport system meant athletes and officials 
feared they would miss events and bus drivers often became lost 
because they were unfamiliar with the city's roads. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to head off similar problems, the Olympic Roads and  
Transport Authority (ORTA) was established in March 1997 to 
coordinate all elements of moving people around during the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Athletes and officials will mostly use ferries on the Parramatta  
River, in addition to dedicated Olympic traffic lanes in the city 
and Victoria Road, one of the main routes to travel the 12 miles 
from the central business district in Sydney to Homebush Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Olympic Park railway station, designed to cope with  
50,000 passengers an hour, was opened last year and has 
successfully coped with several tests of its capabilities. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
