<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 07:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golden Spikes Finalists Picked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Detroit Tigers catcher Eric Munson and  
Colorado right-hander Jason Jennings, both first-round picks in 
June's amateur draft, were among five finalists picked Monday for 
the Golden Spikes award. 
</P>
<P>
	Marshall McDougall, who had an NCAA-record six homers and 16  
RBIs in one game for Florida State, also was picked, as was first 
baseman Ken Harvey, who led the NCAA with a .478 batting average 
for Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortstop Bobby Hill, who played for Miami's NCAA championship  
team, also was a finalist. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill was drafted by the Chicago White Sox in the second round,  
while McDougall was selected by Boston in the 26th round, but 
neither player has signed. Harvey was taken by Kansas City in the 
fifth round. 
</P>
<P>
	The Golden Spikes award is given annually to the nation's top  
amateur player by the U.S. Baseball Federation. The winner will be 
announced Nov. 3 at Las Vegas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
