<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `MNF' Ratings Jump for 9 p.m. Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The ``Monday Night Football'' experiment is over  
and so are the plummeting television ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC posted a 16.1 national rating and a 27 share Monday night in  
the first regular season game since the network returned ``MNF'' to 
a 9 p.m. ET start. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season was the first time in its 29-year history that the  
program began at 8 p.m. and ``MNF'' finished with a 13.9 rating, 
lowest in its history. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami's 38-21 victory over Denver Monday night increased 9  
percent from last season's opener between New England and Denver. 
It was also up 7 percent from the first game in 1997, a 15.0 
between Chicago and Green Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very encouraged that our move back to 9 p.m. is going to  
work in our favor,'' ABC spokesman Mark Mandel said. ``We are 
pleased by the results, especially given the fact it was a lopsided 
game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ABC made the time change prior to last season hoping that  
ratings would increase with an earlier kickoff on the East Coast. 
However, the amount of viewers on the West Coast dropped 
dramatically and the network decided to revert back to the 
traditional time slot. 
</P>
<P>
	All eight of the metered markets on the West Coast increased on  
Monday from last season. Seattle, Sacramento, Portland and San 
Francisco all registered more than 20 percent jumps while Los 
Angeles was up 12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's game peaked between 10-10:30 p.m. with a 17.6/27, when  
the Broncos retired John Elway's number. 
</P>
<P>
	The rating is the percentage of television households tuned to a  
broadcast, and each point represents 994,000 homes. The share is 
the percentage watching a program among those televisions in use at 
the time. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
