<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jets Off To Painful Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- Vinny Testaverde knew it right away. As  
he pounded the Giants Stadium turf in frustration, Testaverde 
understood that his 1999 season was over. Quite likely, so were the 
New York Jets' Super Bowl aspirations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had the running play and Curtis Martin got the handoff  
clean, and when he was hit, he fumbled,'' Testaverde said Monday as 
he sat on a podium with his left leg bandaged almost up to the knee 
following surgery. ``I saw the ball on the ground, pushed off to go 
get it and thought I heard somebody falling behind me. I thought 
somebody fell and hit my ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	``My last thought was my Achilles' popped and I am out for the  
season. We put so much into preparing for this season and finally 
have everything in position to go and things are looking good. It 
is a big disappointment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of many disappointments the Jets have sustained just one  
week into what they believed would be a championship season. While 
they are not abandoning hope, they fully realize how much injuries 
can change things. 
</P>
<P>
	Already they have surpassed last year's total of 29 man-games  
lost to injury in a 12-4 season that ended in an AFC title game 
loss at Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	Star receiver Wayne Chrebet is out for another five weeks with a  
broken foot. Starting cornerback Otis Smith (collarbone), hurt in 
training camp, isn't expected back for a few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, in addition to Testaverde, the Jets lost running  
back-kick returner Leon Johnson for the year with torn knee 
ligaments. Jason Ferguson has a knee and ankle injury that coach 
Bill Parcells expects to sideline the starting nose tackle for this 
week's game at Buffalo. Tight end Eric Green pinched a nerve in his 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	Testaverde, whose rehabilitation should take six months, isn't  
losing faith. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no question they can win; no one player has that much  
of an impact on a team,'' he said. ``If there was any one player 
who had that much impact, you would see guys like Dan Marino and 
John Elway winning Super Bowl after Super Bowl. It just doesn't 
happen that way. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team has expectations because of the team effort we put  
forth. People who are talking about the Jets to be a Super Bowl 
contender, right now it is without me and Leon and Wayne. They are 
going to have to get it done, and I know they will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells, who added several veterans this year with the idea of  
taking the extra step the Jets couldn't manage in 1998, echoed his 
quarterback's comments. 
</P>
<P>
	``You are certainly disappointed, but you just have to move  
forward and try to do what you can do,'' Parcells said. ``Right now 
this is a pretty difficult set of circumstances for us. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if anybody is in this boat yet, but in the last  
eight days we potentially lost four starters and, in Leon, a guy 
who is highly productive offensively. We have lost quite a bit of 
firepower there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most notably Testaverde, of course. After 11 seasons with  
generally mediocre teams in which he was asked to be the focal 
point, Testaverde prospered for the Jets when he no longer was 
forced to carry such a burden. If his 12th season was a coming-out 
party, his 13th could have been a coronation. 
</P>
<P>
	``With all that happened (last year), there are people who  
thought it was a fluke,'' he said. ``I don't think last year was a 
fluke by any stretch. All the things I have been through in my life 
I have gotten through because I have perseverance. I need to stay 
mentally strong, to stay focused and get through this.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
