<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Expresses Union Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley,  
campaigning in the heart of union country, said Tuesday that 
workers fired for union organizing should get triple their back 
wages and punitive damages. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're really interested in working families, you have to  
make it easier to organize,'' Bradley told about 50 union members. 
``Working families are better if we have labor unions that are 
vibrant and growing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said workers now get only back wages if they prove they  
were fired for union organizing. He proposed changing that so they 
could get triple their back wages as well as punitive damages. 
</P>
<P>
	The former New Jersey senator said he doesn't expect to win many  
union endorsements, in part because he supports the North American 
Free Trade Agreement, as does his Democratic presidential rival, 
Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said he hopes unions will stay neutral in the Democratic  
race. 
</P>
<P>
	That appears unlikely, especially since AFL-CIO President John  
J. Sweeney accompanied Gore to Detroit and Iowa over the Labor Day 
weekend. The AFL-CIO is expected at its October meeting to throw 
the weight of its 13 million members behind the vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore was out courting labor support in Tennessee on Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Printing company owner Roger Robinson of Grosse Pointe Park,  
Mich., said Bradley is making inroads with labor with his 
willingness to consider the unions' contention that free trade 
means lost jobs for U.S. workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The broad array of trade issues will determine how I behave in  
the contest for president,'' Robinson said. ``That's the bellwether 
issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several union members said they are willing to listen to Bradley  
because he has spoken out against allowing Mexican trucks that 
don't meet U.S. health and safety standards to cross the border. 
</P>
<P>
	``From the Teamsters standpoint, we've appreciated a few of the  
stances he's taken that Mr. Gore has not taken a position on yet,'' 
said Mark Gaffney, legislative and community affairs director for 
Michigan Teamsters Joint Council 43. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaffney, a candidate to replace outgoing Michigan AFL-CIO  
President Frank Garrison, said it's too early to say who will get 
his union's endorsement. 
</P>
<P>
	But he agreed with Robinson that trade issues will play a large  
part in the Democratic primary. ``We're hurt by trade that's more 
free than fair,'' Gaffney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan Democrats will choose their presidential candidate in  
party caucuses on March 11, 2000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 14:10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Devil Rays Extend Rothschild Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- The Tampa Bay Devil Rays like the  
direction they're heading under Larry Rothschild and on Tuesday 
gave the manager a one-year contract extension through 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Rothschild signed a three-year agreement on Nov. 7, 1997 and led  
the expansion club to 63 victories in its inaugural season. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we hired Larry Rothschild ... we expected him to lead us  
through not only the developmental stages of our organization, but 
through the championship years as well,'' general manager Chuck 
LaMar said. ``In our first two years, he has demonstrated the 
skills that are necessary to take us to the championship level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With 62 victories going into Tuesday night's game against the  
Seattle Mariners, the Devil Rays were one shy of equaling last 
year's total. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's record represented a six-game improvement over a year  
ago at the same time, the fourth-best improvement in the AL. 
</P>
<P>
	In Rothschild's first season, the Devil Rays finished second in  
the league in fielding percentage and fourth in ERA. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
