<DOCNO> APW19990914.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 23:40:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Floyd Juggles Sporting Calendar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The Miami Dolphins had to take a bus the final 2 1/2  
hours on their return trip from Denver. Savannah State football 
began its road trip three days early, only to run into problems. 
And The Citadel called off its football trip to stay home. 
</P>
<P>
	Without coming ashore yet, Hurricane Floyd already was wreaking  
havoc on sports schedules along the entire Florida coast. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tricky,'' said University of Miami quarterback Kenny  
Kelly, who endured a 7:30 a.m. practice Tuesday, one day after 
being called in for an unscheduled workout. ``You never know what 
tomorrow's schedule is going to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Late Tuesday, Floyd was centered 170 miles southeast of Cape  
Canaveral, Fla., its winds stretching some 600 miles across. Its 
top sustained winds of 140 mph were down slightly, but still a 
Category 4 storm, the second-most powerful designation for a 
hurricane. 
</P>
<P>
	No major events were scrubbed, though the massive storm claimed  
a Florida-Carolina NHL exhibition and the deciding Game 5 of 
baseball's Class-A Carolina League championship series. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather, it was travel and practice schedules that took the  
biggest hit as Floyd buzzed its way up the Atlantic coast. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dolphins, flying home from Monday night's 38-21 win over the  
two-time Super Bowl champions, were forced to land at Fort Myers on 
Florida's west coast. They then boarded buses to travel the final 
120 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jimmy Johnson canceled his weekly day-after-game press  
briefing, and team officials postponed ceremonies opening a new NFL 
youth center in Fort Lauderdale. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the Dolphins nor the Jacksonville Jaguars were forced to  
cancel practice, since Tuesday is a day off for most NFL teams. But 
the Jaguars had to call off today's workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this time, our plan is to resume our normal work schedule  
on Thursday morning,'' coach Tom Coughlin said. ``Our first concern 
is clearly the safety and well-being of the families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was that kind of concern that led The Citadel to postpone its  
game Saturday at Western Carolina. Having lived through Hurricane 
Hugo 10 years ago, athletic director Walt Nadzak said the road trip 
should be the last thing on players' minds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our kids have families, our coaches have wives and children,''  
Nadzak said. ``We want them to be with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Georgia, Savannah State's football team left Tuesday on its  
370-mile trip to face Tennessee-Chattanooga on Saturday. Though one 
of their buses broke down east of Atlanta, the Tigers still planned 
to conduct their final three practices in Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	At Division I-AA power Georgia Southern, about 60 miles inland,  
players planned to gather in Kennedy Hall, a 2-year-old brick 
structure and one of the sturdiest buildings on campus. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the thoughts was going to Atlanta, but trying to find  
rooms for 65 kids proved to be impossible,'' sports information 
director Tom McClellan said. 
</P>
<P>
	In baseball, both the Carolina and Southern leagues saw their  
championship series affected by Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	The Double-A Southern League series between Orlando and West  
Tennessee was kept in Jackson, Tenn., for today's Game 3 before 
shifting to Orlando for the final two contests. 
</P>
<P>
	The Class-A Carolina League took even quicker action. Rather  
than play the deciding game of its title series, it declared 
Wilmington and Myrtle Beach co-champions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sports pales to other issues that are at hand, even a  
championship,'' Myrtle Beach general manager Steve Malliet said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even NASCAR and the NBA couldn't avoid Floyd. NASCAR was forced  
to close its offices amid the evacuation of Daytona Beach, Fla., 
sending many staffers to Charlotte, N.C., for the week. In Orlando, 
the NBA postponed today's grand-opening celebration of its first 
theme restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	And in an odd twist, Floyd's approach prompted a mistrial in the  
lawsuit against Charlotte Hornets owner George Shinn by a woman who 
said he sexually assaulted her at his home. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
