<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Herbalife To Take Company Private </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Herbalife International Inc. shares rose 60  
percent after the chief executive of the dietary supplement company 
said he would buy outstanding shares he doesn't already own for 
$500 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Herbalife rose $5.53 1/8 Tuesday to close at $14.68 3/4, a  
52-week high, on the Nasdaq stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief executive Mark Hughes announced on Monday that he would  
buy the stock, citing the poor performance of Herbalife shares in 
recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock closed at $9.15 5/8 on Monday before Hughes'  
announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, worth $17 per share, will give Hughes 100 percent  
ownership and control of the Los Angeles-based company, which sells 
weight-management, personal-care and nutritional products. 
</P>
<P>
	``Herbalife has not been rewarded in the public equity markets  
and the conditions which may have contributed to this are not 
likely to change in the near term,'' Hughes said in a letter to 
investors that was posted on the company's Internet site. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a private company, without the distractions of day-to-day  
and quarter-to-quarter fluctuations in our share price, I will have 
more flexibility in making decisions to bring Herbalife where we 
want to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Herbalife sales have declined in key international markets,  
including Russia and Brazil and the share price has dipped as low 
as $6 earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, the company posted earnings of $48.5 million on sales  
of $867 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In his letter, Hughes said his buyback plan had the backing of  
Herbalife's board of directors and senior management. The buyback 
will be financed in part through $214 million in loans, he said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
