<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sam Donaldson To Host Web News Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Television news' latest convert to the Internet  
is ABC's Sam Donaldson. 
</P>
<P>
	The veteran White House correspondent will be host of  
``SamDonaldson@ABCNEWS.com,'' a 15-minute news report that will air 
three times a week on the Internet only, the network said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	It's part of a restructuring of his duties that will include  
work as a national political reporter for ABC and occasional 
hour-long TV specials for the network. Donaldson is ending his 
second stint as White House correspondent and will no longer be 
host one night a week on ``20/20.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Cokie Roberts, Donaldson will continue as co-host of the  
Sunday morning show, ``This Week with Sam Donaldson and Cokie 
Roberts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Webcast will air Monday, Wednesday and Friday at 12:30 p.m.,  
starting Sept. 27. The general news broadcast, with an emphasis on 
Internet issues, is an experiment that could expand if there's 
enough interest, Donaldson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of smart people tell me the Internet is the future,''  
said Donaldson, 65. ``If there is, there's nothing like being on 
the ground floor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Donaldson was the odd man out when ABC's Barbara Walters decided  
she wanted to be a sole host of Friday's ``20/20'' edition 
following the retirement of Hugh Downs. Connie Chung and 
newly-hired Jack Ford will be hosts of ``20/20-Monday,'' and Diane 
Sawyer and Charles Gibson will anchor Wednesday's newsmagazine. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC also announced that Thursday's ``20/20'' will be renamed  
``20/20 Downtown,'' with Elizabeth Vargas, John Quinones, Jay 
Schadler and Cynthia McFadden as revolving hosts. The network 
describes it as an ``edgier'' broadcast with a greater emphasis on 
first-person narratives. 
</P>
<P>
	Donaldson, meanwhile, is on the mend from surgery to repair a  
nodule on one of his vocal cords. The owner of TV news' most 
insistent voices will know by December whether he's completely 
cured of hoarseness that has plagued him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Psychologically, it's been very bad,'' he said. ``If you cut  
off my right hand, I'll wear a glove ... But if you take my voice 
away, that's what I do for a living, that's my self-image.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 18:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Fuming About U.S.-Russia Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican lawmakers criticized the Clinton  
administration's support for aid to Russia, as investigators 
widened their inquiry into allegations that Russian gangsters 
laundered billions of dollars through a U.S. bank. 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, called the Clinton  
policy toward Russia ``the greatest U.S. foreign policy failure 
since Vietnam.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The unparalleled financial graft in Russia -- much of it  
apparently involving money from U.S. taxpayers -- marks the 
effective end of the Clinton-Gore administration's approach to 
Russian reform,'' Armey said Tuesday at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``The stated purpose of the Clinton-Gore policy was to help  
Russia become a peaceful and productive free-market democracy. 
Instead, Russia has become a looted and bankrupt zone of 
nuclearized anarchy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman David Leavy said Armey's remarks were  
irresponsible and ignored ``the events that have happened in Russia 
in the last 10 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has ``made important strides'' in promoting  
``Russia's transition toward a free-market democracy,'' Leavy said. 
He cited Russia's voluntary disabling of nuclear weapons and the 
rise of personal and press freedom and an independent judiciary. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has been put on the defensive by suspicions  
that International Monetary Fund loans and U.S. food aid to Russia 
may have been illegally diverted. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican criticism came as Russian investigators were in  
Washington to meet with State and Justice Department officials to 
discuss the money-laundering case and ways they can cooperate in 
their inquiries. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, as the IMF's biggest member, has delayed  
deciding whether it should approve new loans to Russia from the 
international lending agency until a full accounting is made of the 
money already lent. The 182-nation IMF has lent Russia some $22 
billion since 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore is coming under fire from Republicans for  
his close relationship with Russian leaders and his hands-on role 
in U.S.-Russian diplomacy, particularly as chairman of a joint 
commission on bilateral ties with former Russian Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of a congressional GOP strategy, Rep. Benjamin Gilman,  
R-N.Y., chairman of the House International Relations Committee, 
announced that he would hold a series of hearings on U.S. policy 
toward Russia, including the bilateral commission headed by Gore 
and Chernomyrdin. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration's support for Russia ``has apparently gone  
hand-in-hand with a willing disregard for the high-level corruption 
within the (Russian) government,'' Gilman said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Banking Committee plans hearings next week on the  
alleged money-laundering scheme involving as much as $10 billion at 
the Bank of New York, the 15th largest U.S. bank. The Senate 
Foreign Relations Committee also plans to hold hearings soon, with 
topics to include corruption in Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the House passed a measure, 419-0, aimed mainly at  
Russia that would impose sanctions on countries helping Iran 
develop nuclear, chemical or biological weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration said the president's senior advisers would  
recommend he veto the bill because it would ``have the effect of 
undermining multilateral support that is vital to effectively fight 
proliferation.'' President Clinton vetoed a similar bill last year. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990914.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 10:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mixed; Gold Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mixed against other major  
currencies in European trading today. Gold prices rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0382 in late European trading, up from  
$1.0351 Monday. Later, in midday trading in New York the euro 
traded at $1.0343. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday,  
included 106.33 Japanese yen, up from 106.25; 1.5444 Swiss francs, 
down from 1.5498; 1.4690 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4727. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6025, down from $1.6130.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 105.54 yen and  
the pound was worth $1.6042. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8839 German marks, down from 1.8895; 
6.3182 French francs, down from 6.3371; 2.1226 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.1290; 1,865.03 Italian lire, down from 1,870.61. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $256.90 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$256.20 on Monday. In Zurich, the bid price was $256.65, up from 
$255.85. Gold rose 10 cents in Hong Kong to close at $256.85. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.11 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$5.13. 
  	   	
</P>
