<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Finds Gore-Bradley Close in NH </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Bill Bradley is in a close race with Vice  
President Al Gore in the Democratic presidential contest in New 
Hampshire, while George W. Bush has kept a big lead over his 
Republican rivals, a new poll indicates. 
</P>
<P>
	A WMUR-CNN poll released Monday shows Gore is favored by 46  
percent of likely voters in the 2000 Democratic presidential 
primary, compared with 41 percent who support Bradley, a former 
senator from New Jersey. That difference was within the poll's 
margin of error of 5 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore had 50 percent to 39 percent for Bradley among registered  
Democrats. But among independents who said they were likely to vote 
in the Democratic primary, 44 percent supported Bradley to 42 
percent for Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley recently pointed to his appeal among independents as a  
major selling point for his candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine percent in the poll were undecided and 4 percent backed  
other candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone poll of 325 likely Democratic primary voters,  
conducted by the University of New Hampshire Survey Center from 
Sept. 5 to Sept. 11, showed the same competitive trend as polls 
released last week by the Boston Globe-WBZ-TV and WNDS-TV. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the WMUR-CNN poll found Gore was favored by 68 percent,  
while Bradley was the pick of only 23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's favorability rating is now lower than Bradley's, and  
Bradley's supporters were more strongly committed to their 
candidate, the poll found. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-three percent of Bradley supporters said they were certain  
to vote for him, compared to 34 percent of Gore supporters who said 
they were sure to vote for the vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	Among 377 Republicans, the poll found that Bush, governor of  
Texas, had 45 percent while former American Red Cross president 
Elizabeth Dole was at 15 percent, Arizona Sen. John McCain was at 
12 percent, and publisher Steve Forbes had the support of 10 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Other candidates trailed in the single digits: political  
commentator Pat Buchanan had 5 percent; former U.N. Ambassador Alan 
Keyes had 4 percent; former Vice President Dan Quayle drew 3 
percent; conservative activist Gary Bauer and Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch 
each had 1 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
