<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Beach Oasis Copes With Rockets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JALAMA BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Surfers relish the waves along this  
secluded beach and vacationers savor the miles of undeveloped 
coast. 
</P>
<P>
	There's only one major inconvenience: wayward rockets.  
</P>
<P>
	When neighboring Vandenberg Air Force Base launches its big  
Titan rockets, the campers and day visitors must leave, just in 
case there's trouble over what the military calls the ``impact 
limit zone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vandenberg, about 180 miles northwest of Los Angeles, is the  
launch site for payloads being placed in a polar orbit. 
</P>
<P>
	``About once a year, on average, we will have to ask Jalama to  
clear the beach for a launch for a Titan II or Titan IV,'' said 
Maj. John Cherry, a Vandenberg spokesman. ``We give plenty of 
notice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Liquid-fueled Titans ``move a little slower and stay over land a  
little longer'' so precautions are necessary, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	There's never been an accident, or ``catastrophic event,'' as  
the Air Force calls it, over the clearing of Jalama Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	The most recent evacuations were in May and June. The next  
beach-clearing launch is tentatively scheduled for Oct. 3, when an 
Air Force weather satellite will be hurled into space. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Kinney, a Santa Barbara County parks ranger, has lived at  
Jalama Beach for about 12 years and can only remember the beach 
being evacuated ``seven or nine times'' in that period. 
</P>
<P>
	``We work around the missile inconvenience,'' Kinney said.  
``People leave their tents and camping gear and go into town for 
dinner. There's usually a four-hour window.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camper Art Feldman, 60, of Monrovia, has been coming to Jalama  
Beach for 30 years, ``back when it was a secret spot'' unspoiled by 
the explosion of tourists and modern conveniences like hot water 
and flush toilets. 
</P>
<P>
	As for a possible wayward rocket, Feldman said: ``You have to  
worry about that, but the real thing you have to worry about is the 
hills are full of rattlesnakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kinney said campers and surfers have always been cooperative  
when it's necessary to evacuate, and he dismissed reports there was 
a seething beach war, adding that the military has been a good 
neighbor. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, one businessman is upset over the launches, which he says  
cost him money. ``Rents and utilities go on for me. Yes, I'm 
annoyed,'' said Don Eittreim, owner of Jalama's, a store and cafe. 
</P>
<P>
	``One launch in the 1980s was scrubbed 11 times and they  
evacuated the park every time. Then, on the 11th day, the thing 
blew up on the launch pad,'' Eittreim said. 
</P>
<P>
	``People got mad, having their vacations interrupted,'' he said.  
``People said, `Jeez, I'll never come back.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Eittreim has filed five claims totaling $2,888 for loss of  
business, all of them rejected by the military. 
</P>
<P>
	Cherry is sympathetic.  
</P>
<P>
	``One of the things that can get people frustrated is the change  
in launch days,'' he said. ``There's a myriad of things that can 
cause a 24-hour delay.... There's probably some frustration from 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Warning about the beach clearing begin about two weeks before a  
launch and signs are posted as far away as 14 miles from the beach, 
Kinney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheriff's deputies and rangers shoo people out of the park a few  
hours before launch and the 110 beach campsites are cleared. 
Military helicopters sweep the beaches and a Navy boat from Point 
Mugu scans the coast for boaters. 
</P>
<P>
	Some boat skippers balk, but the military has figured out a way  
to get them out of the area. 
</P>
<P>
	``They smile very politely and tell them that their boat  
registration number is being called into their insurance company,'' 
Cherry said. ``They leave very quickly.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
